<TITLE>The Publishing Mills Audiobooks - TALKING BACK TO PROZAC, Peter Breggin, M.D.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<FORM METHOD="post" ACTION="/cgi-shl/html_web_store.pl">
 
<img src="/pmhead2.gif" align=right>
<HR noshade>
 
<P>
<center>
<h1>TALKING BACK TO PROZAC<br>
<i></i></h1>
 
<table cellpadding=10 width=90%>
 
<tr valign=top>
 
<td align=center>
<img src="/10000038.gif">
 
<br><p>Nonfiction<br>
ISBN: 1-879371-82-0<br>
Abridged<br>2 tapes, 180 min.<br>
$16.95
 
</td><td>
 
 
<h3>By Peter Breggin, M.D.<br>
Read by Peter Breggin</h3>
<P>
<p>Prozac.  Six million Americans are on it.  And just about everyone else is wondering whether they should be
on it, too.  The claims of the pro-Prozac chorus are enticing: that it can cure everything from depression (the
only disorder for which Prozac was approved) to fear of public speaking, PMS, obesity, shyness, migraine
and back pain.  But is the reality quite different?  At what price do people buy Prozac-induced happiness and
a shiny new personality?

<p><b><I>Talking Back to Prozac</I></b> explains what Prozac is and how it works and takes a hard look at the real
story behind the drug. 


 
