<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Publishing Mills Audiobooks - WHY SHOULD WHITE GUYS HAVE ALL THE FUN?, Reginald F. Lewis</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<FORM METHOD="post" ACTION="/cgi-shl/html_web_store.pl">
 
<img src="/pmhead2.gif" align=right>
<HR noshade>
 
<P>
<center>
<h1>WHY SHOULD WHITE GUYS HAVE ALL THE FUN?<br>
<i>How Reginald Lewis Created a Billion-Dollar Empire</i></h1>
 
<table cellpadding=10 width=90%>
 
<tr valign=top>
 
<td align=center>
<img src="/10000012.gif">
 
<br><p>Business<br>
ISBN: 1-57511-004-0<br>
Abridged<br>2 tapes, 180 min.<br>
$16.95
 
</td><td>
 
 
<h3>By Reginald F. Lewis<br>
Read by Blair S. Walker</h3>
<P>
<p>During his lifetime, Reginald F. Lewis built a financial 
empire of such magnitude that at the time of his
untimely death, he was the wealthiest black man in history.

<p>Profiled by Forbes magazine as one of the four-hundred 
wealthiest businesspeople in America, Lewis reigned
over a commercial empire spanning four continents.  At the 
time of his death in 193, his pesonal fortune was
estimated by Forbes to be in excess of $400 million.  Having 
apprenticed in the art of the leveraged buyout
while head of his own successful Wall Street law firm, he 
went on to mastermind some of the most spectacular
deals ever; including the $1 billion purchase of food giant 
Beatrice International -- one of the largest leveraged
buyouts ever.

<p>Until now, little has been revealed about the life of this 
remarkable but private man.  Based on Reginald
Lewis' unfinished autobiography as well as scores of interviews 
with family, friends and colleagues, WHY
SHOULD WHITE GUYS HAVE ALL THE FUN? cuts through the myth and 
media hype to reveal the man
behind the legend.  

<p>REGINALD F. LEWIS was chairman, chief executive officer, 
and principal shareholder of TLC Beatrice
International Holdings, Inc., until his death of brain cancer 
in January 1993 at the age of fifty.

<p>BLAIR S. WALKER is a financial writer with the "Money" 
section of USA Today.  He has worked as an
editor with  New York Newsday and as a reporter with the 
Chicago bureau of The Associated Press.



 
<INPUT TYPE="hidden" NAME="0012|16.95|WHY SHOULD WHITE GUYS HAVE ALL THE FUN?" VALUE="1">
