<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Congress: Statement of Intent</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>STATEMENT OF INTENT</H2>
<BR>
The concept of sustainable development envisages a co-evolution of humankind
and the biosphere, which ensures and supports their long-time viability,
separately and in their interconnectedness. Humankind depends on a healthy
and nourishing natural and social environment. The increasing overexploitation
of natural resources and the related pollution is endangering the ability
of ecosystems to recover from stress and catastrophes. Humankind is thus
gradually eroding its life-support basis. At the same time the sustainability
of our social, economic and political structures has to be questioned, because
they lead, inherently, to gross inequalities. <BR>
<BR>
The <A HREF="http://www.ciesin.org/datasets/unced/unced.html">United Nations
Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED)</A> in Rio de Janeiro
in 1992 stated general principles of social, economic and ecological development
necessary to make the development process globally sustainable. Since the
Rio Conference researchers, policy-makers and practitioners in different
parts of the world have been trying to work out approaches, appropriate
to local conditions, for the implementation of these principles. It has
become apparent that much more effort is needed to elaborate the concepts
further and to identify the most efficient steps for putting them into practice.<BR>
<BR>
For this reason the International Network of Engineers and Scientists for
Global Responsibility (INES) in cooperation with the University of Amsterdam,
the Wuppertal Institute for Climate, Environment and Energy and the International
Federation of Commercial, Clerical, Professional and Technical Employees
(FIET) has decided to organize an International Congress of Engineers and
Scientists, &quot;Challenges of Sustainable Development,&quot; in August
1996. The congress will be held in Amsterdam, the Netherlands, a country
which fosters innovative development projects and which was the focus of
a pioneering study, <A HREF="http://www.xs4all.nl/~foeint/suscamp.html">&quot;Sustainable
Netherlands&quot;</A>.<BR>
<BR>
The Congress will approach this complicated issue on three different levels:
<UL>
  <LI>The ethical foundation of sustainable development and the underlying
values and attitudes; 
  <LI>Concepts and strategies toward, and the conceptual, cultural and institutional
obstacles against sustainable development; 
  <LI>Implementation of sustainable development, including public education,
regulations, evaluation/monitoring and institutional reform. 
</UL>
<BR>
The organizers will place particular emphasis on conveying to the congress
practical experiences from work for sustainability. This will be facilitated
by seminars with practitioners, topical excursions in the greater urban
area of Amsterdam and by an interactive poster session. The congress will
address scientists and engineers as well as policy-makers, development experts
and economic practitioners. The attendance will be limited to 500 participants.
<BR>
<BR>
We believe that the Amsterdam Congress can be an important step in advocating
and fostering progress towards sustainable development in various parts
of the world. The congress is in the tradition of the 1991 International
Congress of Scientists and Engineers &quot;CHALLENGES,&quot; in Berlin,
which attracted a wide attendance.<BR>
<BR>
Professor Valery Petrosyan, Moscow<BR>
Professor Philip Smith, Groningen<BR>
<BR>
Chairpersons of the International Program Committee <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
