<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Congress: How to Embody Sustainability</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>HOW TO EMBODY SUSTAINABILITY <BR>
IN A CONGRESS</H2>
<BR>
International conferences are usually very resource-demanding and polluting,
particularly due to the long-distance travel of participants. When focusing
on sustainability as a congress theme we have to ask ourselves: how can
we make the congress itself sustainable as a meeting and work process? How
can we transform the physical resources and human efforts invested into
a fruitful event and into a low-waste result of lasting value? So far four
approaches towards this goal are anticipated:<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>1. Evaluation of congress resources and waste </STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Physical resources and energy spent for the congress will be estimated by
one of the congress workshops and brought to the awareness of all participants.
Strategies for optimal use of resources will be addressed. <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>2. Carbon dioxide compensation</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
It is intended to compensate for the carbon dioxide emission caused by the
congress travel through a tree planting project. All participants (except
those who arrive walking or by bicycle) are asked to pay a carbon dioxide
compensation contribution of DM 5.- to 30.-. The funds will be transferred
to a tree planting project.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>3. Contributions and exchange via electronic media </STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Communications by electronic media cannot replace person-to-person meetings,
but they can complement them in a resource-saving way. An exchange by electronic
media (INTERNET and video display) with those who cannot be present in Amsterdam
will be organized. In addition such media will be used in the preparation
stages of the congress. The following measures are being considered: 
<UL>
  <LI>Congress announcement via INTERNET; 
  <LI>INTERNET discussion groups on congress themes before and during the
congress; 
  <LI>Submission of abstracts and registration forms via INTERNET; 
  <LI>Distribution of plenary statements and workshop conclusions via INTERNET;
  <LI>Submission of videotapes on practical examples and case studies relevant
to sustainable development and display of such videos during the congress.
</UL>
<BR>
<STRONG>4. Making the congress a lasting experience; the green bike tour
</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
How can we enhance the quality of the meeting in order to achieve a lasting
impact? Here are some planning goals: 
<UL>
  <LI>Participants will be encouraged to make contact before the congress
and arrange joint travel from nearby countries by train or bicycle. In particular,
a GREEN BIKE TOUR will be arranged from 14 till 22 August, leading from
the INES headquarters in Dortmund to Amsterdam; 
  <LI>Introduction of elements of &quot;experience&quot; in the workshops;
  <LI>Careful follow-up of congress results by participants, and communication
to a wider public. 
</UL>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../amsterdam#anchor339098">main conference page</A>.<BR>
