<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Congress: Workshops</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>WORKSHOPS (23 August, 9.30 - 24 August 12.30)</H2>
<H4>The assignment of rooms in the Literature Faculty buildings, Spuistraat
134 and 210 will be announced at the congress.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><IMG SRC="../images/newred.gif" WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="13" ALIGN="BOTTOM"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3">It is now possible to get some of the workshop programmes
sent via e-mail. This can be handy for your collegues who can not access
the WWW. Please check out the congress <A HREF="emailfileserve.html">e-mail
fileserver</A>.</H4>
<BR>
<HR>The workshops will be the main platform for work and exchange. Each
workshop will be self contained and run through three half-day sessions.
For those workshops where this is relevant, one of the half-day sessions
will be devoted to a seminar with practitioners. Whenever possible the seminars
will be supplemented by an excursion in the greater urban area of Amsterdam
with practical demonstrations. Each workshop will be responsible for formulating
a set of conclusions (statements of fact, intent and implementation). The
conclusions will be presented to other participants in the Poster and Video
Session. 
<H4><A NAME="anchor647794"></A>1. Ethical foundations and basic attitudes</H4>
<MENU><A HREF="workshops/ws11ethdim.html">1.1 Ethical dimension of sustainability</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="workshops/ws12suslif.html">1.2 Sustainable lifestyles and underlying
human attitudes<BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="workshops/ws13socpro.html">1.3 Social problems of sustainability<BR>
</A><BR>
<A HREF="workshops/ws14edusus.html">1.4 Education for sustainable development</A>
</MENU>
<H4><A NAME="anchor647966"></A>2. Challenges to economy: Concepts and strategies
for sustainable economies</H4>
<MENU><A HREF="workshops/ws21ecodim.html">2.1 Economic dimensions of sustainability:
Challenges to the world economic order</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="workshops/ws22criind.html">2.2 Criteria and indicators for sustainability</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="workshops/ws23indsus.html">2.3 Industry and sustainability</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="workshops/ws24manmat.html">2.4 Management of material flows and
energy supply<BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="workshops/ws25evaper.html">2.5 Evaluation of personal and institutional
energy and resource budgets<BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="workshops/ws26susagr.html">2.6 Sustainable agriculture, forestry,
fishery and food processing<BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="workshops/ws27manwat.html">2.7 Management of water and waste
water</A> 
</MENU>
<H4><A NAME="anchor648545"></A>3. Sustainable development on a local, regional
and global scale</H4>
<MENU><A HREF="workshops/ws31tramob.html">3.1 Transportation and mobility<BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="workshops/ws32telsus.html">3.2 Telecommunications and sustainability
</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="workshops/ws33casstu.html">3.3 Case studies of successfull development
through sustainability<BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="workshops/ws34conune.html">3.4 Confronting unequal development<BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="workshops/ws35polsus.html">3.5 The politics of sustainability:
Challenges to democracy</A> 
</MENU>
<H4><A NAME="anchor648909"></A>4. Elements of a safe and secure world</H4>
<MENU><A HREF="workshops/ws41peares.html">4.1 Peaceful resolution of social,
ethno-national and environmental conflicts<BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="workshops/ws42nucwea.html">4.2 Nuclear weapons abolition and
nuclear waste storage<BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="workshops/ws43chebio.html">4.3 Chemical and biological disarmament</A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="workshops/ws44condis.html">4.4 Conventional disarmament and conversion
of military resources and production</A> 
</MENU>
<BR>
