<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Inl&auml;gg av Karl-Henrik Rob&egrave;rt m.fl.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
August 1996<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<P><CENTER><B>Simplicity without Reduction<BR>
-Thinking Upstream Towards the Sustainable Society-</B><BR>
Karl-Henrik Rob&egrave;rt, John Holmberg and G&ouml;ran Broman</CENTER>
<P><BR>
<BR>
The Natural Step works with a scientific dialogue method that we have termed
&quot;Simplicity without Reduction&quot;. The aim is to understand ecological
connections without having to reduce the whole into a collection of details.
It is impossible to keep every detail in mind at the same time, so instead
we describe overall principles for systems. After understanding the overall
principles, one can interpret details and foresee changes with a much higher
degree of accuracy. We hand the principles over to decision-makers, so that
within their own particular fields they can implement the necessary actions.<BR>
<BR>
We can refer to the overall principles as &quot;trunk and branches&quot;,
and all consequences and activities of the system as &quot;leaves&quot;.
The leaves could be various measures such as technical designs or changes
in behaviour that are attempts to satisfy the overall principles for the
system. Once the overall principles are established, decision-makers within
various fields of expertise can undertake the measures required to meet
the principles - &quot;put on the leaves&quot;. It is easier to build mutual
understanding, creativity and initiative if you start with the &quot;trunk
and branches&quot; for several reasons:<BR>
<BR>
	It is easier to think upstream in cause-effect chains, if you know the
overall principles.<BR>
<BR>
	Complexity is reduced as far as possible without losing comprehension of
the whole system.<BR>
<BR>
	This reduced complexity also applies to opinions and social norms.<BR>
<BR>
	Professional people have detailed knowledge within their own fields, but
often lack the sort of overview necessary for an understanding of the ecological
basis of their activities.<BR>
<BR>
	By stimulating professionals to interpret the information on the overall
principles into concrete measures, one creates engagement and mutual respect
instead of opposition.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The Compass<BR>
&quot;Simplicity without Reduction&quot; is designed to support systems
thinking in organisations. The fulfilment of overall principles defines
the frame for success in any plan. To know the frame is a prerequisite for
effective envisioning of the goal. Furthermore, the frame is a prerequisite
to determine which subgoals actually bring us closer to the goal - and,
conversely, to determine which subgoals are only providing short-term benefits
without bringing us closer to the goal. To exclude mistakes of this kind
is particularly important when subgoals are expensive to reach. High investment
ties us to a certain course, and will prove fatal to business in the long
run if they obstruct a viable course that is checked in relation to the
overall principles. This method for systems thinking has been developed
into a precise planning instrument - the &quot;Compass - in which a chart
with a time axis relates individual decisions to their eventual outcome,
even when this is a long way into the future. The overall goal for the sustainable
society (or even the overall goal for the local authority/corporation within
the sustainable society) cannot be defined in detail. On the other hand,
all details do not always need to be defined a long way in advance because
it is the understanding of overall principles - dealing with problems &quot;upstream&quot;
- that enables control over development. With regard to the most crucial
task on tomorrow's market, i.e. sustainable development, this occurs when
all economic activity is steered in accordance with the four System Conditions
for sustainable interactions with nature (see page 3).<BR>
<BR>
The scientific basis for the systems perspective of The Natural Step is
set out in a Doctoral Thesis by John Holmberg, PM) in Physical Resource
Theory at Chalmers Technical University in Gothenburg, Sweden, and in a
string of publications including the consensus documents of TNS which can
be ordered from The Natural Step.<BR>
<BR>
The consensus documents have been drawn up by editorial groups striving
to find overall principles within their respective fields. They describe
how the details relate to one another and to the overall principles. The
documents are then sent out for consideration by a larger group of people
who are knowledgeable within the specific field in question. Lastly, the
editorial group integrates feedback into a final version upon which all
the collaborators are agreed.<BR>
The System Conditions, supplemented by a chart containing a list of measures
and a time-axis, are an instrument (see page 4) to tackle the complexity
of economical/ecological planning. This instrument is not just another tool
for environmental planning, but rather an overall framework for sustainable
development.<BR>
<BR>
Experience of the planning instrument up to now has shown that:<BR>
<BR>
* Because the instrument proceeds from the whole system of the Earth, with
nature included - not just the technical cycles of our society - it provides
an absolute frame of reference. Seeing the whole system, one discover both
the obstacles and the possibilities. Since everything in the ecosystem is
connected, the instrument can be applied to any activity regardless of the
scale. With the planning instrument, one gains greater control of future
development. But without the overall goal right in front of one's eyes,
it is all too easy to lose control. Combined with this instrument, life-cycle
analysis and environmental auditing are excellent tools. Without it, such
tools can even be hazardous, for they may lull management teams into a false
sense of control.<BR>
<BR>
* Because the instrument proceeds from an absolute frame of reference, it
is valid at any scale. For the same reason, it can be used to optimise return
on investment in the individual organisation. The global society is living
outside the frame of sustainability by violating the four Systems Conditions.
If your enterprise is one of the contributors to this violation - and this
is easy to ascertain since the Systems Conditions are clearly defined -
your enterprise is doomed economically unless you change strategy. If you
continue to invest into an even deeper economical dependence on continued
violation of the System Conditions, you will - sooner or later - lose your
money. (Note the last sentence in each System Condition on the next page,
and the funnel of the Compass on the last page).<BR>
<BR>
* The time-axis on the planning chart means that one can see short-term
subgoals in relation to the overall goal (meeting the System Conditions).
The sub-goals must not undermine future improvements. Sticking to this procedure
saves one from making major investment errors which may today minimise an
environmental impact, but tomorrow might be wholly irrelevant.<BR>
<BR>
* For a management team, upstream principles are generally more important,
easier to gain commitment to, and more readily agreed upon than details.
While life-cycle analysis and environmental auditing are tools the expert
utilises for subgoals, this planning instrument gives the CEO, otherwise
commonly isolated from the environment division, a personal engagement.
He becomes part of the same team as the people in the environment division,
and can share their language. This, in addition, usually leads to not only
better long-term planning but also higher budgets for sustainable development.<BR>
<BR>
* The time-axis also functions as a sort of psychological shock absorber.
It can be disturbing to see the gap between the overall goal and today's
reality. Yet every journey begins with a single step. This strategy of gradual
improvement ensures that the &quot;best does not become an enemy of the
good&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Deduction of the four System Conditions</B> <BR>
<BR>
The precondition of our lives<BR>
Humanity cannot tolerate a systematic shift in environmental parameters.
We cannot, for instance, sustain ever higher levels of heavy metals, ever
higher levels of greenhouse gases, ever smaller areas of productive crop-land
and ever lower pH values.<BR>
<BR>
Basic science<BR>
Matter and energy cannot appear or disappear. <BR>
Matter and energy tend to spread spontaneously. <BR>
Material quality is the concentration and structure of matter. <BR>
Material quality on Earth is net-produced only by sun-driven processes.
<BR>
<BR>
The cyclic principle<BR>
Basic science and the precondition of our lives lead to the cyclic principle.
It means that waste must not systematically accumulate in Nature, and that
material quality is recreated at least as fast as it is used up. Consequently,
matter must go in cycles: society's metabolism of resources must be integrated
into the sun-driven cycles of Nature. This avoids a systematic shift in
environmental parameters and enables the continuing diversity of nature
and human activity. Thus the sustainable society stands for much more than
recycling. A sustainable society is a society where resources are used in
a way that allows Nature to maintain the resource base. A model of such
a society is presented in fig 1.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
 <BR>
<BR>
<I>Figure 1. For its photosynthesis, the green cell A uses exergy from the
Sun to concentrate and </I>structure dispersed matter into resources, such
as carbohydrates. These exergy-rich resources are <I>then also used to maintain
the animal cell B. The animals together with the decomposers </I>discharge
these resources into carbon dioxide, water and nutrients that can again
be used as <I>building blocks and be recharged into exergy-rich structures
by the green cell. Thus, the matter </I>goes around in huge cycles, partially
in the form of exergy-rich structures and partially in the <I>form of dispersed
matter. The energy is converted in many steps. The final form is low-temperature
</I>heat which is radiated into space. The exergy from the Sun also maintains
the great water cycle, <I>in which water is lifted to high altitudes, and
thus charged with gravitational exergy that is </I>gradually lost when the
water is running back to the sea. There is also a continuous weathering
of <I>substances from the lithosphere which is balanced by sedimentation
back to the lithosphere. The </I>pre<I>-industrial so</I>ciety used resources
mainly from the ecosphere and returned the &quot;waste&quot; to the <I>ecosphere,
where it was recharged into new resources, by processes that used exergy
from the </I>Sun. These charging processes have exceeded or at least kept
pace with the societal discharging <I>processes until recently. As discussed
in Section 4, the industrial society has increased the use of </I>substances
from the lithosphere (1) and its emissions of artificial substances (2).
It has also <I>increased its manipulation of the ecosphere (3). These trends
imply that resources are </I>systematically depleted; substances are systematically
accumulating in the ecosphere and the <I>long-term productivity capacity
and diversity are systematically deteriorated. Furthermore, the </I>societal
transformations of natural resources into services to humanity are afflicted
with low <I>efficiency and injustices (4) [Holmberg 1995].<BR>
<BR>
</I><BR>
If waste is systematically accumulating in the biosphere at the expense
of resources, it can only be due to three overall mechanisms which don't
overlap functionally:<BR>
	Waste is increasing because matter is systematically introduced to the
biosphere from the Earth's<BR>
	crust at a higher rate than it is redeposited back.<BR>
	Waste is increasing, because it is produced by society at a higher rate
than it can be deposited in<BR>
the Earth's crust or be used as building blocks in nature.<BR>
	Waste is increasing, because Nature itself is turned into waste (such as
greenhouse gases) while<BR>
in the same time its sun-driven capacity to process waste into resources
is diminished.<BR>
	A fourth mechanism is social, and acts as an accelerator on all these mechanisms:
a wasteful and 	unfair handling of resources with respect to human needs.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
These mechanisms are formulated into the System Conditions:<BR>
<BR>
<B>System Condition 1.</B>	Substances from the Earth's crust must not systematically
increase in <B>nature. <BR>
<BR>
</B>This means that in the sustainable society: fossil fuels, metals and
other minerals are not extracted at a faster pace than their slow redeposit
into the Earth's crust. <I>Because: </I>otherwise quality will be lost due
to the inevitable spread of wastes and their accumulation towards often
unknown limits beyond which irreversible changes occur. <I>In practical
terms this means in today's situation: </I>radically decreased mining -
particularly of minerals that are scarce in Nature and where continued mining
consequently will lead to rapid increases in concentration, and use of fossil
fuel.<BR>
Does your organisation systematically decrease its economical dependence
on mining and fossil fuels?<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>System Condition 2.</B>	Substances produced by society must not systematically
increase in <B>nature. <BR>
<BR>
</B>This means that in the sustainable society: substances are not produced
at a faster pace than they can be broken down in nature or deposited into
the Earth's crust. <I>Because: </I>otherwise quality will be lost due to
the inevitable spread of substances and their accumulation towards often
unknown limits beyond which irreversible changes occur. <I>In practical
terms this means in today's situation: </I>decreased production of natural
substances that are accumulating, and a phase out of all persistent and
unnatural substances.<BR>
Does your organisation systematically decrease its economical dependence
on persistent unnatural substances?<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>System Condition 3.  </B>	The physical basis for the productivity and
diversity of nature must not <B>be </B>	<B>	</B>	<B>	systematically deteriorated.
<BR>
<BR>
</B><I>This means that in the sustainable society: </I>the productive surfaces
of nature are not diminished in quality or quantity (for instance soil and
groundwater), and we must not harvest more from nature than can be recreated.
<I>Because: </I>our health and prosperity depend on the capacity of nature
to re-concentrate and restructure wastes into resources. <I>In practical
terms this means: in today's </I>situation: sweeping changes of our use
of areas in, for instance, agriculture, forestry, fishing and planning of
societies.<BR>
Does your organisation systematically decrease its economical dependence
on activities which encroach on productive parts of Nature e.g. long road
transports?<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>System Condition 4.</B>	Fair and efficient use of energy and other resources
to meet human <B>needs. <BR>
<BR>
</B><I>This means that in the sustainable society: </I>basic human needs
must be met with the most resource-efficient methods possible, including
ajust resource distribution and a levelling-out of population growth. <I>Because:
</I>humanity must prosper with a resource metabolism meeting system conditions
1-3. This is necessary to achieve the social stability and co-operation
for making the changes in due time. <I>In practical terms this means in
today's situation: </I>an increased technical and organisational efficiency
in the whole world, including a more resource-economical lifestyle in the
rich part. Does your organisation systematically decrease its economical
dependence on using a large amount of resources in relation to added human
value?<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Taken together, these System Conditions define the framework for any sustainable
society. System Conditions 1-3 are based on a scientific analysis and are
&quot;true bottom line&quot; System Conditions (they do not overlap, they
define the problem at the source of cause-effect chains, all must be fulfilled,
and violations of these explain all the environmental problems that concern
sustainability. Furthermore: If you violate them, time that is needed to
tackle other important questions in society is lost.<BR>
System Condition 4, which so many actions for the environment are related
to - recycling, reuse, reduction etc., - is as important but takes on a
special role. This condition is a consequence of the first three conditions.
Many organisations are working with this System Condition without connecting
it to the other three. This means that System Conditions 1-3 are neglected
despite the fulfilment of these being the main purpose - seen from a sustainability
perspective - of working with System Condition 4. Also, this condition does
not deal so much with physics, rather with people and societies, In physical
terms it is enough to fulfil System Conditions 1-3 in order to achieve ecological
sustainability. Consequently, System Condition 4 is relative to System Conditions
1-3 and cannot be described in absolute terms. There is probably no limit
to resource efficiency for the satisfaction of human needs. But if System
Condition 4 is not met at a high enough degree, we cannot meet the first
three conditions either. It is therefore logical to include it amongst the
other System Conditions, but what makes &quot;Fair and efficient use of
resources to meet human needs&quot; the overall social consequence from
System Conditions 1-3?<BR>
<BR>
Efficiency<BR>
The term&quot; efficiency&quot; has a different meaning to the common term,
e.g. to make 1000 plastic ducks per hour instead of 500. Here, &quot; efficiency&quot;
means resource efficiency for meeting human needs, i.e. to make better use
per resource investment: &quot;to satisfy 20 people instead of 5 with the
same resource input&quot;. This follows from the first three System Conditions
constituting a kind of frame for sustainable use of resources. To be able
to stay within this frame, it's important not to waste resources, but rather
to develop more and more resource-efficient and sophisticated methods for
meeting human needs. It is important that the term &quot;efficiency&quot;
is not seen in a narrow perspective, e.g. more energy-efficient dishwashers
and cars. In the larger perspective a more effective organisation of society
as such is a far more critical problem, e.g. to avoid unnecessary long transports
of goods that have a low degree of refinement (such as bread or soft drinks).
We must instead learn to exchange recipes.<BR>
<BR>
Fairness<BR>
Fairness refers to efficiency on the global scale. On the global scale,
an inefficient local use of resources is not fair when taking global human
needs into account. The term &quot;fairness&quot; has been discussed for
so long, with loaded arguments, that we have almost forgotten what the word
really means. In this discussion, we have applied the term in the less strict
meaning &quot;not-unfair&quot;, because it poses smaller risks of argument
over values. Furthermore, in an ecological sense, fairness must be seen
in the large perspective of humanity. From this perspective, it's easy to
see that the distribution of resources is unfair, since 20% of humans use
80% of the resources, while another 20% starve and lack access to clean
water. This unfairness is not compatible with ecological practice. We live
in the same system, the ecosphere, without boundaries. Those who want to
survive in the long run must support - not tear down - the total system
on which we all depend. If the children in Brazil starve, dad cuts down
the rain forest regardless of whether the rest of the world strives to meet
the three first System Conditions. Therefore, resource-efficient activities
in defined technical or even national perspectives are not sufficient. No
actions can be said to be sustainable, if today's unfair resource distribution
is maintained. The first three System Conditions cannot fairly be met within
the wealthy parts of the world, while at the same time controlling the starving
part of the world with weapons, so that System Conditions 1-3 are met also
here. The word &quot;fairness&quot; is sometimes thought of as a politically
loaded notion. However, this is not necessary, since no political parties
have unfairness on their manifestos. Efficiency of resource-use from an
ecological perspective requires that we dare to address the term fairness.
From a social perspective, efficiency means that resources are used where
they are most needed.<BR>
<BR>
The Compass<BR>
The &quot;Compass&quot; in the figure below, with its global efficiency/fairness
perspective, is already the foundation for development strategies within
many Swedish companies and municipalities. It is an instrument for dialogue,
problem-solving and investment-strategies. It is constituted by the System
Conditions, a program for transformation, and the &quot;funnel&quot; (see
fig). The latter is a metaphor for the decrease of resources in the biosphere.
We are today over 5 billion people, and will in a short time be 10 billion
on an Earth that is not growing. At the same time, violation of the System
Conditions are decreasing the absolute amounts of available resources. Per
capita, the walls of the funnel are of course leaning inwards even more.
This will have a major impact on tomorrow's rules in the business market,
regardless if one chooses to see the problems now, or if one tries to hide
in ignorance until the consequences are inescapable. Forward-looking corporations
and other organisations, have therefore started the search for production
methods and lifestyles that can be applied internationally - as good examples
- at the same time as they strive for establishing economical relations
with the poor parts of the world that do not undermine the possibilities
to satisfy their needs. These organisations avoid mistakes such as investing
in a recycling plant for metals, without determining whether this investment
gives a positive outcome on System Conditions 1 and 4. Did it decrease the
demand on thined metals? Was it a link in the attempts to satisfy human
needs in a more efficient way from a global perspective?<BR>
<BR>
 <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<I>Fig 2: Since we are violating the four System Conditions, waste is steadily
accumulating at the </I>same rate as resources are diminishing. This means
that the resource-potential for health and <I>economy is systematically
decreasing. At the same time, the Earth's population is rapidly </I>increasing.
Non-sustainable development could be visualised as entering deeper and deeper
into <I>a rinnel, in which the space becomes narrower and narrower. To the
individual company, </I>municipality, or country - wanting to make skilful
investments, the crucial thing must then be to <I>direct its investments
towards the opening of the funnel, rather than into the wall. In reality
this </I>means that the smart investor makes himself less and less economically
dependent on continued <I>violation of the System Conditions. The laws of
nature supersede man-made laws. Hence it will be </I>inevitable to suffer
economically - and eventually to be wiped out from the market - if the <I>economical
course is not altered to meet the System Conditions. The wall of the funnel
will </I>superimpose itself more and more into daily economic reality in
the following way: more and <I>more environmentally concerned customers,
stricter and stricter legislation, higher and higher </I>costs and fees
for resources as well as pollution, and tougher and tougher competition
from <I>competitors who invest themselves skilfully towards the opening
of the flinnel by meeting the four </I>System Conditions.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><BR>
<HR>G&aring; till <A HREF="mts-CMTS-17dec.html">seminariets huvudsida</A><BR>
