<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Congress: Peggy Antrobus presentation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>SUMMARY OF PEGGY ANTROPUS' PRESENTATION</H2>
<H3>FROM LOCAL TO GLOBAL: ALTERNATIVE APPROACHES TO SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT</H3>
<BR>
Presentation by Peggy Antrobus, General-Coordinator Development Alternatives
with Women for a New Era (DAWN) to the Panel Discussion of the International
Congress of Engineers and Scientists, Challenges of Sustainable Development,
Amsterdam, Saturday afternoon, 24 August 17:00 - 18:30<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Since 1962, and especially in the past five years in the context of the
UN Conferences of the 1990s, starting with the UN Conference on Environment
and Development (UNCED), increasing attention has been paid to the crises
in development and to the need to promote a more sustainable approach to
development.<BR>
<BR>
The concept of sustainable development is loosely defined and has different
meanings to different groups of people. While to the mainstream it has come
to be equated with sustained growth and market-oriented economic policies,
to those who see in these strategies the cause of the environmental crisis
it means finding alternative approaches to development. An alternative to
the mainstream concept of sustainable development is development which ensures
sustainable livelihoods for the poor without harming or endangering present
or future environments.<BR>
<BR>
However, there is no global blueprint: each country/region needs to define
its own approach based on its resources and on indigenous visions and conceptions
of sustainable development. A comprehensive understanding and respect for
the values, practices and rituals related to indigenous knowledge systems
are desirable components which facilitate sustainable development. It is
also of critical importance that indigenous experience and work with local
communities be linked to work on macro-economic policies.<BR>
<BR>
The need for alternative approaches to development has been continually
and forcefully articulated by women whose special responsibility for the
health and livelihood of people places them in a special relationship with
the environment and the management of natural resources. This relationship
is most clearly seen in the lives of rural women from the South.<BR>
<BR>
The network of Third World women, Development Alternatives with Women for
a New ERA (DAWN), is one of those promoting alternatives which are grounded
in the reality of women from different regions - from the islands of the
Caribbean and the Pacific to the largest countries of Africa, Asia and Latin
America. The diversity of these habitats demand that approaches to sustainable
development be defined by the people who live in these countries/regions
and that women, especially poor women, be assured a central role in this
definition and in the strategies for achieving a model of development which
is sustainable not only ecologically but economically, socially and culturally
as well.<BR>
<BR>
Go back to the <A HREF="../plenaries.html#anchor269081">plenary page</A><BR>
Go back to <A HREF="../../amsterdam#anchor298722">main page</A><BR>
<BR>
