<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Ethical dimension of sustainability </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>1.1 Ethical dimension of sustainability</H2>
<BR>
Tentative Programme (<A HREF="#anchor46261">below</A>)<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="ws11/ws11abstr.html">List of abstracts and poster presentations</A><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Lars Ryd&eacute;n, Director<BR>
The Baltic University Programme, the Secretariat at Uppsala University<BR>
Box 2109, S-75002 Uppsala, Sweden.<BR>
Tel +46-18-18 18 38, Fax +46-18-18 17 89, E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:Lars.Ryden@uadm.uu.se">Lars.Ryden@uadm.uu.se</A><BR>
<BR>
Guillermo A. Lemarchand, Professor of astrophysics, Universidad de Buenos
Aires, Argentina, <BR>
collaborator in the formulation of a code of ethics for researchers<BR>
Centro de Estudios Avanzados, Universidad de Buenos Aires <BR>
Casilla Coreos 8, Sucursal 25, 1425 Buenos Aires, Argentina <BR>
TEL: +54 1 774 0667, FAX: +54 1 963 6962 <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:lemar@seti.edu.ar">lemar@seti.edu.ar </A><BR>
<BR>
Hans-J&uuml;rgen Fischbeck, physicist, Lecturer<BR>
Haus der Begegnung, Evangelische Akademie <BR>
Uhlenhorstweg 29, 45479 M&uuml;hlheim/Ruhr, Deutschland <BR>
TEL: +49 208 5990 6544 / 5990 6543, FAX: +49 208 5990 6600<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Local organizer:<BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Jan Vorstenbosch<BR>
Centre for Bioethics and Health Law<BR>
Rijksuniversiteit Utrecht<BR>
Postbus 80105, 3508 TC Utrecht, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 30 253 1853, FAX: +31 30 253 3241<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:Jan.Vorstenbosch@phil.ruu.nl">Jan.Vorstenbosch@phil.ruu.nl
</A><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Topics:</STRONG> <BR>
<BR>
What are the conflicts between society and nature? <BR>
To what extent should nature be left alone? <BR>
What is the intrinsic value of nature? <BR>
What is a just distribution of scarce resources? <BR>
What normative reasoning is behind the shaping of landscape <BR>
by humankind? <BR>
How to respect the right of future generations? <BR>
Spiritual basis of sustainability <BR>
<BR>
The Concept of Sustainability in the contemporary debate on development
In the contemporary debate on development and environmental impact the word
sustainability is found in different contexts and with different connotations.
It plays the role of metaphor for not always spelled out hopes, fears and
visions. In this contribution I will attempt to analyse which some of these
are.<BR>
<BR>
The fact that Sustainability is understood in a diversity of ways is not
necessarily negative, as sometimes said. It can be compared to how concepts
such as Peace and Health are understood. They are also carriers of hopes,
fears and visions as well as rather detailed technical descriptions and
definitions. This is not perceived as negative.<BR>
<BR>
Sustainability may be identified as carrier of six clearly different connotations.
These are: 
<OL>
  <LI>Civilisation shift, the genuinely new, not previously known in social
debate; 
  <LI>The systems analysis perspective, beyond the reductionistic tradition
now dominating science; 
  <LI>Just distribution of resources between generations, required by the
long term conservation of resources; 
  <LI>Respect for Nature necessitated by the long term conservation of Nature
productivity and diversity; 
  <LI>The role of grass roots perspective for implementation making sustainability
a picture of true democracy; and finally 
  <LI>The personal involvement where sustainability stands for the Good
Life, the goals for the strivings by in particular young people. 
</OL>
It is thus possible to express sustainability in a mathematical form (no.2
above), or as a political program (no.1 above), in particular if the development
aspect is stressed. However of the six connotations mentioned above, five
have a very obvious ethical aspect. And above all the requirement for intergenerational
equity makes sustainability in itself unavoidably an ethical concept.<BR>
<BR>
The following subjects will be discussed: 
<UL>
  <LI>Society vs nature. Man intrudes on and exploits Nature in a massive
and irreversible way. What is the value basis for the &quot;rights&quot;
of Nature and Society resp, i.e. for biocentric vs anthropocentric ethics.
  <LI>The rights of future generations. The basis of sustainbility is the
respect for future generations. This is however not trivial. What are our
responsibilities and their future obligations? 
  <LI>Distribution of scarce resources. Unequal distribution of resources
is an obvious problem for e.g. people living upstream and downstream a river.
Have only upstreamers right to clean water? Similar questions apply to distribution
also on a global scale, e.g. for carbon dioxide emissions. 
  <LI>Choosing our Future. Developing a sustainble society involves a number
of choices, e.g. if a road should be built, a forest cut etc. Each time
value conflicts occur. How do we handle these conflicts? 
  <LI>The responsiblity of science and technology. Developing sustainability
is a challenge for science and technology. In which way does it contribute?
Or hinder? Is there a sustainable science? 
</UL>
<H4><A NAME="anchor46261"></A>Tentative Programme (as of July 1, 1996)</H4>
<PRE>Friday, August 23

1. <B>The dilemma of Man and Nature. The meaning of sustainability.</B>
   Chair: Christiane Floyd, University of Hamburg.

9.30	Opening. Lars Ryden, The Baltic University Programme, Uppsala University.
9.45 	Ethics of sustainbility - the discussion within the IUCN framework.
	Sheelagh O'Reilly, Centre for Arid Zone studies, University of 		Wales, Bangor
10.15 	Discussion
10.45 	Coffee break
11.00 	Review of papers I
11.30 	Discussion of the papers. Comments by the authors.

2. <STRONG>The reasons and roots of unsustainbility in our culture.</STRONG>
   Guided by Jan Vorstenbosch, Center for Bioethics, University of Utrecht

12.45	Departure for Kerk en Wereld, Driebergen. On the way Jan Vorstenbosch
	will act as guide and point to several places where there were conflicts
	between Nature and man and explain how these were managed.
13.45 	Welcome to Kerk en Wereld, Driebergen Lunch, walk
15.00 	Prof. van der Wal, Problems of sustainability from a general cultural
	perspective. The shortcomings of present approaches and the need for
	changes in attitudes and lifestyles.
15.45 	Discussion of the contribution
16.00 	Break
16.30 	All powers comes from within, Mathias Braunig and Faul Tilman:
	Meditative and communitative event.
