<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Sustainable lifestyles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>1.2 Sustainable lifestyles and underlying human attitudes</H2>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Eric Hol, Buddhist Perception of Nature<BR>
438 North &quot;C&quot; Street, Springfield, OR 97477, USA <BR>
TEL: +1 503 741 0251, FAX: +1 503 741 0251 <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:ehol@mcimail.com">ehol@mcimail.com</A><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Local organizer:<BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Piet Schenkelaars, <BR>
Rembrandtlaan 68, 2251 HA Voorschoten, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 71 561 4409, FAX: +31 70 350 7171<BR>
<STRONG><BR>
Topics: </STRONG>
<UL>
  <LI>Population issues and impacts 
  <LI>Lessons from anthropology 
  <LI>What motivations and attitudes are behind unsustainable lifestyles?
  <LI>Analysis of different lifestyles (case studies for different countries)
  <LI>How to change unsustainable lifestyles (Personal and institutional
approaches in different countries). 
</UL>
<STRONG>Objectives and summary:</STRONG> <BR>
<BR>
While the theory of sustainable production has been developed rapidly during
the last few years, in particular in academic circles, one of the main problems
in achieving sustainable communities pertains to the practical implementation
of sustainable living, a.k.a. sustainable consumption. While sustainable
consumption seems to be the key to achieve sustainable living, this topic
seems to be relatively obscure. We will try to focus on sustainable consumption
and the reasons for its unpopularity.<BR>
<BR>
Many initiatives to live in a sustainable manner are already in place, but
relatively little is known about their existence and activities. In session
I, we will explore some of these initiatives, and we will focus on some
of the characteristics that make such initiatives successful, or for that
matter, made others fail. The panel discussion will feature members from
sustainable communities, individuals that have attempted living in a sustainable
manner, and members of NGO's and academia that actively inform the public,
and/or conduct research to increase practical knowledge and experience about
sustainable consumption. In session II, we will explore some of the reasons
why sustainable consumption is a rather unpopular topic in the press, and
in academic research. One of the major impediments to provide much needed
knowledge and experience about sustainable consumption may be academia itself,
since published studies have to meet certain &quot;scholarly&quot; standards.
We, however, feel that first hand experience is imperative to provide necessary
experience for sustainable consumption. The press may focus on academic
&quot;experts&quot; for information on sustainable consumption. The panel
discussion will feature individuals from academia and environmental journalists.
An excursion to explore the relationship between farming communities, technology
and sustainability is at this point in preparation.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Invited speakers:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Jan Juffermans, De Kleine Aarde, Boxtel, Nederland <BR>
Guy Dilweg and Hans Zevenhuizen, Franciscanen Milieuproject,<BR>
Amersfoort, Nederland <BR>
Brad Marden, Salt Lake City, USA<BR>
Laura Westra, Secretary ISEE, Windsor, Canada <BR>
Michiel van der Zeeuw, Desk Editor of RTL 4 News,<BR>
Naarden, Nederland <BR>
JoAnn Valenti, BYU, Provo, Utah, USA<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Programme:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
The workshop will be in panel-discussion format. <BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor4624139"></A><STRONG>Proffered papers</STRONG>:<BR>
<BR>
Proffered papers by the following will be featured in an open session on
Friday, August 23:<BR>
<BR>
Lifestyle discussion in the Netherlands: wrong questions yield wrong answers<BR>
Chris Elzinga (<A HREF="ws12/elzinga.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
All power comes from within<BR>
Tilmann Faul (<A HREF="ws12/faul.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Return to sustainable dwelling?<BR>
Genevieve Jones, Arch Robert Gordon University, School of Surveying, Garthdee,
Aberdeen, Scotland (<A HREF="ws12/jones.html">abstract)</A><BR>
<BR>
Frugal lifestyles and values: How economics influences more sustainable
ways of life<BR>
Kathrine Richardson, Department of Planning, Public Policy and Management<BR>
University of Oregon (<A HREF="ws12/richardson.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Sustainable socio-natural interaction: cultural dimension and spiritual
basis<BR>
Marina Mojeiko and Alexander Zhdanovsky, Belarussian State University, Minsk,
Belarus (<A HREF="ws12/mojeiko.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Militarism: Whose security? -- The impact of militarism on environment and
on development<BR>
Carlota Lopes da Silva, Women's International League for Peace and Freedom
(WILPF) (<A HREF="ws12/silva.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
From responsible science to sustainable knowledge<BR>
Tom Wakeford, Department of Biology, University of York, United Kingdom
(<A HREF="ws12/wakeford.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
