<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Social problems of sustainability</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>1.3 Social aspects of sustainability</H2>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenor: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Gerhard Rohde, Trade Section Secretary, International Federation of Commercial,
Clerical, Professional and Technical Employees (FIET), Geneva, Switzerland<BR>
Avenue de Balexert 15, CH-1219 Ch&acirc;telaine - Gen&egrave;ve, Suisse
<BR>
TEL: +41 22 979 0311, FAX: +41 22 796 5321<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:hqinfo@fiet.org%20">hqinfo@fiet.org </A><BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor4769798">The programme can be found below.</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Topics: </STRONG>
<UL>
  <LI>Integrating the approach to the complex social issues of sustainability
  <LI>The effects of economic and ecological factors on workers' lives and
work 
  <LI>Sustainable development as a trade-union goal 
  <LI>Mobilization for sustainability of engineers and scientists 
  <LI>Alliances between trade unions and other groups 
</UL>
<STRONG>Introduction:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Although the concept of sustainability is promising in that it offers an
optimistic vision of the future and is probably the only concept that could
guarantee the long-term survival of men and nature, it is not unambiguous
and it entails a number of social problems and conflicts.<BR>
<BR>
The concept is complex since it comprises economic, ecological and social
aspects. The concept has to be implemented in a world that is characterised
by the globalisation of a market economy which leads to increasing competition,
even hypercompetition. A world that is also split between the North and
South and the West and East. In both directions there exist steep social,
economic and ecological differences.<BR>
<BR>
The workshop will look into the implications of these diverse backgrounds
which have to be reconciled with the concept of sustainability. A first
panel analyses the impact of globalisation and<BR>
depicts the role of international organisations such as the ILO, ICFTU,
OECD, UNEP, etc. There will be particular emphasis on social and environmental
clauses (sustainability clause) in international trade agreements such as
GATT, for example.<BR>
<BR>
A second panel will look at the different preconditions to which sustainable
development has to adapt since the whole context of political, technological,
economic, and social circumstances varies<BR>
greatly from the northern to the southern and from the western to the eastern
hemisphere. Different regions will be represented on this panel. They will
give their views of the social implications, their idea of sustainable development
and what they expect to be done in order to achieve social justice and a
reduction in the environmental burden on various countries.<BR>
<BR>
Sustainable development has also a significant societal connotation relating
to equality. Another aspect, probably the most controversial, is the issue
of sustainable production and consumption patterns. A panel will look into
the different aspects of equality, life styles, consumerism and cultural
attitudes on the one hand side and at the use of raw materials, product
life cycles and environmental auditing on the other. The ethics of renunciation
put forward by certain proponents of<BR>
sustainability probably conflict with the view that economic growth is the
means to safeguard employment. This discussion is indispensable if all the
relevant organisations are to be committed to the fight for our common future.<BR>
<BR>
From a trade union point of view, the workplace constitutes a crucial area
where the concept of sustainability has to be applied. A complex approach
will be presented by the Swedish TCO, called the &quot;6 E-model&quot; (Ecology,
Emission, Efficiency, Economy, Energy, and Ergonomics). this<BR>
is a systematic approach which does not merely considered the individual
elements, but rather shapes all the &quot;E's&quot; into a systemic whole.<BR>
<BR>
The workshop will sum up by considering the different problems that challenge
trade unions in their aspirations for sustainability in: 
<UL>
  <LI>the work place 
  <LI>in collective bargaining, 
  <LI>in the wider society and at international level, 
  <LI>and in their efforts to seek allies and join forces with other organised
interest groupings such as scientists and engineers. 
</UL>
<A NAME="anchor4769798"></A><STRONG>Programme:</STRONG> 
<PRE>Friday, 23 August  -  Morning Session

