<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Economic dimensions of sustainability</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>2.1 Economic dimensions of sustainability: Challenges to the world economic
order</H2>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Hans Opschoor, Rector,<BR>
Institute of Social Studies <BR>
Postbus 29776, 2502 LT Den Haag, Nederland <BR>
TEL: +31 70 426 0412, FAX: +31 70 426 0759<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:opschoor@iss.nl">opschoor@iss.nl </A><BR>
<BR>
Tariq Banuri, Director,<BR>
Sustainable Development Policy Institute (SDPI) <BR>
46. Street 12, F-6/3 Islamabad, Pakistan <BR>
TEL: +92 51 211 097 / 218 134, FAX: +92 51 218 135<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:tariq@sdpi.sdnpk.undp.org">tariq@sdpi.sdnpk.undp.org</A><BR>
<BR>
Philip Smith, Professor of physics (ret.), Rijksuniversiteit Groningen,
Netherlands<BR>
Steenhouwerskade 22, 9718 DB Groningen, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 50 314 5093, FAX: +31 50 312 9186<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:p.b.smith@phys.rug.nl">p.b.smith@phys.rug.nl</A><BR>
<BR>
The <A HREF="#anchor46883">programme can be found below</A>.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Topics:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
This workshop is devoted to a discussion of some broad and highly policy
relevant issues on the interface of the economy and the biosphere, with
the object of arriving at a well-founded conception of what the notion of
sustainability implies as an injunction to the economic system at the national,
regional and global levels. The underpinnings of (neo-)liberal market-theory
will be examined in this light.<BR>
<BR>
Participants at the workshop will address such questions as: What types
of economic transformation can be discerned in various parts of the world
and what do they entail in terms of resource claims and flows of waste and
pollutants? What does the process of globalisation of economic growth under
liberalising conditions mean for these transformation processes and the
resulting environmental repercussions? What experiences and proposals can
be used in ecologically restructuring economies and in greening structural
adjustment? What are the impacts of a diversifying division of labour for
the biosphere, through changing patterns of production and international
trade? What are the prospects for applying environmental or ecological conditionalities
as constraints on international trade? Does sustainability entail regional
self sufficiency rather than global interdependence? Which types of institutional
reform (at the national, regional and global level) are necessary to gear
economic processes toward sustainability?<BR>
<BR>
What are the potentials of, and prospects for, altering regimes of property
and access rights and for incorporating environmental costs in prices (e.g.
through greening systems of taxation)? What are the distributional implications
(environmental, economic and social costs and benefits) of economic development
along traditional lines (&quot;business as usual&quot;) and along alternative,
ecologically restructured ones?<BR>
<BR>
The results of the workshop, in terms of a set of conclusions and recommendations,
along with several outstanding presented papers (if necessary in abridged
form) will appear in the conference proceedings. The following broad topics
will be covered: 
<UL>
  <LI>Economic growth, development and sustainability 
  <LI>International division of labour, trade and the environment 
  <LI>Redressing market and policy failures in achieving sustainability
  <LI>Poverty, environment and development. 
</UL>
<A NAME="anchor46883"></A><B>Programme:</B> 
<PRE>Friday, 23 August - Morning Session

Chairperson: Hans Opschoor

