<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Criteria and indicators for sustainability</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>2.2 Criteria and indicators for sustainability</H2>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Joachim Spangenberg, biologist, Research Associate<BR>
Wuppertal Institut f&uuml;r Klima, Umwelt Energie, Germany<BR>
D&ouml;ppersberg 19, 42103 Wuppertal, Deutschland<BR>
TEL: +49 202 2492 181, FAX: +49 202 2492 138 <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:%20j.spangenberg@mail.wupperinst.org">j.spangenberg@mail.wupperinst.org</A>
<BR>
<BR>
Ekaterina Nikonorova, Professor ,<BR>
Department of Social Ecology, Russian Academy of Public Service,<BR>
Pr. Vernadskoyo 84, Moskwa 117606, Rossia <BR>
TEL: +7 095 436 0900 / 436 0860, FAX: +7 095 434 5700<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor76368">The programme can be found below.</A><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Topics:</STRONG> 
<UL>
  <LI>The human development index 
  <LI>Environmental quality and human health 
  <LI>Social and environmental safety of families as a basis of sustainable
community development 
  <LI>Shortcomings of the GNP as an indicator 
  <LI>The index for sustainable economy (Club of Rome proposal) 
  <LI>Use and misuse of the concept of sustainability 
</UL>
<STRONG>Introduction:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Sustainability is a phrase made famous by the 1992 UNCED conference, but<BR>
although it has been quoted by statesmen all over the world ever since,<BR>
it still lacks operationability. The main inherent reason is that<BR>
sustainability means achieving different policy goals at the same time:<BR>
environmental, social and economic concerns must be addressed together.<BR>
<BR>
However, the traditional organisation of policy making is based on the<BR>
division of tasks: economic politics bears the responsibility for<BR>
economic growth and development, social politics has to moderate its<BR>
social impacts, and environmental politics is focussed on curing the<BR>
devastations resulting from economic growth. Furthermore, no simple<BR>
criteria are available which would help decision makers in the political<BR>
as well as in the business sector to respect social and environmental<BR>
criteria while pursuing their economic goals.<BR>
<BR>
This is where indicators can play a role: they are a tool to reduce<BR>
complexity in order to enable decision makers to take otherwise<BR>
unnoticed &quot;side-effects&quot; of their decisions into account. They
can act<BR>
as a permanent reminder, a &quot;cetero censeo&quot; before any decision
is taken,<BR>
and thus help to harmonise otherwise uncoordinated special politics.<BR>
<BR>
Lastly, good indicators enhance transparency of decision making and thus<BR>
enable the public to follow closely the actions of all stake holders<BR>
involved. The workshop is thought to present some of the most important<BR>
concepts for the development of systems of indicators, compare them,<BR>
identify weaknesses and produce some recommendations to be addressed to<BR>
the relevant institutions on the international level. <BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor76368"></A><STRONG>Programme:</STRONG>
<PRE><B>Friday, August 23rd
</B>
