<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Sustainable agriculture etc.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>2.6 Sustainable agriculture, forestry, fishery and food processing</H2>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Anne H. Ehrlich, Senior research associate<BR>
Biological Sciences Department <BR>
Stanford University <BR>
Stanford, CA 94305 USA <BR>
TEL: +1 415 725 1853, FAX: +1 415 723 5920 / 493 2092 <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:aehrlich@leland.stanford.edu">aehrlich@leland.stanford.edu</A><BR>
<BR>
Bede Okigbo, Director, Institute for Natural Resources in Africa, United
Nations University, Ghana<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Local organizers: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Hans van Baren, International Soil Reference and Information Centre (ISRIC),<BR>
Postbus 353, 6700 AJ Wageningen, Nederland <BR>
TEL: +31 317 420 042 / 471 711, FAX: +31 317 471 700<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:soil@isric.nl">soil@isric.nl</A><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Topics:</STRONG> 
<UL>
  <LI>Soil losses and soil regeneration 
  <LI>Integrated eco-agriculture 
  <LI>Phosphate and nitrogen budgets 
  <LI>Pesticide and heavy-metal pollution 
  <LI>Food additives and conservation techniques 
</UL>
<STRONG>Introduction:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
The workshop will cover many topics related to designing and developing
sustainable agricultural systems, including preventing soil erosion and
restoring degraded farmlands. Developing farming methods that make use of
the natural cycling of essential nutrients, especially nitrogen and phosphorus,
and the pest-control services of ecosystems will be a theme, where feasible
buiding on traditional farming systems. The importance of maintaining elements
of natural ecosystems in an agricultural landscape will be included. Avoidance
of pollution from pesticides and excessive synthetic fertilizers will be
considered, as will finding cultivation methods that minimize greenhouse
gas emissions (especially N2O and CH4). Sustainable fisheries management
and conservation will be discussed, and the roles of pollution and coastal
develoment in damaging fish populations. Alternative methods of food processing,
the benefits and environmental or health costs of food additives will be
investigated as well. The human food production system is a major component
of the human predicament; its importance in making a successful transition
to a sustainable world would be hard to overstate. Not least of the challenges
humanity faces will be continuing to increase production to accommodate
the expected several billion more people in the next half-century, while
making the system sustainable.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1463063"></A><STRONG>Programme:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Invited speakers:<BR>
<BR>
Bede Okigbo<BR>
<BR>
Rattan Lal, Professor of soil science, Ohio State University, U.S.A. (<A HREF="ws26/lal.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Martha Rosemeyer, Adjunct professor, Cornell University, USA; ecological<BR>
agriculture specialist in Latin American farming systems. (<A HREF="ws26/rosemeyer.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
In addition the following papers will be presented:<BR>
<BR>
Strategies and visions for ecologically adapted agricultural systems (<A HREF="ws26/ohlander.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
Lars Ohlander, Charlotte Lagerberg and Ulla Gertsson<BR>
<BR>
Population development - environmental relations (<A HREF="ws26/lechuga.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
Miguel Lechuga and Olga Lopez<BR>
<BR>
Human potential, livelihood security and anthropogenic stress: challenges
of <BR>
sustainability in India (<A HREF="ws26/singh.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
R.B.Singh<BR>
<BR>
Ecological animal breeding: An approach to holistic criteria (<A HREF="ws26/mathes.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
Maite Mathes<BR>
<BR>
