<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Management of water and waste water</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>2.7 Management of water and waste water</H2>
<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor4489844">The programme can be found below</A>.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Wlodzimierz Wojcik, Professor<BR>
Department of Environmental Protection and Management<BR>
Academy of Mining and Metallurgy <BR>
Al. A. Mickiewicza 30, 30-059 Krak&ograve;w, Polska<BR>
TEL: +48 12 172 260 / 557 152, <BR>
FAX: +48 12 331 014 / 330 717<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:wwojcik@uci.agh.edu.pl">wwojcik@uci.agh.edu.pl</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Fritz H. Frimmel, Lehrstuhl f&uuml;r Wasserchemie, Engler Bunte Institut<BR>
Richard Willst&auml;tter Allee 5, 76131 Karlsruhe, Deutschland<BR>
TEL: +49 721 608 2580, FAX: +49 721 699 154<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Local organizer:</STRONG> <BR>
<BR>
Rob Leuven<BR>
Vakgroep Milieukunde FWN<BR>
Katholieke Universiteit Nijmegen<BR>
Postbus 9010, 6500 GL Nijmegen<BR>
TEL: +31 24 356 3391 / 365 2096, FAX: +31 24 365 3030<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:rleuven@sci.kun.nl">rleuven@sci.kun.nl</A><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Topics: </STRONG>
<UL>
  <LI>Self-supporting water and sewage systems 
  <LI>Technologies for sustainable water management 
  <LI>Reduction of water use 
  <LI>Trans-boundary water conflicts 
  <LI>Recovery of resources from water 
</UL>
<STRONG>Introduction:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
The limited resource of clean water is one of the most critical constraints
on the survival of our civilization. In the workshop, evaluation of available
technologies and scientific tools for sustainable water management should
give a good foundation for addressing optimal technical, financial, organizational
and legal solutions. There is no doubt that water must be used in a more
rational way and existing methods of reduction of water use should be implemented
broadly as soon as possible - particularly in developed countries.<BR>
<BR>
Every use of water causes degradation of its quality, therefore the proper
approach is stimulation of changes of technologies for decreasing waste-water
production instead of an &quot;end of the pipe&quot; approach to waste-water
treatment. Since there is no totally clean technology available, the problem
of efficient methods of waste-water treatment should be addressed to include
recovery of resources. Technical and scientific tools cannot be implemented
without a proper legal and organisational framework. This framework should
help to encourage self-supporting water supply and sewerage systems under
conditions of competition and open market rules. Adoption of these open
market rules is not easy in this field, due to the usual monopoly of water
supply and sewerage systems, and therefore some form of public control should
be designed.<BR>
<BR>
One of the most critical problems in sustainable water management on a larger
scale is trans-boundary water conflicts which are seen in every part of
the world. These conflicts have very often impacts on peace-building, too.
The workshop will give an opportunity to discuss general approaches, and
hopefully some cases of trans-boundary water conflicts. However it is not
planned that the workshop will be a place for direct negotation of existing
conflicts.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor4489844"></A><STRONG>Programme:</STRONG>
<PRE>Friday Aug. 23

9:00-9:20	Meeting of the convenors and speakers.
		Discussion of organizational issues
