<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Transportation and mobility</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>3.1 Transportation and mobility</H2>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Bengt Mansson, Professor,<BR>
Umweltforschungszentrum Leipzig <BR>
Permoserstr. 15, 04318 Leipzig, Deutschland<BR>
TEL: +49 341 235 2686, FAX: +49 341 235 2511<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:mansson@alok.ufz.de">mansson@alok.ufz.de</A> <BR>
<BR>
Ogunlade Davidson, Professor and Head of the Department<BR>
Department of Mechanical Engineering <BR>
University of Sierra Leone <BR>
Freetown, Sierra Leone <BR>
TEL: +232 22 226 325 / 226 786, FAX: +232 22 224 439 <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Topics:</STRONG> 
<UL>
  <LI>Mobility as an expression of economic need, individual freedom or
addiction. 
  <LI>Future transportation technology 
  <LI>Minimizing of transport by regional planning and management 
  <LI>Alternatives to the automobile 
</UL>
<STRONG>Goals:<BR>
</STRONG><BR>
The primary scientific goal is to illuminate the problematique of sustainability
of urban transportation systems, including the relationships of urban conglomerates
with their surrounding regions. This problematique will be discussed both
from social, economic and technical points of view, with the aim of identifying
major research lacunae as well as important achievements. However, the workshop
does not aim at purely theoretical analysis, but will have a strong emphasis<BR>
on operationalization. In praticular, steps in the direction of sustainability
that may be taken in the near future should be a main focus of the discussion.<BR>
<BR>
Another goal is to lay the groundwork for new research/policy networks,
e.g. by establishing contacts and identifying common research interests.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Methods:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
The first part of the workshop will be spent on short presentations of invited
and contributed papers. Then follows a session in which the other participants
introduce themselves and briefly (possibly only with a couple of keywords)
describe their research activities and interests. Next comes a short brainstorming
session, aiming for a list of subjects, one or two of which will be chosen
for final closing discussion.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor206250"></A><STRONG>Programme:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Friday, 23 August 09.30 - 13.00<BR>
<BR>
Professor Ogunlade Davidson, University of Sierra Leone, Freetown, Sierra
Leone:<BR>
Sustainable Transport options for African Countries. (<A HREF="ws31/davidson.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Dr. Karel Mulder, Delft Univ. of Technology, Netherlands:<BR>
Expert opinions on the future prospect for external sources of vehicle<BR>
propulsion (<A HREF="ws31/mulder.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Rob Kemmeren, Netherlands<BR>
Subsidization of parking space in the Netherlands (<A HREF="ws31/kemmeren.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Stefan Bratzel, Freie Universit&auml;t Berlin, Germany:<BR>
Integrated Mobility Management in Berlin (<A HREF="ws31/bratzel.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Brainstorming session<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Friday, 23 August 14.30 - 18.00<BR>
<BR>
Excursion<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Saturday, 24 August 09.30 - 13.00<BR>
<BR>
Dr. Bengt M&aring;nsson, Centre for Environmental Research Leipzig/Halle,
Germany:<BR>
Rapid Personal Transit: A Mobility Option in Sustainable Cities?<BR>
<BR>
Final discussion<BR>
<BR>
