<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Telecommunications and sustainability</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>3.2 Telecommunications and sustainability</H2>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenor: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Juergen Malley<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:j.malley@t-online.de">j.malley@t-online.de</A><BR>
<BR>
This workshop is organized in collaboration with the <A HREF="http://unep.frw.uva.nl/">UNEP-
Working Group on Sustainable Product Development</A> (UNEP-WG-SPD, Amsterdam)<BR>
TEL: +31 20 525 6268, FAX: +31 20 625 8843, <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:unep@unep.frw.uva.nl">unep@unep.frw.uva.nl</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor16730103">Programme</A> is below.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Description:</B><BR>
<BR>
A deep structural change towards an information society is under way. Information
and Communication Technology (ICT) by itself is neither good nor bad; its
potential benefits or harms, respectively, depend strongly on the societal
and individual framework under which ICT is<BR>
used. To achieve progress toward a sustainable information society, the
different ascpectof sustainable development, i.e. social, economic, and
ecological, must be integrated.<BR>
<BR>
ICT will be discussed in the light of the following questions:<BR>
<BR>
1) What are the most significant environmental, economic and social-impact
potentials within the fast developing ICT-sector?<BR>
2) Which positive and negative impacts on all of the other economic sectors,
on social behaviour, and on the overall environmental impact potential are
obvious or to be expected?<BR>
3) Which recommendations for environmentally, socially and economically
sustainable applications of ICT can be given, and which especially unsafe
or harmful applications can be identified?<BR>
<BR>
Answers to these questions will require a wide-angle approach; global impacts
require broad global and life-cycle oriented analysis. Special attention
will be given as to how ICT can contribute to sustainable development in
developing countries.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor16730103"></A><B>Programme:</B> 
<PRE>Friday 23 August
10.15 - 18.00 hrs.

