<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Confronting unequal development</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>3.4 Confronting unequal development</H2>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Ana Maria Cetto, Professor of theoretical physics,<BR>
Instituto de F&iacute;sica<BR>
Universidad Nacional Aut&ograve;noma de M&eacute;xico<BR>
Apartado postal 20 - 364, 01000 M&eacute;xico D.F., M&eacute;xico <BR>
TEL: +52 5 548 9783 / 622 5014 / 658 7528, FAX: +52 5 616 1535 / 658 7528<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:ana@sysul1.ifisicacu.unam.mx%20%20">ana@sysul1.ifisicacu.unam.mx
</A><BR>
<BR>
Marc Ollivier, CNRS/ISMEA, France<BR>
CNRS/ISMEA, France<BR>
Les Arnauds, 38220 St Jean de Vaulx, France<BR>
TEL/FAX: +33 76 731 235, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:marc@criss.fr">marc@criss.fr</A><BR>
<BR>
<HR><STRONG>Topics:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
This workshop has been designed as a special meeting of <A HREF="http://www-com.grenet.fr/inesdev">INESDEV,
the INES international working group on unequal development problems</A>.
Links between unequal development processes and threats to sustainability
will be discussed from an interdisciplinary point of view and on the basis
of concrete experiences.<BR>
<BR>
It is not a Third-World workshop, insofar as unequal development problems
are expressing a global and consistent process: they are spreading out all
over the world, between and within industrialized and developing countries,
with various local and regional specificities and responsibilities.<BR>
<BR>
Participants at the workshop will contribute by addressing the following
questions: Why is unequal development becoming a world wide challenge? What
are the processes leading to this situation? To what extent are science
and technology involved in these processes? What are the reponsibilities
of engineers and scientists in helping to find new ways to deal with them?<BR>
<BR>
The results of the workshop will be appropriately published and disseminated.
As guidelines for the debate, the workshop convenors suggest to present
the papers and contributions according to four main topics: 
<UL>
  <LI>Economical aspects: effects of economic and financial practices, IMF
and IBRD rules and actions, debt burden, unequal distribution of income
and wealth, tax havens, privatization. 
  <LI>Social aspects: labour organization and unemployment, health, social
security and educational systems, migrations, rural decline and overcrowding
of urban areas. 
  <LI>Military and political factors: political instabilities, military
expenditure and its uses, role of dictatorships and human-rights violations,
organized responses of the population. 
  <LI>The knowledge system and the environment: management of natural and
human resources, use/misuse of old and new technologies. 
</UL>
<STRONG>Invited speaker:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Jorge Bula, Lecturer of economic sciences, Universidad Nacional de Colombia<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Programme:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
There is no programme available yet but papers from the following are up
for presentation:<BR>
<BR>
Marc Ollivier, CNRS/ISMEA (<A HREF="ws34/ollivier.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
Ana Maria Cetto, Instituto de F&iacute;sica, Universidad Nacional Aut&ograve;noma
de M&eacute;xico (<A HREF="ws34/cetto.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
Abraham Serfaty (<A HREF="ws34/serfaty.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Other papers are presented on the <A HREF="http://www-com.grenet.fr/inesdev">INESDEV,
the INES international working group on unequal development problems</A>,
home page (http://www-com.grenet.fr/inesdev).<BR>
<BR>
