<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: The politics of sustainability</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>3.5 The politics of sustainability: Challenges to democracy</H2>
Workshop, August 23rd and 24th, 1996 in Amsterdam (9 hours)<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor10311622">The programme can be found below</A>.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Elmar Altvater, Professor of political sciences<BR>
Freie Universit&auml;t Berlin, Fachbereich 15<BR>
Ihnestr. 21, 14195 Berlin, Deutschland <BR>
TEL: +49 30 838 4965, FAX: +49 30 838 4160<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:prokla@ipn-b.comlink.apc.org">prokla@ipn-b.comlink.apc.org</A>
<BR>
<BR>
Annegret Falter, political scientist, executive secretary of the Vereinigung
Deutscher Wissenschaftler, <BR>
Sybelstr. 6, 1000 Berlin 12, Deutschland <BR>
TEL: +49 30 324 7865<BR>
<BR>
Iftikh&aacute;r Ahmad,<BR>
Sustainable Development Policy Institute SDPI<BR>
P.O. Box 2342, Islamabad, Pakistan<BR>
TEL: +92 51 218 134, FAX: +92 51 218 135<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:iftikhar@sdpi.sdnpk.undp.org">iftikhar@sdpi.sdnpk.undp.org</A><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Topics:</STRONG> <BR>
<BR>
Democratic systems tend to be stable as long as the economy grows and the
<BR>
per capita income remains on a high level. It is, though, an ecological
common<BR>
place, that not everybody in the world can share or reach the material wealth
of <BR>
the rich industrial societies. The global environmental space is limited;
it <BR>
cannot be extended. Industrial wealth is a positional good. Does that mean<BR>
that democracy is a luxury good of the rich and that poorer societies have
to<BR>
be submitted to authoritarian regimes? How should democratic<BR>
participation be organized, which institutional forms and new incentives<BR>
are conceivable to dissolve the &quot;linkage&quot; of welfare and formal<BR>
democracy? Is it possible at all that ecological issues gain recognition<BR>
and acceptance, as long as the dominant model of development gives top<BR>
priority to material welfare?<BR>
<BR>
UNDP brought attention to the fact that since the Sixties the distance<BR>
between the poorest and the richest 20% of the world population has<BR>
grown from 1:30 to 1: 61, thus more than doubled. IMF arrives at similar<BR>
conclusions. As long as this unequal distribution persists or grows even<BR>
further, democracy as a societal form of participation may be possible<BR>
on a local, regional or national level for some more time - but not<BR>
everywhere and not on the global level. As mankind is increasingly<BR>
confronted with ecological problems and &quot;sustainability&quot; needs
to be<BR>
globally moulded, new forms of material equity and political<BR>
participation must be arranged for decisions on the local, regional and<BR>
local level as well as for those of global reach. Democracy has also to<BR>
become a principle of the global order and global &quot;governance&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
How could this, and how could equal access to the global environmental<BR>
space be obtained considering monetary unequality? Which political<BR>
institutional mechanisms exist to control the economic powers of the<BR>
world market as a precondition of sustainability? The challenges which<BR>
the economics of sustainability creates for democracy may be split up<BR>
in a series of interrelated questions:<BR>
<BR>
1. How can the inevitable future reduction (instead of the past<BR>
expansion) in the consumption and use of environmental goods be arranged<BR>
under democratic conditions? How can authoritarian solutions be excluded?<BR>
<BR>
2. So far, democratic participation is mostly confined to the national,<BR>
regional and local level. There, with the diminishing capacity of the<BR>
welfare state in the North and an increasing shortage of the<BR>
environmental space worldwide, we are confronting an erosion of the<BR>
rights and the readiness for participation. How can these rights be<BR>
upheld, respectively be restituted?<BR>
<BR>
3. The Industrial Relations between capital and labour have been, in the<BR>
past, basically a growth coalition. How do these relations have to be<BR>
reorganized, when the basis of the coalition, continuous growth and<BR>
redistribution of the GNP, gets under ecological pressure?<BR>
<BR>
4. &quot;Sustainability&quot; needs decentralization and, at the same time,<BR>
centralized, globally effective decisions and regimes. What does this<BR>
antagonism mean for democracy, theoretically and empirically? How can<BR>
democratic legitimacy be extended in both directions? E.g:<BR>
<BR>
5. How do existing international institutions such as the World Bank,<BR>
IMF, WTO, have to be organized to be in accordance with principles of<BR>
democracy and sustainability?<BR>
<BR>
6. What is, what could be, the role of NGOs in the process of shaping a<BR>
global regime of sustainability? Are the emerging networks of NGOs a<BR>
factor of constituting global governance, and what kind of relationship<BR>
between them and formal political institutions should be established?<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The following broad topics will be discussed: 
<UL>
  <LI>Democratic feasibility of sustainability; 
  <LI>Chances of popular participation; 
  <LI>Impact of sustainability on industrial relations; 
  <LI>International governance with special regard to IMF, WB etc; 
  <LI>International governance: the role of NGOs. 
</UL>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor10311622"></A><STRONG>Programme</STRONG> 
<PRE>Friday, August 23, 9.30-13.00

