<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Peaceful resolution of conflicts</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>4.1 Peaceful resolution of social, ethno-national and environmental
conflicts</H2>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Norbert Ropers, Executive Director, <BR>
Berghof Stiftung,<BR>
Berghof Research Centre for Constructive Conflict Management<BR>
Altensteinstr. 48a, 14195 Berlin, Deutschland <BR>
TEL: +49 30 831 8090, FAX: +49 30 831 5985<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:berghof@ipn-b.comlink.apc.org">berghof@ipn-b.comlink.apc.org</A>
<BR>
<BR>
Valerij Tishkov, <BR>
Institute of Ethnology and Anthropology, <BR>
Russian Academy of Sciences,<BR>
Leninski prospect 32-a, Moskwa 117334, Rossia<BR>
TEL: +7 095 938 1747, FAX: +7 095 939 O600,<BR>
TEL/FAX: +7 095 938 0043<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:anthpub@iea.msk.su%20">anthpub@iea.msk.su </A><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Topics:</STRONG> 
<UL>
  <LI>Challenges of new internal ethno-political conflicts 
  <LI>Ethnicity and nationalism 
  <LI>Conflict resolution in the realm of states and societies 
  <LI>Peace keeping, peace making and peace building in the UN system 
  <LI>Power Sharing in multi-ethnic states as a method of conflict resolution
  <LI>Interactive Conflict Resolution of deep-rooted conflicts 
</UL>
<STRONG>Introduction:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
The growing number of social, ethno-national and environmental conflicts<BR>
influences all the major development issues in the world, including<BR>
market reforms in the post-communist world, overcoming poverty and<BR>
inequality in less developed countries as well as more integration and<BR>
sustainable development in the western world. Because of the different<BR>
nature of these conflicts (lack and unequal distribution of resources<BR>
and wealth, power asymmetries, suppression of cultures, patterns of<BR>
industrial development etc.) diffe rent strategies and mechanisms for<BR>
conflict resolution should be developed. The workshop aims at dealing<BR>
with some of the core challenges in this respect.<BR>
<BR>
The first session on Friday morning will be devoted to a general<BR>
overview of basic trends of conflict, on the relations between conflict<BR>
resolution and development and on the importance of time and space in<BR>
the peaceful transformation of conflicts. The second session on Friday<BR>
afternoon will deal with practical approaches and experiences in<BR>
conflict management and minority issues. It will be based on<BR>
introductions by representatives from the &quot;High Commissioner on National<BR>
Minorities of the OSCE&quot; and the &quot;Foundation on Inter-Ethnic Relations&quot;<BR>
in The Hague. The third session will concentrate on the challenges of<BR>
ethnopolitical conflicts and their resolution in the post-Soviet states,<BR>
in Central Asia and South Asia. <BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Programme:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Friday, 23 August, 9.30 - 13.00<BR>
Chairperson:Valery Tishkov<BR>
<BR>
Dan Smith, Director, Peace Research Institute Oslo<BR>
The world map of conflicts<BR>
<BR>
Rudolfo Stavenhagen, Professor sociology, El Colegio de M&eacute;xico <BR>
Conflict resolution and development<BR>
<BR>
Norbert Ropers <BR>
Time and space in conflict transformation<BR>
<BR>
Friday, 23 August, 14.30 - 18.00<BR>
Chairperson:Valery Tishkov<BR>
<BR>
Frans Timmermans, Charge d'Affaires, The High Commissioner on National Minorities
of the OSCE, The Hague, and Jonathan Cohen, The foundation of Inter-Ethnic
Relations, The Hague<BR>
Practical approaches and experiences in conflict management and minority
issues<BR>
<BR>
Saturday, 24 August, 9.30 - 13.00<BR>
Chairperson: Norbert Ropers<BR>
<BR>
Valery Tishkov<BR>
Prospects for conflict resolution in the Soviet successor states <BR>
<BR>
Ainura Elebaeva, Professor of ethnology, Academy of Sciences of Kirgizia,
Bishkek <BR>
Inter-ethnic conflicts in Soviet successor states of Central Asia<BR>
<BR>
Neelan Thiruchelvam, Director, International Centre for Ethnic Studies,<BR>
Colombo, Sri Lanka<BR>
Peaceful resolution of ethno-national conflicts and conflict relating to
resources<BR>
