<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Nuclear weapons and nuclear waste</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>4.2 Nuclear weapons abolition and nuclear waste storage</H2>
<P><CENTER><IMG SRC="../../images/newred.gif" WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="13" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3">  <STRONG><A HREF="ws42/report42.html">Conclusions
of Workshop</A>  </STRONG><IMG SRC="../../images/newred.gif" WIDTH="32"
HEIGHT="13" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER>
<P><STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
David Krieger, lawyer, President <BR>
Nuclear Age Peace Foundation <BR>
1187 Coast Village Road, Suite # 123, Santa Barbara CA 93108, USA <BR>
TEL: +1 805 965 3443, FAX: +1 805 568 0466<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:napf@igc.apc.org">napf@igc.apc.org</A><BR>
<BR>
Wolfgang Liebert, physicist, assistant of the IANUS Group, <BR>
IANUS, c/o Institut f&Uuml;r Kernphysik <BR>
Technische Hochschule Darmstadt <BR>
Schlo&szlig;gartenstr. 9, 64289 Darmstadt, Deutschland <BR>
TEL: +49 6151 163 016, +49 69 335 615, FAX: +49 6151 164 321<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:liebert@hrzpub.th-darmstadt.de">liebert@hrzpub.th-darmstadt.de</A>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Vladimir Yakomets, <BR>
Centre of Arms Control, Energy and Environmental Studies<BR>
Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology<BR>
Institutsky per 9, 141700, Dolgoprudny, Moskwa area, Russia<BR>
TEL: +7 095 552 8512, FAX: +7 095 408 4477<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Topics:</STRONG> 
<UL>
  <LI>Steps towards a nuclear weapon free world 
  <LI>Reactor safety 
  <LI>Treatment of nuclear waste 
</UL>
<STRONG>Introduction:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
This workshop will examine two of the key issues of our time. Participants<BR>
will report on the momentum that has been created toward a nuclear weapons<BR>
free world. This will include reports on the World Court decision on the<BR>
illegality of nuclear weapons, and the work of the Abolition 2000 Network,<BR>
including the drafting of a Nuclear Weapons Convention, and campaigns to<BR>
involve citizen participation throughout the world. There will also be<BR>
discussion of the international efforts for a Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty,<BR>
a Fissile Material Cut-off Treaty, a No First Use Agreement, as well as<BR>
other measures to achieve the goal of a commitment by the nuclear weapons<BR>
states by the year 2000 to the total abolition of nuclear arsenals. <BR>
<BR>
The workshop will also examine the available options for disposing of<BR>
nuclear wastes, and the needed international actions to reduce the<BR>
proliferation as well as environmental and health hazards of nuclear waste<BR>
storage to present and future generations.<BR>
<BR>
Among the participants in the workshop will be Professor Joseph<BR>
Rotblat, the 1995 Nobel Peace Laureate.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor515837"></A><STRONG>Programme:</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
The following are up for presentation:<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
David Krieger, Nuclear Age Peace Foundation, Abolition 2000: lessons of
the past year (<A HREF="ws42/krieger.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
David Krieger, Nuclear Age Peace Foundation, Ridding the world of nuclear
weapons (<A HREF="ws42/silva.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Carlota Lopes da Silva, Women's International League for Peace and Freedom
(WILPF), Nuclear weapons/energy versus security (<A HREF="ws42/krieger2.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Boris Golubov, Russian Academy of Sciences, The ecological outcomes of the
underground nuclear explosions and problems of sustainable development (<A HREF="ws42/golubov.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
