<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Conventional disarmament and conversion</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>4.4 Conventional disarmament and conversion of military resources and
production</H2>
<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Convenors: <BR>
</STRONG><BR>
Martin Grundmann (Germany)<BR>
Schleswig-Holstein Institute for Peace Research (SHIP)<BR>
University of Kiel<BR>
Kaiserstr. 2 (Geb. B), 24143 Kiel, Deutschland<BR>
TEL: +49 431 14357, FAX: +49 431 77572<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:grundmann@schiff.uni-kiel.d400.de">grundmann@schiff.uni-kiel.d400.de</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Henny van der Graaf, , Brigardier-General (ret.), Director, <BR>
Centre for Arms Control and Verification Technology <BR>
Technical University Eindhoven<BR>
Garonnelaan 15, 5627 VW Eindhoven, Nederland <BR>
TEL: +31 40 262 2704, +31 40 247 3485, <BR>
FAX: +31 40 262 4644, +31 40 244 7035<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:h.j.v.d.graaf@phys.tue.ne">h.j.v.d.graaf@phys.tue.ne</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Esmat Ezz, chemist, Colonel (ret.), <BR>
34 Talat Harb Street, Apt 16, Cairo, Egypt <BR>
TEL: +202 575 5668 / 350 5899, FAX: +202 775 914<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The aim of the workshop is to discuss the interconnection of conventional
disarmament and economic and social conditions.The subject matter can be
divided into two main categories: conventional disarmament, and the conversion
of military resources and production.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>I. Conventional disarmament</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Conventional arms control<BR>
<BR>
One of the first topics to discuss is how to bring small arms back under<BR>
the authority of states functioning through democratic rules. Another<BR>
task for the workshop is to devise ways and means to halt the<BR>
proliferation of conventional (small) arms through effective and<BR>
practical preventive actions such as, on the political side, the<BR>
integration of security and development in order to create better<BR>
conditions for effective arms control and disarmament of conventional<BR>
weaponry.<BR>
<BR>
A second aspect is the relationship between small arms and intra-state<BR>
conflict. The problems related to excessive proliferation of small arms<BR>
in various trouble spots in the world are daunting. Overcapacities and<BR>
surplus equipment in industrialized countries are increasingly feeding<BR>
arms markets in the developing world. National programmes for arms<BR>
collection are badly needed. In an increasing number of developing<BR>
countries economic and social development has come to an end as a result<BR>
of the unstable security situation. There is a recurring coincidence<BR>
between overabundance of small arms and the outbreak of intra-state<BR>
conflicts.<BR>
<BR>
Since the international community is becoming increasingly involved in<BR>
intra-state conflicts and small arms are not covered by traditional arms<BR>
control considerations and agreements, time is ripe to develop a package<BR>
of practical arms control measures for small arms.<BR>
<BR>
Demobilization and reintegration of combattants<BR>
<BR>
The second topic the workshop will address, under the heading of<BR>
disarmament, is the issue of demobilization and reintegration of former<BR>
combattants once a civil war has ended. This issue is one of the most<BR>
urgent problems in those countries where civil war is raging. A number<BR>
of problems are apparent: 
<UL>
  <LI>the process of demobilization has to be organized; 
  <LI>national institutions - as far as they still exist - have to be<BR>
supported by international organizations; 
  <LI>control and transparency of the process has to be ensured; 
  <LI>weapon collection programmes have to be organized; 
  <LI>reintegration needs infrastructure that often has to be built up;
  <LI>vocational and technical training has to be organized; 
  <LI>civil jobs are needed; 
  <LI>medical care and psychological support is necessary; 
  <LI>child-soldiers need special help. 
</UL>
Successful demobilization and reintegration is one of the main conditions<BR>
for peaceful development and the installation of a new national/regional<BR>
order of security and stability. If reintegration fails, there is the danger<BR>
of the war starting again. The workshop will discuss these problems.<BR>
<BR>
The workshop will also deal with the problem of landmines, in particular<BR>
anti-personnel mines, one of the cruellest weapons used in intra-state<BR>
conflict, causing hundreds of casualties every day, in particular children,<BR>
even long after the end of hostilities. The workshop will discuss<BR>
possibilities for a global ban on landmines including measures for non<BR>
circumvention. Also the problem of mine clearance will be addressed.<BR>
<BR>
<B>II. Conversion</B><BR>
<BR>
In this context the workshop will discuss problems related to conversion
of<BR>
military capabilities to peaceful uses. The underlying hypothesis is that<BR>
conversion of arms production and of military facilities and personnel is<BR>
dependent on the political will for conventional disarmament, and that at<BR>
the same time the political will for disarmament is supported by conversion<BR>
that is successful in economic and social terms.<BR>
<BR>
The interdependence of conventional disarmament and conversion is on the<BR>
political agenda of the new Europe. It is seen as one of the most<BR>
significant aspects of peace-oriented development. Europe is one of the<BR>
main producers of conventional weapons. Especially in Central and<BR>
Eastern Europe conventional disarmament and conversion is a problem of<BR>
economic and social development. The idea of disarmament and conversion<BR>
has to compete with arms production and sales all over the world. A<BR>
related problem, at least in Central European countries, are newly<BR>
defined concepts of national security where national arms industries<BR>
play a major role.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor236576"></A><B>List of issues to be addressed in the workshop
by invited contributors:</B><BR>
<BR>
Swadesh Rana: Small arms and intra-state conflict<BR>
<BR>
Henny van der Graaf: The proliferation of light weapons and intra-state<BR>
conflict: a case study<BR>
<BR>
Patrick Blagden: The landmine legacy and its effects<BR>
<BR>
Sverre Lodgaard: Managing arms in peace processes<BR>
<BR>
Kees Kingma: Demobilization of soldiers after civil wars and their<BR>
reintegration into civil life<BR>
<BR>
Peter Lock: Conventional disarmament, arms exports and conversion in<BR>
Russia/CEE (<A HREF="ws44/lock.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
Igors Tipans: Conventional disarmament and conversion in the Baltic<BR>
states<BR>
<BR>
Lars Eric Ballugi: Case study on conversion of a Russian arms producer<BR>
<BR>
Roland Vogt: Possibilities of the civilian reuse of large military<BR>
facilities (<A HREF="ws44/vogt.html">abstract</A>)<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>About the convenors and the speakers:</B><BR>
<BR>
Martin Grundmann, Senior Researcher, Schleswig-Holstein Institute for<BR>
Peace Research at the University of Kiel (SHIP)<BR>
<BR>
Henny van der Graaf, Brigadier-General (ret.), Member of the UN Advisory<BR>
Board for Disarmament Affairs, Director of the Centre for Arms Control<BR>
and Verifcation Technology at Technical University of Eindhoven<BR>
<BR>
Esmat Ezz, Member of the Board of INES<BR>
<BR>
Swadesh Rana, Senior Political Affairs Officer of UN Centre for<BR>
Disarmament Affairs<BR>
<BR>
Patrick Blagden was Senior Advisor on Mine Clearance of UN Department of<BR>
Peace Keeping and Operation (1992-95)<BR>
<BR>
Sverre Lodgaard, Director of UNIDIR, Geneva<BR>
<BR>
Kees Kingma, Researcher, Project Leader of Demobilization Projects, Bonn<BR>
International Center for Conversion, Bonn<BR>
<BR>
Peter Lock, Director, European Association for Research on Transformation,<BR>
Hamburg/Moscow<BR>
<BR>
Igors Tipans, Director, Baltic International Centre for Human Education,<BR>
Technical University of Riga <BR>
<BR>
Lars Eric Ballugi, Swedish Engineers, Economists and Scientists for<BR>
Conversion, Grythyttan<BR>
<BR>
Roland Vogt, Head of Department for Conversion, Ministry of Economy of<BR>
the State of Brandenburg; Network Demilitarized of the European Union<BR>
<BR>
