    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Workshop 1.1 abstracts</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Workshop 1.1 abstracts</H2>
<BR>
THE FOLLOWING IS A COMPLETE LIST OF THE ABSTRACTS FOR POSTER PRESENTATIONS
AND PAPERS FOR WS 1.1 AMSTERDAM CONFERENCE AS OF JULY 1, 96.<BR>
<BR>
POSTER PRESENTATIONS<BR>
<BR>
Linas Kliucininkas (Poster)<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1117997">GIS Based Planning of Protected Areas Development
in South West Lithuania</A><BR>
<BR>
Tian Xiang Yue, et al. (Poster)<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1164379">Models for landscape dynamics and their application</A><BR>
<BR>
ABSTRACTS FOR WORKSHOP 1.1<BR>
<BR>
Robert Berloznik,<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1124885">Sustainable development research: challenges to
science policy</A><BR>
<BR>
R.B. Jain,<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1130375">Ethical foundations of sustainable development:
an Indian perspective</A><BR>
<BR>
Andreas Metzner,<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1136725">Ecological-Social Conditions of Ethical Behavior</A><BR>
<BR>
J. Scheffran,<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1155491">Sustainable development and peace</A><BR>
<BR>
Ian F. Voges,<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1172088">Justice, sustainability and corporate management
in developing countries</A><BR>
<BR>
Tom Draisma,<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1126847">The ecological consequences of mining in developing
countries</A><BR>
<BR>
Philemon Mukendi,<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1142237">Techno-science and nature</A><BR>
<BR>
Peter Klein,<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1133295">Sustainability and the Morally Good</A><BR>
<BR>
Lars Ryd&eacute;n,<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1148300">The Concept of Sustainability in the contemporary
debate on development</A><BR>
<BR>
Guillermo Lemarchand,<BR>
<A HREF="#anchor1103959">Ethical Principles and Normative Models of Sustainable
Development</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1124885"></A>1. BERLOZNIK, MOL<BR>
<BR>
Sustainable development research: challenges to science policy<BR>
Robert Berloznik, Advisor for Technology Assessment,<BR>
Flemish Institute for Technological Research,<BR>
Boeretang 200, 2400 Mol, Belgium<BR>
TEL: +32 14 33 55 53, FAX: +32 14 33 55 99, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:berloznr@vito.be">berloznr@vito.be</A><BR>
<BR>
The Commission on Sustainable Development in its 1995 meeting<BR>
leaves no doubt about the importance of science for sustainable<BR>
development: &quot;It is not a exaggeration to assert that without science<BR>
there can be no sustainable development.&quot; There is indeed a strong
emphasis<BR>
on the importance of the role of science and technology as instruments in<BR>
the implementation of Agenda 21. Therefore, the role of science in<BR>
establishing sustainable development is generally qualified as important,<BR>
as well by the research community as decision-makers. Little knowledge<BR>
however is available on how to use the instrument in such a way that<BR>
knowledge helps to pave the way for a sustainable society.<BR>
<BR>
This paper deals with the issue of science and science policy in respect<BR>
to sustainable development. It is based on a study commissioned by the<BR>
Belgian National Council for Sustainable Development in order to<BR>
formulate an advise on science and science organisation and sustainable<BR>
development, research options and a long term vision for research in<BR>
Belgium, given that the concept of sustainable development is accepted<BR>
as guideline for science policy.<BR>
<BR>
This research was done by a interdisciplinary team of researchers<BR>
from two research institutions, the Flemish Institution for<BR>
Technological Research (VITO, Mol) and the Foundation for Work and<BR>
Society (FTU, Namur) and was funded and co-ordinated by the Belgian<BR>
Science Policy Office. The members of the research team were: Robert<BR>
Berloznik, Dominiek Vancolen, Jan Van Rensbergen (all VITO), G&eacute;rard<BR>
Valenduc, Patricia Vendramin and Jean-Yves Marion (all FTU).}<BR>
<BR>
The objectives of the study are :<BR>
<BR>
- Analysis and synthesis of how the concept of sustainable development<BR>
is dealt with on the regional and the federal level in Belgium, in other<BR>
relevant countries and in international programmes ( EU, UN});<BR>
- Analysis of the needs and priorities of the Belgian civil society, the<BR>
scientific world and the policy makers concerning research on sustainable<BR>
development;<BR>
- Definition of research priorities, based on the concept of<BR>
sustainable development as well as on the ecological, the economic and<BR>
the socio-cultural system and the interactions between them.<BR>
- To provide recommendations and advice to the federal government<BR>
strategy to come to a policy based on the concept of sustainable<BR>
development. This also includes the identification of possible<BR>
obstacles.<BR>
<BR>
The research was conducted in three phases. During the first phase an<BR>
analysis was made of selected bibliographical material and a number of<BR>
international and national initiatives. In a second phase, the strong<BR>
and the weak points of the Belgian R\&amp;D system in respect to sustainable<BR>
development were analysed. Together with this, a consultation took place<BR>
with the &quot;civil society&quot; on the expectations of the different
societal<BR>
groups regarding the role of science in implementing sustainable<BR>
development. In the third phase of the study, conclusions and<BR>
recommendations were formulated on the orientation and organisation of<BR>
scientific research.<BR>
<BR>
This paper will first give a summary of the first and the second parts<BR>
of the study, to further go deeper into detail on the conclusions and<BR>
recommendations, focusing on the science policy aspects.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1126847"></A>2. DRAISMA, LEIDEN<BR>
<BR>
The ecological consequences of mining in developing<BR>
countries: of actors, ethics and environmental policy<BR>
<BR>
Tom Draisma<BR>
Institute for International Studies<BR>
Social Science Faculty, State University of Leiden,<BR>
P.O. Box 9555, 2300 RB Leiden, Nederland<BR>
Tel: +31 71 527 3411, +31 71 541 7800, Fax: +31 71 527 3619,<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:draisma@rulfsw.leidenuniv.nl">draisma@rulfsw.leidenuniv.nl</A><BR>
<BR>
Since the publication of the first Report to the Club of Rome (1972) the<BR>
mining of mineral resources, including oil and gas, has been discussed in<BR>
the perspective of dwindling reserves. Although that perspective has<BR>
remained important, especially for the rarer minerals, the initial alarm<BR>
has quieted. From the mid-1980s however, forms of environmental degradation<BR>
other than depletion, associated with mining activities are receiving<BR>
growing attention.<BR>
<BR>
In Western Europe the cost of making up for environmental damage and the<BR>
costs involved in controlling health risks and compensating for health<BR>
damage done, have, besides other factors, contributed to the closing of<BR>
large numbers of coal mines in EU member states.<BR>
<BR>
On an international scale, the rapid increase of coal-fuelled power plants,<BR>
both working and planned, and of oil-, gas- or petrol-fuelled automobiles<BR>
and aeroplanes is causing growing concern in view of their contribution
to<BR>
global warming and climate change. Nuclear energy based on uranium from<BR>
uranium mines have not fulfilled their erstwhile promise and the disposal<BR>
of radioactive waste has proved problematic. The cases mentioned in this<BR>
paragraph may be called indirect environmental effects of the preceding<BR>
mining operations, as opposed to direct environmental effects.<BR>
<BR>
In affluent Western countries the general public is aware of the dangers
to<BR>
human society posed by mining and the use of mining's end-products. A<BR>
multitude of action groups and non-governmental organisations combat<BR>
pollution and degradation, take companies to court, protect nature, and/or<BR>
advocate 'sustainable development,' 'selective growth,' and new lifestyles:<BR>
activities aimed at stopping what they believe to be humankind's suicidal<BR>
course.<BR>
<BR>
In the 'South', formerly called 'underdeveloped world,' the 'developing<BR>
countries' or the 'Third World,' the situation is quite different.<BR>
Confining ourselves to mining, it is safe to say that output is increasing<BR>
at an unprecedented scale. Most traditional mineral exporting countries
of<BR>
sub-Saharan Africa have by and large been unable to diversify their<BR>
economies to a great extent. World Bank and IMF advice to them has<BR>
been to cut down on social policy expenditures, minimize the civil service,<BR>
to privatise state corporations and parastatal companies, to stimulate<BR>
agriculture by payimg local farmers a fairer price and to increase<BR>
mineral and other exports, all this in order to get the government's<BR>
financial books in order. The situation of economic distress in many of<BR>
these countries hardly permits their governments to be very choosy when<BR>
attracting investment by transnational mining companies. Low world market<BR>
prices for most metalliferous minerals form a barrier to both better wages<BR>
for the miners and to protective measures aimed at reducing pollution and<BR>
degradation of the environment. The emphasis on market forces, the weakness<BR>
of many African governments and the laying off of government personnel<BR>
reduce rather than increase public control over the activities of foreign<BR>
companies.<BR>
<BR>
Other countries in the South, e.g. China and other aspiring NICs,<BR>
are embarking on ambitious industrialization schemes, the energy for which<BR>
they plan to generate in large numbers of new coal-fuelled power plants<BR>
whose output of carbon-dioxyde and other greenhouse gases will dwarf<BR>
reductions achieved in the older industrialized countries. Since the World<BR>
Conference on Environmental and Development (WCED) held at Rio de<BR>
Janeiro in 1992, and despite adverse conditions alluded to above, many<BR>
governments in the South have appointed a cabinet minister for the<BR>
environment, enacted laws, issued regulations, and appointed controlling<BR>
officers in order to improve the implementation of environmental policies.<BR>
<BR>
In this discussion paper the author seeks answers to the following questions:<BR>
<BR>
- What are the nature and the scale of environmental pollution and<BR>
degradation caused by the mining of solid minerals, oil and gas? Two cases<BR>
will be considered in particular: sub-Saharan Africa, and clashes between<BR>
mining companies on the one hand and unrepresented nations and peoples on<BR>
the other.<BR>
<BR>
- By what ethics may mining operations and their effects, direct and<BR>
indirect, on the environment be judged?<BR>
<BR>
- Who are the main actors in North and South in the mining field, and what<BR>
consequences for their operations could they possibly draw from ethical<BR>
guidelines as outlined?<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1130375"></A>3. JAIN, NEW DELHI<BR>
<BR>
Ethical foundations of sustainable development:<BR>
an Indian perspective<BR>
R.B. Jain<BR>
Professor of Political Science<BR>
University of Delhi<BR>
38 18 Probyn Road, Delhi-110007, India<BR>
TEL/FAX: +91 11 725 ,7472<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The spirit of sustainable development and environmental harmony has<BR>
been the recurring theme in the writings of the precepts of the<BR>
seers and sages in India, since the Vedic times. However, with constant<BR>
and unabated inroads of commercialisation and wastefulness, followed<BR>
later even by criminalisation of politics and the devaluation of<BR>
democratic norms, the ethical foundations of sustainable development<BR>
have been badly shaken. Sustainable development strongly reinforces<BR>
the attainment of quality in development efforts. It espouses pronounced<BR>
concern for accountability, ethics, morality, cultural moorings and ethos<BR>
as well as environmental stewardship.<BR>
<BR>
It is becoming increasingly clear that many of the values held by us<BR>
are totally inadequate for long-term survival and sustainable<BR>
development, that is why it is not surprising that we are witnessing<BR>
an emergence of a wide-spectrum of challenges to the traditional<BR>
materialistic view, and instead we find a growing interest in Hindu,<BR>
Buddhists and Jaina norms. All these represent a desire by many to<BR>
ascribe to a radically set of values. Without this change in our value<BR>
system, there is little hope of correcting the present environmental<BR>
problems that one faces today. Thus to save ourselves from our own past<BR>
mistakes, we have to change our attitudes, the way we think, value<BR>
and act towards the environment.<BR>
<BR>
The paper is a brief attempt to trace some of the ethical traditions,<BR>
embodied in various ancient Indian scriptures, which enjoin upon the human<BR>
beings to change their attitudes towards nature and realise our duties and<BR>
responsibilities towards nature, and in doing so understand the<BR>
benefit the concept of Dharma - the Indian principle of duty -<BR>
can have in helping us evolve a global perspective. Based on the<BR>
analyses of classical Indian perspective of sustainable development,<BR>
the paper suggests adoption of a universal code of conduct for<BR>
environmental conservation based on the Indian concept of<BR>
Manav Dharma (Global duty) and Vasudhaiv Kutumbakam<BR>
(the Earth as an extended family).<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1133295"></A>4. KLEIN, HAMBURG<BR>
<BR>
Sustainability and the Morally Good<BR>
Peter Klein<BR>
University of Hamburg, Faculty of Education, Von-Melle-Park 8, D-20146<BR>
Hamburg, Germany<BR>
tel. +49 40 4123 2151, fax +49 40 4123 2112<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Sustainable development&quot; means human action that is suitable
to the world<BR>
and to nature in such a way that the requirements of human welfare are<BR>
fulfilled without doing disastrous harm to the resources by which human<BR>
lives is sustained: &quot;Suitable&quot; action does &quot;justice&quot;
to both, man and<BR>
nature.<BR>
<BR>
It is the expression: the &quot;Idea of Suitability&quot; which Immanuel
Kant denotes<BR>
as the general guideline of human orientation in the world, that is given,<BR>
in contrast to mere accidental prerational motivations of human life, by<BR>
human reason, as the preeminent quality of Man as the very creature of<BR>
reason.<BR>
<BR>
The structure of reason, according to Kant, reads briefly like this: In<BR>
order to shape his life (instead of just running it unconsciously and by<BR>
chance), Man needs orientation in the world. Orientation aims for<BR>
knowledge, meaningful goals, and, as their intended result, for welfare.
So<BR>
reason is constituted by three basis components:<BR>
- systematic knowledge, rendered by cognition (the structure of which is<BR>
called &quot;pure cognition&quot;);<BR>
- a system of moral laws, rendered by postulates of &quot;practical reason&quot;;<BR>
- a system of criteria that balances knowledge and moral law in a way<BR>
that welfare of Man in the world may happen; this is rendered by &quot;power<BR>
of judgement&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
The latter must be added because both, cognition and morals, tend to set<BR>
themselves autonomously, thus exaggerating the range of their validity:<BR>
Isolated cognition, and it's action-oriented application, technology, tend<BR>
to turn laws of scientific knowledge about the world into senseless<BR>
products that may result in damage of the world as well as of Man making<BR>
use of them: this restraintless fundamentalism of cognition, that<BR>
Horkheimer and Adorna (in &quot;Eclipse of Reason&quot;) called &quot;instrumental<BR>
reason&quot;, nowadays is well known as the instrument of ecological crisis.<BR>
<BR>
Isolated moral systems tend to demand absolute obedience no matter what
the<BR>
concrete situation is like; furthermore, they mostly have been formulated<BR>
and ritualized during early stages of cultural evolution, and have been<BR>
based on a transcendent image of the world as a whole. Their limitless<BR>
application thus would cause inhumane &quot;fundamentalism&quot; in social<BR>
development.<BR>
<BR>
Judgement now has to balance out these two components of reason in order<BR>
to result in &quot;suitable&quot; orientation and action, which:<BR>
- give justice to the world by means of an image of a well-ordered<BR>
world; &quot;teleological suitability&quot; and<BR>
- gives justice to Man within the world by means of an image of Man<BR>
acting properly so that he gains welfare for himself by feeling himself<BR>
at his proper place: &quot;aesthetic suitability&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
Thus, in fact, &quot;beauty is the expression of the Morally Good in the
world&quot;<BR>
(Schiller). Insofar it aims for the proper development of both sides of<BR>
action, Man and the world, it results in sustainability. This -seemingly<BR>
esoteric - image of Man's reason will be illustrated by analysing concepts<BR>
of &quot;cultivated landscape&quot; and of a &quot;world order of socio-economic
justice&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1103959"></A>5. LEMARCHAND, BUENOS AIRES<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
ETHICAL PRINCIPLES AND THE NORMATIVE MODELS OF SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT<BR>
<BR>
Guillermo A. Lemarchand<BR>
Centro de Estudios Avanzados,<BR>
Universidad de Buenos Aires,<BR>
C.C. 8 - Sucursal 25; (1425)-Buenos Aires, Argentina<BR>
TEL: +54 1 774 0667, FAX: +54 1 963 6962 <BR>
E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:lemar@seti.edu.ar">lemar@seti.edu.ar</A><BR>
<BR>
Abstract<BR>
<BR>
What we are today depends to a great extent upon how we have been<BR>
formed by generations that have preceded us. The actions we take today<BR>
will shape the world that future generations will live in. What kind<BR>
of world we leave to the future is essentially a question of moral<BR>
responsibility.<BR>
<BR>
In this paper we make a brief review of the principal ethical basis,<BR>
towards the fellow being and nature that are common statements in<BR>
the main philosophical schools and religions. We found that most of<BR>
them share a common ground that sets the individual and collective<BR>
responsibility for the practices of altruistic fraternal attitudes. It<BR>
will be shown that the extension of these principles can also be<BR>
applied to respect the rights of future generations and to set the<BR>
normative reasoning behind the shaping of landscape by humankind.<BR>
<BR>
As an example of how these guidelines can modify the present global<BR>
situation, we show the results that could be obtained from the<BR>
application of a &quot;normative world model&quot;. Among the global formal<BR>
models of the seventies, the so-called Latin American or Bariloche<BR>
Model, was the closest to a definite quality-of-life orientation. This<BR>
model was a life-expectancy-at-birth, optimizing model. It simulated<BR>
world phenomena at the regional level, incorporating economic<BR>
production and health variables of basic needs (food, housing,<BR>
education) and assumes average production equal to average<BR>
consumption. The focus was on basic needs satisfaction feasibility in<BR>
the intermediate and long term. The quality of life through the life<BR>
expectancy at birth was used as the objective function of the model.<BR>
Hence, a human end consideration was central for this model.<BR>
<BR>
The Bariloche model showed, within the obvious limitations of this type<BR>
of work that the fate of man does not depend, in the last instance, on<BR>
insurmountable physical barriers but on social and political factors<BR>
(relations among the members of the human species) that man must<BR>
modify following the beauty of the ethical principles. Their solution<BR>
is not at all easy, because to change the organization and values of<BR>
society, as it is shown by our history, is much more difficult that<BR>
overcoming the resources of nature. This model also shows that is<BR>
possible to control population growth to the point of equilibrium by<BR>
raising the general standard of living, particularly with relation to<BR>
basic needs. This equilibrium could be achieved on a global scale well<BR>
before the Earth's capacity to produce food -the only foreseeable<BR>
physical limitation within the time horizon of the model- is fully<BR>
exploited, even if food production continues to be based on currently<BR>
available technology.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1117997"></A>6. KLIUCININKAS, KAUNAS<BR>
<BR>
GIS Based Planning of Protected Areas Development<BR>
in South West Lithuania<BR>
<BR>
Linas Kliucininkas<BR>
Assoc. Prof., Department for Environmental Engineering<BR>
Algirdas Kliucininkas<BR>
Prof., Department of Human Safety<BR>
<BR>
Kaunas University of Technology<BR>
Radvilenu 19, 3028 Kaunas, Lithuania<BR>
Tel.: +370 7 751016, Fax: +370 7 756366<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:Linas.Kliucininkas@ct.ktu.lt">Linas.Kliucininkas@ct.ktu.lt</A><BR>
<BR>
Abstract<BR>
<BR>
Protected areas in Lithuania are established with a view to preserve all<BR>
aspects of the landscape and its individual components as well as<BR>
biological diversity. At present protected areas cover 6 percent of the<BR>
total country's territory. The further formation of a network of protected<BR>
areas will occur according to the Lithuanian Natural Framework Concept -
a<BR>
system of natural balances to an environment disturbed and cultivated by<BR>
man. According to the concept, protected areas would make up 10 percent
of<BR>
the country's territory.<BR>
<BR>
The study being conducted was to foresight strategy for sustainable<BR>
development of protected areas in south west part of Lithuania. The study<BR>
area is covered by Sesupe river watershed (6105 km2) and makes up a region<BR>
with the similar environmental conditions and infrastructure. The region<BR>
comprises 3 administrative counties with 5797 ha of protected areas, which<BR>
make up 1.3 percent of the total region's area.<BR>
<BR>
The use of natural resources and landscape planning were based on the<BR>
short/mid term as well as the long term perspectives. The aim of the study<BR>
was to make a zoning maps which will indicate wildlife areas to be<BR>
protected, while at the same time will estimate industry, infrastructure
as<BR>
well as agriculture development perspectives. Since land can be allocated<BR>
to only one of these uses at any one time, the objectives must be viewed
as<BR>
conflicting - i.e., they may potentially compete for the same land.<BR>
<BR>
Geographic Information Systems (GIS) were applied for decision support<BR>
procedure. IDRISI for Windows 1.0 - a grid-based geographic information<BR>
and image processing system was employed to develop different scenarios.<BR>
The choice between alternatives was made on multi-objective and<BR>
multi-criterion basis. A set of suitability maps, each derived in the<BR>
context of a specific objective, serve as the factors for a new evaluation<BR>
in which the objectives are themselves weighted and combined by linear<BR>
summation.<BR>
With conflicting objectives, one possible solution lies with a<BR>
prioritization of objectives. However, the instance where a prioritised<BR>
solution makes sense are rare. More often a compromise solution is required<BR>
<BR>
As a result, a solution to the problem of multi-objective land allocation<BR>
under conditions of conflicting objectives are the suitability maps to be<BR>
thought of as axis in a multi-dimensional space. Every raster cell in the<BR>
image can be located within this decision space according to its<BR>
suitability level on each of the objectives. To resolve these areas of<BR>
conflict, a simple partitioning of the affected cells is used. The process<BR>
of resolving conflicts and lowering the decision lines is iteratively<BR>
repeated until the exact area targets are achieved.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1136725"></A>7. METZNER, COTTBUS<BR>
<BR>
Ecological-Social Conditions of Ethical Behavior<BR>
<BR>
Dr. Andreas Metzner<BR>
Fakult&auml;t Umweltwissenschaften<BR>
Technische Universit&auml;t Cottbus<BR>
Karl-Marx Str. 17, 03044 Cottbus, Germany<BR>
Tel: 0355 / 69 - 3160- 3037<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:metzner.umwelt@tu-cottbus.de">metzner.umwelt@tu-cottbus.de</A><BR>
<BR>
Global environmental changes and the strategy of a &quot;Sustainable<BR>
Development&quot; have substantial ethical implications. A prevailing general<BR>
consent is, that we are responsible for the present condition of our planet<BR>
and also for the future generations.<BR>
<BR>
This consent is a necessary condition for a change of our behavior, but
is<BR>
not sufficient enough for putting these changes into effect. This<BR>
discrepancy is a challenge for all ecological ethics. Also it is<BR>
presumably necessary to attend more to the dissent and the conditions under<BR>
which the ecological issues are being debated.<BR>
<BR>
Social conflicts over ecological issues are determined by three complexes:<BR>
<BR>
1.) Along with the increasing consequences and escalating effects of our<BR>
own actions and decisions our dependency on the behavior of others is<BR>
growing. Concerning the social and ecological conditions and effects of<BR>
our acts, a cumulation of reciprocal dependencies is taking place. In the<BR>
development of modern, differentiated, and complex societies however the<BR>
relative significance of our direct and personal interdependencies is<BR>
lessening, though the indirect, socially and ecologically imparted<BR>
interdependencies are gaining even more significance. Consequently the<BR>
ethics are confronted with the problem that development has promoted the<BR>
greatest individuality ever, while on the other hand it demands more<BR>
collective responsibility than ever.<BR>
<BR>
2.) The problems of ecological aftereffects of human behavior are becoming<BR>
all the more difficult and more complex to control as society manifests<BR>
itself less homogeneously, but rather fragmented into different population<BR>
groups and social systems. These are affected differently by environmental<BR>
repercussions according to their different utilization of ecological<BR>
resources and dependence on environmental media. Moreover they process<BR>
their affectedness differently, according to their selective standards<BR>
formed by their interests, reason, and culture. Hence the competition<BR>
processes for the<BR>
utilization of environmental goods and resources are diversified and<BR>
multiplied. Simultaneously the possible externalizing effects of ones own<BR>
actions upon others are growing. The ethics cannot count on environmental<BR>
problems leading to an equalization of affectedness but rather have to<BR>
consider that the objective and subjective utilization conflicts over<BR>
environmental goods and damages will be increasing.<BR>
<BR>
3.) In modern societies the relationship between the perception of<BR>
environment and environmentally determined behavior is highly complex, in<BR>
so far as a prevailing and behavior determining nature model as it exists<BR>
in archaic and traditional societies is missing. Instead a multitude of<BR>
functionally, culturally and professionally differentiated nature models<BR>
are strongly influencing the metabolism of nature and society. (Luhmann<BR>
1986, Thompson/Ellis/Wildavsky 1990, Huber 1989) This diversity of<BR>
efficient, social behavior determining nature models, correlates with a<BR>
growing range of different utilization forms of nature and increasing<BR>
contradictions between them, which are further aggravated by the growing<BR>
aftereffects and consequences of their specific operations . Now towards<BR>
which standards are ethics supposed to orientate, when ecological problems<BR>
are being judged by totally different experiences, cognizance perspectives<BR>
and interests?<BR>
<BR>
If one starts from a fastidious socio-theoretical analysis of the whole<BR>
ensemble of modernization risks and ecological problems, the only possible<BR>
conclusion is, that there can't be a simple 'logic of salvation', but only<BR>
a 'dialogic' (Barben/Dierkes 1990, 443), that takes up all differences and<BR>
contradictions, liquefies them and thus makes them socially pliable. In<BR>
Habermas' terminology (1981/1985) this means to attempt a lasting<BR>
strengthening of social reason through communication which is orientated<BR>
towards coming to an understanding of each other.<BR>
<BR>
A simple consent orientated social communication process would certainly
be<BR>
problematic. Consent is often achieved only at the cost of equivocal and<BR>
watered-down positions and it supports the build up of hidden conflicts.<BR>
An orientation towards dissent however could bring more rationality into<BR>
conflicts, and thus improve the conditions for ethically responsible<BR>
decisions, since the opposing positions would become more transparent for<BR>
each other, be it the positions of experts and laymen or those of<BR>
industrial and developing countries. As ethics turn into a process of<BR>
intercommunication and negotiation, they loose their foothold within<BR>
categorical statements, but simultaneously gain the opportunity for a<BR>
greater future competence.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1142237"></A>8. MUKENDI, BRUSSELS<BR>
<BR>
Techno-science et nature<BR>
<BR>
Phil&eacute;mon Mukendi<BR>
Centre Bruxellois d'Action Interculturelle<BR>
Avenue de Stalingrad 24, 1000 Bruxelles, Belgique<BR>
Tel: +32 2 513 ,9602, Fax: +32 2 512 ,1796<BR>
<BR>
La techno-science moderne est n&eacute;e de la raison instrumentale apparue
sous<BR>
les auspices de Galil&eacute;e et Descartes. Aux yeux de ces penseurs, la
nature<BR>
est envisag'ee comme un objet &agrave; conna&icirc;tre et &agrave; ma&icirc;triser.
D&egrave;s<BR>
le d&eacute;part, s'est donc instaur&eacute; entre la techno-science et
la nature un<BR>
rapport conflictuel, un rapport d'objectivation.<BR>
<BR>
L'&eacute;puisement des ressources et les catastrophes &eacute;cologiques
actuelles<BR>
contraignent &agrave; reprendre &agrave; nouveaux frais la question du statut
de la<BR>
nature ainsi que celle des limites de sa mise en valeur.<BR>
<BR>
La nature a-t-elle une subjectivit&eacute;, comme le pense Ernst Bloch?
A-t-elle<BR>
des droits similaires &agrave; ceux de l'homme, comme le sugg`ere Michel
Serres?<BR>
<BR>
Telles sont les questions sur lesquelles reposera la communication dont
les<BR>
points principaux sont les suivants:<BR>
<BR>
- La techno-science moderne:<BR>
un instrument de manipulation et de domination de la nature. Il s'agit ici<BR>
d'examiner avec quels instruments la rationalit'e instrumentale et la<BR>
techno-science exercent leur domination sur la nature. L'analyse sera<BR>
philosophique sous l'inspiration de l'Ecole de Francfort et d'Ernst Bloch.<BR>
<BR>
- Des droits de la nature?<BR>
Pour un bon nombre de penseurs, la nature ne peut se r&eacute;duire &agrave;
un simple<BR>
objet soumis &agrave; la domination humaine. Le philosophe allemand Ernst
Bloch<BR>
lui reconna&icirc;t une subjectivit&eacute;. Michel Serres lui revendique<BR>
des droits. Qu'en est-il au juste?<BR>
<BR>
Une nouvelle &eacute;cologie?:<BR>
Ernst Bloch pr&eacute;conise une relation concr&egrave;te entre l'homme
et la nature,<BR>
&agrave; travers ce qu'il appelle une technique d'alliance. Ilya Prigogine
abonde<BR>
dans le m&ecirc;me sens, proposant une 'ecoute po'etique de la nature. Pour
sa<BR>
part, Edgar Morin propose des &eacute;changes dialectiques entre l'&eacute;co-sph&egrave;re<BR>
et la sph&egrave;re anthropo-sociale, pour que la soci'et'e rentre dans
la nature<BR>
et la nature dans la soci&eacute;t&eacute;.<BR>
<BR>
Comment r&eacute;aliser cette nouvelle &eacute;cologie et en m&ecirc;me
temps<BR>
assurer le bien-&ecirc;tre de tous par la techno-science? Comment utiliser
les<BR>
ressources naturelles sans les &eacute;puiser?<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Techno-science and nature<BR>
Philemon Mukendi<BR>
<BR>
Modern techno-science arose from the instrumental reasoning initiated by<BR>
Galileo and Descartes. In the view of these thinkers, nature was an<BR>
object to understand and to master. Therefore, from the very start, the<BR>
relationship between techno-science and nature was one of conflict, a<BR>
relationship of objectivation.<BR>
<BR>
The present exhaustion of natural resources and ecological catastrophes<BR>
force us to reformulate the question of the status and the value of<BR>
nature.<BR>
<BR>
Has nature a subjectivity, as Ernst Bloch thinks? Does it have similar<BR>
rights to those of mankind, as suggested by Michel Serres?<BR>
<BR>
These are the questions treated in this communication, the principal<BR>
points being:<BR>
<BR>
Modern techno-science: an instrument for the manipulation and domination<BR>
of nature. It is a question of examining what the means are by which<BR>
instrumental reasoning and techno-science exercises its domination of<BR>
nature. The analysis will be philosophical and follow the line of the<BR>
Frankfurt school and that of Ernst Bloch.<BR>
<BR>
The rights of nature: For a number of thinkers nature cannot be reduced<BR>
to a simple object, which is subject to human domination. The German<BR>
philosopher Ernst Bloch recognizes a subjectivity in nature. Michel<BR>
Serres demands rights for nature. What is correct?<BR>
<BR>
A new ecology: Ernst Bloch advocates a concrete relationship between man<BR>
and nature through what he calls a technique of alliance. Ilya Prigogine<BR>
goes farther, proposing a poetic sensitivity in nature. Edgar Morin<BR>
proposes dialectic exchanges between the ecosphere and the<BR>
anthropo-social sphere by means of which society re-enters nature and<BR>
nature re-enters society.<BR>
<BR>
How to chieve this new ecology while at the same time ensuring the<BR>
welfare of all through techno-science? How to use natural resources<BR>
without exhausting them?<BR>
<BR>
English translation (Ph.B. Smith)<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1148300"></A>9. RYDEN, UPPSALA<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The Concept of Sustainability in the<BR>
contemporary debate on development.<BR>
Lars Ryd&eacute;n<BR>
The Baltic University Programme<BR>
Uppsala University, Box 2109, S-75002 Uppsala, Sweden<BR>
Tel +46-18-18 18 38, Fax +46-18-18 17 89, E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:Lars.Ryden@uadm.uu.se">Lars.Ryden@uadm.uu.se</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
In the contemporary debate on development and environmental impact the word<BR>
sustainability is found in different contexts and with different<BR>
connotations. It plays the role of metaphor for not always spelled out<BR>
hopes, fears and visions. In this contribution I will attempt to analyse<BR>
which some of these are.<BR>
<BR>
The fact that Sustainability is understood in a diversity of ways is not<BR>
necessarily negative, as sometimes said. It can be compared to how concepts<BR>
such as Peace and Health are understood. They are also carriers of hopes,<BR>
fears and visions as well as rather detailed technical descriptions and<BR>
definitions. This is not perceived as negative.<BR>
<BR>
Sustainability may be identified as carrier of six clearly different<BR>
connotations. These are: 1) Civilisation shift, the genuinely new, not<BR>
previously known in social debate; 2) The systems analysis perspective,<BR>
beyond the reductionistic tradition now dominating science; 3) Just<BR>
distribution of resources between generations, required by the long term<BR>
conservation of resources; 4) Respect for Nature necessitated by the long<BR>
term conservation of Nature productivity and diversity; 5) The role of<BR>
grassroots perspective for implementation making sustainability a picture<BR>
of true democracy; and finally 6) The personal involvement where<BR>
sustainability stands for the Good Life, the goals for the strivings by
in<BR>
particular young people.<BR>
<BR>
It is thus possible to express sustainability in a mathematical form (no
2<BR>
above), or as a political program (no 1 above), in particular if the<BR>
development aspect is stressed. However of the six connotations mentioned<BR>
above, five have a very obvious ethical aspect. And above all the<BR>
requirement for intergenerational equity makes sustainability in itself<BR>
unavoidably an ethical concept.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1155491"></A>10. SCHEFFRAN, DARMSTADT<BR>
<BR>
Sustainable development and peace<BR>
J&uuml;rgen Scheffran<BR>
IANUS, Institut f&uuml;r Kernphysik<BR>
Schloss gartenstr. 9, 64289 Darmstadt, Germany<BR>
TEL: +49 6151 16 4468, FAX: +49 6151 16 6039,<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:scheffran@hrzpub.th-darmstadt.de">scheffran@hrzpub.th-darmstadt.de</A><BR>
<BR>
There is a close relationship between sustainable development and peace:<BR>
while sustainable development is an essential precondition for peace,<BR>
the preservation of peace is an essential precondition for the cooperative<BR>
implementation of sustainable development. In other words:<BR>
if the world remains or becomes more violent and unpeaceful, sustainable<BR>
development, requiring a large degree of cooperation, is threatened,<BR>
which could be a cause for new violent conflicts. The vicious cycle<BR>
between environmental destruction and social violence needs to be<BR>
studied more carefully.<BR>
<BR>
Conflicts on the road to sustainable development could emerge on<BR>
various levels:<BR>
1. Conflicts between values: Development, justice, preservation<BR>
of the environment and the principle of non-violence can be conflicting<BR>
goals, which need to be harmonized. Different perspectives on which goal<BR>
should have the highest preference could lead to intra- or interpersonal<BR>
conflicts.<BR>
2. Conflicts between actors within society: If the mentioned<BR>
goals are associated with social actors (parties, companies, trade<BR>
unions, citizens initiatives), conflicts within the society could be<BR>
the consequence.<BR>
3. Conflicts between states and regions: If states or groups<BR>
of states each follow different objectives, conflicts between states are<BR>
possible (e.g. North-South conflict).<BR>
4. Conflicts between present and future generations: Largely<BR>
ignored is the conflict of interests between different generations<BR>
over scarce resources. Future generations have no power to<BR>
influence current decisions, except the ethical reflection, the<BR>
responsibility and the solidarity of the present generation.<BR>
<BR>
Ethics could play an important role in transcending conflicts by<BR>
influencing the distribution of objectives into one or the other<BR>
direction. The following questions could be seen as starting points for<BR>
discussion:<BR>
- In which way do environmental degradation, under-development<BR>
and violence mutually influence each other?<BR>
- How can concepts of peace and sustainable development mutually<BR>
inspire each other?<BR>
- How can sustainable development be achieved, even under<BR>
non-peaceful conditions?<BR>
- How can peace be achieved, even under unsustainable conditions?<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1164379"></A>11. TIAN, LEIPZIG<BR>
<BR>
Models for landscape dynamics and their application<BR>
<BR>
Tian Xiang Yue, et al.<BR>
Research Center for Environment<BR>
P.O.~Box 2, 04301 Leipzig, Deutschland<BR>
<BR>
Since the early 1970's, W. Haber's Continuous studies upon spatial<BR>
diversity of land use has created small DLU strategy. Since the late<BR>
1970's, owing to yhe continuous efforts mainly from B.B.~Mandelbrot, the<BR>
theoretical system of fractal geometry has been developed. According to
the<BR>
Haber's small DLU strategy, the models for landscape dynamics are<BR>
constructed by means of fractal geometry. In their case studies of<BR>
experimental zones that are separately located in Europe and Asia, several<BR>
major issues of landscape changes are analyzed. They are:<BR>
- Spacial dynamics,<BR>
- Temporal dynamics,<BR>
- Driving forces of the landscape changes,<BR>
- Their effects on economic efficiency and ecological environment.<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="anchor1172088"></A>12. VOGES, STELLENBOSCH<BR>
<BR>
Justice, sustainability and corporate management in developing countries<BR>
Ian F. Voges, Researcher<BR>
University of Stellenbosch, Stellenbosch, 7600, South Africa<BR>
Temporary address from Jan 1996 to Jan 1997:<BR>
Vakgroep Praktische Wijsbegeerte, University of Amsterdam,<BR>
Nieuwe Doelenstraat 15, 1012 CP Amsterdam, Nederland<BR>
<BR>
It is now commonplace that a constructive response to the environmental<BR>
crisis will require continuing philosophical and moral debate about the<BR>
appropriate nature of sustainable development and its management. A great<BR>
amount of thinking has already been done on the inadequacy of narrow<BR>
anthropocentric and ego-centric value orientations and new values which<BR>
should guide our interaction with our environment have been put forward.<BR>
These new values are reflected in the urgent call for sustainability, the<BR>
equitable redistribution of resources (environmental justice) and an<BR>
ecocentric or enlightened anthropocentric attitude of care for the<BR>
environment.<BR>
<BR>
Responding to these moral demands, the business sectors of developing<BR>
countries are incorporating environmental values (such as sustainability)<BR>
and social values (such as equity) in policy documents. However,<BR>
unsustainable and unjust corporate activity continues today even though<BR>
corporations concern themselves with new ethical values in policy<BR>
documents. Although management theorists and managers are working<BR>
on (and implementing) strategies with which to transform unsustainable<BR>
and inequitable institutional and management processes there has as yet<BR>
been no ethical and philosophical reflection on this topic.<BR>
<BR>
What is in serious need of being done, and is also the focus of this<BR>
paper, is to do a philosophical-ethical evaluation of the organisational<BR>
procedures and management processes which can facilitate the<BR>
implementation of new ethical values. In the first section of the paper<BR>
I will approach issues of justice and sustainability from an ethical<BR>
perspective. I will discuss and evaluate ways in which these values can<BR>
be given ethical content and in each case provide an argument for a<BR>
specific ethical content for each of these values. In the case of<BR>
justice I will argue for a thicker approach (drawing on the work of<BR>
Amartya Sen, Martha Nussbaum, Manfred Max-Neef) to questions of justice<BR>
against the more liberal, thin approach characteristic of the theories of<BR>
justice advanced by liberal theorists like John Rawls.<BR>
<BR>
My discussion of justice will focus on theories which come to have a<BR>
direct bearing on one or more of the following topics: the development<BR>
problematique (i.e. ,North-South relations and the question of &quot;just&quot;<BR>
development), questions of international, intergenerational and<BR>
interspecies justice. In the context of sustainability I will argue for<BR>
a more eco-centric approach which not only takes future generations into<BR>
account but also the inherent value of nature hic et nunc (such a move<BR>
can already be seen in the content of Caring for the Earth vis a vis<BR>
that of Our Common Future).<BR>
<BR>
In the second section of the paper I will focus on the &quot;tools&quot;
of corporate<BR>
management. Some of the tools which I will evaluate in terms of their<BR>
ability to achieve the ethical objective of sustainability and justice are:<BR>
Action-centred network management, internal environmental management<BR>
systems, integral life-cycle management, environmental and<BR>
social reporting and auditing. Throughout the paper the central values<BR>
of justice and sustainability will be used as an evaluational criteria<BR>
to judge the relative value of the above mentioned measures.<BR>
<BR>
