<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Elzinga abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Lifestyle discussion in the Netherlands: wrong questions yield wrong
answers</H3>
Chris Elzinga<BR>
Koppestokstraat 63, 2014 AN Haarlem, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 23 524 7542<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Last year the Dutch Ministry of the Environment (VROM) started a<BR>
discussion about current lifestyles in the Netherlands in connection<BR>
with (global) environmental degradation. The issue is how we possibly<BR>
can induce a change in mentality of citizens and institutions in order<BR>
to stop environmental damage. Until now VROM-publications <BR>
mainly contain<BR>
descriptions of human behaviour. But for a lifestyle discussion we need<BR>
more. Without focusing on underlying causes of human behaviour it is<BR>
impossible to formulate effective strategies of change.<BR>
<BR>
We are hardly aware of the assumptions our lifestyles are based upon.<BR>
Key-assumptions are: a) our needs are insatiable, b) we are not part of<BR>
nature and therefore permit ourselves to exploit nature merely to<BR>
satisfy our growing needs, c) nature's resources are unlimited and d)<BR>
technology will find proper solutions whenever resources are depleted.<BR>
To meet insatiable demands economy must grow and nature must provide the<BR>
means. Thus an ever-growing economy is seen as a necessity and a blessing<BR>
for mankind. These assumptions can easily be recognized in Dutch<BR>
environmental policy.<BR>
<BR>
Focusing on the assumption of insatiable needs, we can find an<BR>
explanation by looking at the way individual human beings develop their<BR>
sense of identity. In this process we make a distinction between<BR>
ourselves and our environment, both physical and social. This produces<BR>
painful feelings of isolation. In order to cope with these feelings<BR>
without losing our sense of identity, we wish to gain control: we<BR>
control things (by gathering possessions), people and situations (by<BR>
power) and our feelings of unrest (by sex and pleasure). Control gives a<BR>
feeling of identity (we 'are' what we 'have') and an illusion of<BR>
relatedness with the world. But because there is always (unconscious)<BR>
fear of losing what we 'have', the desire to expand control is<BR>
unsatiable.<BR>
<BR>
In addition the control exerted by others functions as a point of<BR>
reference: we desire to possess what others possess and we like to<BR>
display what others lack. In this way our needs are socially determined.<BR>
This makes us vulnerable to manipulation, thus further increasing our<BR>
needs.<BR>
<BR>
In western society the strong emphasis on satisfaction of insatiable<BR>
needs has severe implications. On the individual level it leads to<BR>
different forms of addiction. On the level of human society it has<BR>
resulted worldwide in democratically accepted forms of human<BR>
exploitation. As far as nature is concerned its effects are global<BR>
environmental degradation and loss of biodiversity.<BR>
<BR>
What does this diagnosis add to the lifestyle discussion? First of all<BR>
it sheds light upon the addictive sides of our way of life. Secondly, it<BR>
shows how an addictive lifestyle harms not only nature, but human<BR>
society and eventually individuals as well. Thirdly, it draws attention<BR>
to the effects of industrial and commercial activities on lifestyles.<BR>
And finally, we only can start rethinking our way of life fundamentally<BR>
when we have enough psychological understanding of human transformation<BR>
processes.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws12suslif.html#anchor4624139">workshop 1.2
page</A>.<BR>
