<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Elzinga abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>All power comes from within</H3>
Tilmann Faul<BR>
Waldstr. 14, 85757 Karlsfeld, Deutschland<BR>
TEL/FAX: +49 8131 92131<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:wolfram.faul@eikon.e-technik.tu-muenchen.de%20">wolfram.faul@eikon.e-technik.tu-muenchen.de
</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The inability to react freely on a situation is stress. The problems of
our<BR>
global situation, the stress-phenomena in our society and the stress-related<BR>
tensions in the physical bodies reflect each other in a figurative way.<BR>
<BR>
The reason of stress can be seen in a dualistic thinking process. The problem<BR>
is seen in the environment (global, social, physical) and the solution is<BR>
to change the environment. But more profound the problem is connected to
the<BR>
viewpoint of the observer and the &quot;solution&quot; does not change the
viewpoint.<BR>
<BR>
The experience of nonduality gives us the chance to realize the possibilities<BR>
of self-organisation and authentic action and changes the viewpoint toward
the<BR>
observer.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws12suslif.html#anchor4624139">workshop 1.2
page</A>.<BR>
