<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Jones abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Return to sustainable dwelling?</H3>
Genevieve Jones<BR>
Arch Robert Gordon University, School of Surveying <BR>
Garthdee, Aberdeen, Scotland<BR>
E-MAIL: susgj@garthdee1.rgu.ac.uk<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Sustainable housing was the norm and the tradition until relatively<BR>
recently in the history of human inhabitation. When we 'housed ourselves'
as<BR>
opposed to 'being housed' the use of materials and space could have been<BR>
described as being 'ecological'; it tended to be constructed or adapted
from<BR>
materials or forms that were found locally. Caves, stones from cleared fields<BR>
or occasionally quarries, trees, mud. Space responded to domestic and<BR>
agricultural requirements in terms of size and layout and was rarely any
larger<BR>
than absolutely necessary. Technically it responded to the environment in
quite<BR>
sophisticated ways given the available resources. This was generally the
case<BR>
until the designers and improvers got to work on it. This is not to say
that<BR>
traditional agricultural dwellings were perfectly warm, dry and comfortable;<BR>
they obviously were not. But then neither are they always today. Over the
last<BR>
two or three centuries various institutions and individuals such as those<BR>
passing health regulations or constructing model houses have taken over
from<BR>
the family or social group. They have decided how our dwellings should be<BR>
organised, of what they should be built and where they should go. I would
like<BR>
to suggest that it during this same period, perhaps coincidentally, our<BR>
dwellings have become increasingly less sustainable in their use of resources<BR>
and less adapted to the special and psychological needs of the dwellers.
The<BR>
dweller has lost control of his dwelling. This is true of owner occupiers
as<BR>
much as of tenants. There are many squatter camps which show better adaptation
<BR>
to<BR>
the users needs and priorities while using what might be called more<BR>
sustainable forms and materials. These dwellers could be said to have more<BR>
control than their apparently better housed countrymen in the formal<BR>
sector. Increasingly community groups and individuals are acquiring rights
from<BR>
housing providers to build, modernise, manage their homes and districts.
'Do it<BR>
yourself' is a booming industry. The dwellings are not really becoming anymore<BR>
sustainable and sustainability or even energy conservation is not an issue
with<BR>
most purchasers. control over resources then is not the whole story. The
paper<BR>
argues that while control of resources is important that it is perhaps even<BR>
more important that users must also regain control over the knowledge and<BR>
understanding of how to use those recources. Squatters understand how their<BR>
dwellings are put together and keep the sun and rain out as did the dwellers
of<BR>
the Hebredian Black House. The solution, however, is not to go backwards
into<BR>
more technically simple forms, our requirements have changed. We need to<BR>
educate everyone to comprehend the more complex and ultimately more responsive<BR>
technology that is available today; to make the language of building and<BR>
development a universal one, a more appropriate one. The challenge after
that<BR>
is to make the technology that leads to sustainability the one that we want<BR>
to use rather than that which simply leads to maintaining the global economy.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws12suslif.html#anchor4624139">workshop 1.2
page</A>.<BR>
