<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Richardson abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Frugal lifestyles and values: How economics influences more sustainable
ways of life</H3>
Kathrine Richardson<BR>
Department of Planning, Public Policy and Management<BR>
University of Oregon<BR>
Eugene, Oregon 97403, USA <BR>
TEL/FAX: +1 541 741 0251, <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:lulley@darkwing.uoregon.edu%20">lulley@darkwing.uoregon.edu
</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Spiritual incentives and economic circumstances have caused people to<BR>
live frugally throughout the course of history. The values that these<BR>
people had demand that each person be frugal with their material goods<BR>
in order to conserve and make what one owned last whether it be of<BR>
spiritual or economic importance. This way of life and value system is<BR>
much closer to the principle of &quot;sustainability&quot; than the socio-cultural<BR>
milieu of materialism which dominates modern western society today. This<BR>
being the case, it is then of key importance to understand how these<BR>
values and lifestyles which support sustainable ethics develop, and how<BR>
they maintain themselves, even in time of abundance. Although<BR>
spirituality and religion play a major role in influencing a frugal<BR>
lifestyle, this paper will examine case studies of economic<BR>
circumstances at both the local and regional scale which have led<BR>
people to live more frugal lifestyles and develop and maintain more<BR>
frugal material values. This paper will then discuss how these frugal<BR>
ways of life and values contribute to sustainability.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws12suslif.html#anchor4624139">workshop 1.2
page</A>.<BR>
<BR>
