<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Mojeiko abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Sustainable socio-natural interaction: cultural dimension and spiritual
basis</H3>
Marina Mojeiko<BR>
Alexander Zhdanovsky<BR>
<BR>
The authors are Associate Professors of the Belarussian State University
and <BR>
Researchers of the Research Centre of Social Ecology<BR>
Department of Philosophy and Methodology of Science<BR>
Belarussian State University<BR>
F. Skorina av. 4, Minsk 220050, Republic of Belarus<BR>
TEL: +7 0172 226 5936, FAX: +7 0172 220 8821<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The contemporary ideal of global civilization supposes an orientation to<BR>
humanity as a united socio-natural planet complex. This orientation<BR>
proposes lifestyle aimed at unconflicting relations between people and<BR>
the environment. That is why one of the most important grounds of<BR>
sustainability nowadays is the forming of an ecological consciousness of<BR>
the new type.<BR>
<BR>
Its specific features are the following. On the one hand, this<BR>
ecological consciousness must be universal (the same for different<BR>
regions), because its axiological system and ethical code are founded on<BR>
the newest scientific investigations and the latest industrial and<BR>
agricultural technologies. At the same time, contemporary ecological<BR>
culture may be characterized as polycentric in the ethno-national<BR>
aspect. This does not mean, of course, the recovery of archaic forms of<BR>
socio-natural interaction.<BR>
<BR>
The question is about values and priorities of national traditions, that<BR>
may be useful from the point of view of ecological sustainability.<BR>
Comparative analyses allows one to distinguish diverse types of<BR>
ecological consciousness: first of all, the opposition of Western<BR>
(transformational) and Eastern (contemplative) manners of human-natural<BR>
relations.<BR>
<BR>
Besides these classical forms of ecological consciousness, it is<BR>
possible to discover some untypical versions. Such versions arise under<BR>
frontal collisions of Western and Eastern traditions in the spiritual<BR>
area of some national cultures. Western and Eastern interpretations of<BR>
harmony between man and nature are irrevocably opposed, and this makes<BR>
their parallel coexistence in the same national culture impossible. -<BR>
Usually specific &quot;annihilation&quot; of opposite values takes place.<BR>
<BR>
History gives us an opportunity to discover similar situations in<BR>
&quot;frontier&quot; cultures, such as Arabic culture of medieval Spain
or<BR>
Euro-Asian culture of Eastern Slavs. Reciprocal influence of Western and<BR>
Eastern axiological systems of ecological consciousness gives rise to a<BR>
fan of perspectives of eco-cultural evolution. As a rule, conceptual<BR>
levels of culture demonstrate higher interest in the ecological problems<BR>
(for example: the Russian philosophy of cosmism, V. Vernadsky's and<BR>
A. Chizhevsky's theoretical models, etc.).<BR>
<BR>
At the same time the mass consciousness shows an indifference to the<BR>
problems of human-natural relations. Values of environmental protection<BR>
are not in the centre of attention. But mass consciousness is exactly<BR>
the decisive factor, determining favourable or unfavourable perspectives<BR>
of ecological development. This form of ecological tradition is pregnant<BR>
with dangerous consequences. Really a person in such society belongs to<BR>
different technological worlds (traditional mode of life on the one<BR>
hand, and modern industrial technologies of production on the other).<BR>
Incomparability of these elements of culture gives rise to the lack of<BR>
agreement of individual technological experience and non-coordination of<BR>
industrial skill. An absence of fixed ecological priorities in mass<BR>
culture aggravates the unsustainability of such society. The tragic<BR>
accident of Chernobyl electric power station (the 26th of April, 1986)<BR>
is the striking example of it. Our social system is similar to a baby<BR>
amusing himself by lighting matches. This type of evolution is<BR>
characterized by an inclination to conflict forms of socio-natural<BR>
interaction and serious ecological unsustainability.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws12suslif.html#anchor4624139">workshop 1.2
page</A>.<BR>
