<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Lopes da Silva abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>MILITARISM: WHOSE SECURITY? -- The impact of militarism on environment
and on development</H3>
Carlota Lopes da Silva<BR>
Women's International League for Peace and Freedom (WILPF)<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:100571.502@compuserve.com">100571.502@compuserve.com</A><BR>
<BR>
International address: WILPF<BR>
1, Rue de Varembe, 1211 Gen&Ouml;`eve, Suisse<BR>
TEL: +41 22 733 6175, FAX: +41 22 740 1063,<BR>
E-MAIL: womensleague@gn.apc.org<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The prevailing view of militarism as a means to national security is<BR>
unsustainable and is inconsistent with our growing understanding of<BR>
Planet Earth with its finite resources and complex life systems, of<BR>
which we are part.<BR>
<BR>
The emerging concept of security as &quot;common security&quot; is based
not on<BR>
national boundaries, but on the boundaries provided by the earthly<BR>
habitat whose ecosystems are becoming increasingly fragile. Our needs as<BR>
human beings are basically simple and common to us all. Safeguarding and<BR>
providing these is the goal of our common security.<BR>
<BR>
Militarism is based on the goal of gaining a position of superiority<BR>
over others, who may or may not be aggressors, no matter what is the<BR>
cost. Thus &quot;Security&quot; that is derived from military force has
led to<BR>
environmental destruction:<BR>
<BR>
&#183;environmental destruction as a method or tool of warfare;<BR>
&#183;environmental destruction that leads to conflict, the migration of<BR>
refugees to marginal areas in which the environment is further strained,<BR>
leading to even greater strife over resources;<BR>
&#183;environmental destruction in preparing for war by building up<BR>
arsenals, transporting and testing weapons and practising for war;<BR>
&#183;environmental destruction by irresponsible storage or dumping of<BR>
waste from chemical, nuclear and biological weapons.<BR>
<BR>
An open assessment of health or environmental impact has never been made<BR>
as part of the military's concern. Since military activities are<BR>
shrouded in secrecy, it is difficult to get firm quantitative data<BR>
regarding military activities. This secrecy is also inconsistent with<BR>
our understanding of common security and democracy.<BR>
<BR>
The UN Summit on Environment and Development (UNCED, 1992) failed to<BR>
significantly address in Agenda 21 the issue of the impact of military<BR>
activities on the environment and on development . The UN Commission on<BR>
Sustainable Development (CSD) also fails to do so. Nevertheless<BR>
the Rio Declaration states in Principle 24: &quot;Warfare is inherently<BR>
destructive of sustainable development.&quot; And Principle 25: &quot;Peace,<BR>
Development and Environmental protection are interdependent and<BR>
indivisible.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The negative impact on development of excessive military expenditures,<BR>
the arms trade, and investment on arms production must be addressed.<BR>
<BR>
A view of national security based on militarism requires enormous<BR>
amounts of intellectual, material and energetic resources. We pay the<BR>
price for these military activities in the diversion of these resources<BR>
from education, social services, health care and artistic expression, to<BR>
sustain the machinery for real and make believe wars. (see <BR>
UNDPs Human Development Report, 1994).<BR>
<BR>
The Platform for Action, the final document of the 4th World Women's<BR>
Conference, Beijing 1995, is clear about the impact of militarism and<BR>
excessive military spending on people living in poverty, specially women<BR>
and children.<BR>
<BR>
To point out to governments to address sustainable development with<BR>
entirety, not excluding the large sector of the military, is a challenge<BR>
to all of us.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws12suslif.html#anchor4624139">workshop 1.2
page</A>.<BR>
