<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Wakeford abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>From responsible science to sustainable knowledge</H3>
Tom Wakeford<BR>
Department of Biology, University of York<BR>
York, YO1 5DD, United Kingdom<BR>
E-MAIL: tw100@mailer.york.ac.uk<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Both philosophers and green thinkers have suggested a flaw in the<BR>
concept of &quot;global responsibility&quot; when applied to networks of<BR>
engineers, scientists and technologists. Any organisation of scientists<BR>
for global responsibility can be subject to at least two criticisms.<BR>
<BR>
Firstly it accepts traditional notions of what is science and who is a<BR>
scientist. In general, only scientists are encouraged to join <BR>
INES and<BR>
its member bodies. Only knowledge with some sort of scientific<BR>
accreditation is accepted. And yet much of the knowledge crucial to<BR>
sustainable development is generated by indigenous and peasant peoples,<BR>
usually regarded as non-scientific.<BR>
<BR>
The second criticism relates to the public aims of INES-type<BR>
organisations. Is it to educate responsible scientists about society and<BR>
ecology, or educate society about science? What constitutes responsible<BR>
science and who decides? What should scientists have responsibility for?<BR>
All these questions have yet to be fully addressed.<BR>
<BR>
This paper argues that such criticisms are a major challenge to the<BR>
effectiveness of INES and its member organisations. I suggest some<BR>
possible solutions and call for a continued and urgent debate.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws12suslif.html#anchor4624139">workshop 1.2
page</A>.<BR>
<BR>
