<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Kollmann abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Lean Consumption</H3>
Karl Kollmann<BR>
AK-Wien<BR>
Prinz Eugenstr. 20, 1040 Wien, &Ouml;sterreich<BR>
TEL: +43 1 50165 2307, FAX: +43 1 50165 2693<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:kollmann@isis.wu-wien.ac.at">kollmann@isis.wu-wien.ac.at</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
From an ecological perspective it seems clear that production and<BR>
consumption must become more sustainable. The technical goals as to make<BR>
consumer goods more sustainable, to make them longer usable etc, are not<BR>
the real 'hard' problems. The real problem is: how can we change and<BR>
restructure the social and economic conditions to get a decrease in the<BR>
volume of consumption without causing a decrease in the quality of life?<BR>
<BR>
Sustainability is mainly a problem of volume: our western style<BR>
industrialism and post industrialism market economies are characterised<BR>
by an increasing consumption hypertrophy for the majorities (of course<BR>
beside that, there is growing poverty). Looking closer at these<BR>
circumstances, consumption is a societal and a consumer-psychological<BR>
problem. The mainstream economic view says: there is no need to take<BR>
measures - the marketplace will regulate itself, Adam Smith's &quot;invisible<BR>
hand&quot; and individual economical egoism will optimize everything. In
view<BR>
of this, &quot;sustainability&quot; must be seen not only as a &quot;material&quot;
task,<BR>
but also as a societal task and a responsibility of all societal<BR>
institutions.<BR>
<BR>
In a first step the paper discusses the boundaries of ecological<BR>
rationality from the viewpoint of the individual consumer, e.g. how<BR>
consumer decisions are structured and how consumers are often seduced<BR>
and forced by societal (social and economic) circumstances. In a second<BR>
step it focuses on the societal institutions and investigates their<BR>
possibilities to take action for enhancing sustainability (especially in<BR>
the consumption area). In the last step strategies of responsible social<BR>
and ecological involvement of both individuals and institutions will be<BR>
discussed.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws13socpro.html#anchor4828530">workshop 1.3
page</A>.<BR>
<BR>
