<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Sanne abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Public opinion and economic growth</H3>
Christer Sanne<BR>
Infrastructure and Planning, Royal Institute of<BR>
Technology KTH<BR>
100 44 Stockholm, Sverige<BR>
TEL: +46 8 790 7905, FAX: +46 8 790 6761,<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:sanne@regplan.kth.se">sanne@regplan.kth.se</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Sustainability calls for a brake on production and consumption in the West.<BR>
But many observers hold this to be politically infeasible since consumers<BR>
(who are also voters) are unlikely to alter their habits, customs and needs<BR>
in what is taken to be a thoroughly materialistic society.<BR>
<BR>
I suggest that this situation be analysed with a model of three types of<BR>
actors: Capital (business), People (the public), and The political<BR>
class, each with its interests and world views and mass media as a<BR>
powerful intermediary. I assume that change will not follow when and<BR>
because &quot;we&quot; (all actors) become informed (and begin to act morally<BR>
&quot;right&quot;). It is more likely that the different interests will
lead to<BR>
controversies and alliances which block or promote change.<BR>
<BR>
The focus of my paper will be on results from attitude surveys on needs<BR>
and belongings and on the duration of work (working hours). In my<BR>
interpretation, these indicate that people have a rather composed<BR>
attitude. Many instances of consumption of goods and services are<BR>
considered &quot;not needed&quot; even by those engaged in it. This attitude
to<BR>
consumption is supported by a widespread preference for free time. A<BR>
majority prefers shorter working hours over future higher income. The<BR>
present household budget may not allow any income reduction but a higher<BR>
material living standard is not the first priority for the future. The<BR>
notion of a green and sustainable society has a corresponding strong<BR>
support in public opinion.<BR>
<BR>
A number of objections can be and are raised against this kind of survey<BR>
results. The questions are called unrealistic, or the answers are said<BR>
to reflect adapted preferences (&quot;the sour grapes' reaction&quot;) etc.
This<BR>
is the standard sociological approach whereas the economist's standard<BR>
objection is that the replies given do not match actual behaviour.<BR>
Stated preferences are not supported by revealed preferences.<BR>
<BR>
This has some relevance but it should also be observed that all<BR>
objections fit within the paradigm of the insatiable consumer which is a<BR>
justification for economic growth. To regard the described attitudes as<BR>
a genuine value statement in favour of other aspects of the good life<BR>
implies a change of policy. It exposes the &quot;scientific&quot; explanations
as<BR>
ideological, as a way to explain away the contentment, and directs our<BR>
attention to those structural elements which impede change. Today<BR>
consumption as well as employment are strongly institutionalized and<BR>
Capital as well as The political class have a strong interest in<BR>
maintaining status quo.<BR>
<BR>
This is evident in the working hours issue where work sharing has been<BR>
ruled out for a long time in spite of strong support from the third type<BR>
of actor, People. There is not only a logical connection between working<BR>
less and ecological sustainability, but also a striking and instructive<BR>
resemblance in the way the issues are dealt with in society.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws13socpro.html#anchor4828530">workshop 1.3
page</A>.<BR>
