<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Makarov abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>The Russian Federation environmental strategy and policy under social
and economic crisis conditions</H3>
Sergei V. Makarov and Tatiana V. Guseva<BR>
Associate Professors of the Department of Industrial Ecology,<BR>
D.&uuml;Mendeleyev University of Chemical Technology of Russia<BR>
Miusskaya square 9, Moskwa, Rossia 125190<BR>
FAX: +7 095 200 4204, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:tvguseva@mhti.msk.su">tvguseva@mhti.msk.su</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The Russian Federation is suffering from a deep social and economic<BR>
crisis. At the same time, Russia's environment is deteriorating.<BR>
According to the recent State Report on the state of environment,<BR>
&quot;though industrial production continuously decreases, the amounts of<BR>
gaseous, liquid and solid wastes causing environmental impacts are not<BR>
being decreased adequately.&quot; Since the beginning of this millennium,
one<BR>
of the best known Russian sayings is, &quot;enormous resources but horrible<BR>
disorder.&quot; As far as the environmental side of this problem is<BR>
concerned, the reasons for it are the lack of public participation in<BR>
environmental activities and serious gaps in environmental enlightenment<BR>
and education in the broad sense.To change the situation to the better,<BR>
to obtain positive results in environmental protection and nature<BR>
conservation, it is crucially important to determine reasonable and<BR>
intelligible environmental strategy and policy.<BR>
<BR>
If environmental strategy formulates principal aims and objectives,<BR>
environmental policy deals with major instruments needed to implement<BR>
this strategy. Both clear environmental strategy and policy are vitally<BR>
important for the development of environmental practices at local,<BR>
territorial and higher levels. Today, the core principal of the national<BR>
environmental strategy translates to &quot; transition to the model of the<BR>
sustainable development.&quot; Such a definition, rather political, causes<BR>
serious complication not just in understanding current environmental<BR>
aims and objectives, but in their realisation and assessment of results<BR>
achieved. We believe that an efficient national environmental strategy<BR>
ought to be based on the principal of the introduction in our country of<BR>
environmental order. We need to put everything in order: emissions and<BR>
discharges of pollutants and wastes, use of natural resources,<BR>
technological processes, life cycles of major products, etc. It is<BR>
simply impossible to overcome the environmental crisis by any other way<BR>
than solving these tasks. The necessary environmental order has to be<BR>
introduced by real, not overcomplicated and not too expensive, measures.<BR>
In fact, most tools already exist in our country, but they are not used<BR>
efficiently.<BR>
<BR>
To put Russia in environmental order, we have to concentrate on two<BR>
major objectives. First of all, we must introduce rational<BR>
environmental standards (including production restrictions and ethical<BR>
rules) and strictly comply with them. Second of all, we must develop and<BR>
implement environmental projects and programmes with clear aims and<BR>
objectives (beginning with the simplest ones). Expected results should<BR>
be easily assessable and evident to the general public. They should form<BR>
a chain of gradual environmental improvements (at such levels as impact<BR>
factors and wastes, enterprises, protected landscapes, communities,<BR>
etc.). Ways and instruments for the introduction of the desirable<BR>
environmental order are well-known and well-practiced in the world. They<BR>
include environmental auditing, control and management based on public<BR>
and professional environmental education and community involvement. To<BR>
start using these tools we do not have to wait for the economic upsurge.<BR>
We have all the needed pre-requisites and conditions to begin tidying<BR>
Russia up environmentally, right now.<BR>
<BR>
