<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Andersson abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Towards a new ecological world order: a proposal to create a Global
Environmental Organization</H3>
Magnus Andersson<BR>
Institute for Environmental Studies<BR>
Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam<BR>
De Boelelaan 1115,<BR>
1081 HV Amsterdam, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 20 444 9555, FAX: +31 20 444 9553,<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:eapspol@waw.pdi.net">eapspol@waw.pdi.net</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
This article argues that coping with the environmental threats now<BR>
facing humankind will require an effort of scale and vision similar to<BR>
the economic reconstruction after the second world war. However,<BR>
existing international institutions are weak and toothless and our<BR>
national policies are diffused and uncoordinated. Policy gaps,<BR>
confusion, duplication and incoherence are frequent features of global<BR>
environmental affairs. The international environmental policy community<BR>
acts as an emergency squad, responding to crises but unable to achieve<BR>
fundamental change. The UN Commission for Sustainable Development, set<BR>
up after Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro 1992, has been given to narrow<BR>
mandate to change the current ad hoc approach to planetary management.<BR>
Consequently, small battles are (sometimes) won while the big ones -<BR>
such as climate change and loss of biodiversity - are perpetually lost.<BR>
The article proposes the establishment of a Global Environmental<BR>
Organization (GEO) to ensure a systemic and comprehensive worldwide<BR>
response to global environmental issues. The role of the GEO would be to<BR>
constitutionalize the commitment to a sustainable development and the<BR>
long-term interests of humankind just as GATT constitutionalizes the<BR>
commitment to freer trade. Important tasks for the GEO could be:<BR>
<BR>
&#183;to promote cost internalization<BR>
&#183;to coordinate and evaluate the effectiveness and efficiency of ongoing
<BR>
global environmental programmes<BR>
&#183;to reconcile trade and environment disputes with the GATT<BR>
&#183;to initiate strategic actions programmes (regional - e.g. to save
<BR>
Sahel, the rain forests and the Aral Sea - as well as sectoral - e.g. a
<BR>
global sun power programme)<BR>
&#183;to establish an independent funding system (such as a tax on global
<BR>
trade and capital flows)<BR>
<BR>
In the absence of an &quot;interest group&quot; - a strategic partnership
between <BR>
representatives of national governments, international organizations, <BR>
non-governmental organizations as well as the business and research <BR>
communities, it seems unlikely that the institutional vacuum in global <BR>
environmental governance will be filled.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
