<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Cottey abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>A future-oriented course on science and ethics for science students</H3>
Alan Cottey<BR>
School of Physics, University of East Anglia<BR>
Norwich NR4 7TJ, United Kingdom<BR>
FAX: +44 1603 259 515, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:a.cottey@uea.ac.uk">a.cottey@uea.ac.uk
</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
I will describe a course I have given at UEA for six years, called<BR>
Science, Values and Ethics. This is an optional course open to science<BR>
students studying any natural science subject. It differs from the more<BR>
usual academic courses in science and society, science and technology<BR>
studies, and philosophy of science. The fundamental aim is to help the<BR>
students gain the knowledge of cases, the analytical skills, the<BR>
confidence and the courage to address the science and ethics dilemmas<BR>
which they are likely to experience after they graduate. The course is<BR>
seen as an applied one, which will help the students to use wisely the<BR>
technical skills they learn in other courses.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Facing up to humanity's crisis of survival is a central feature of the<BR>
course. How to do this in a way that is meaningful, but not overwhelming<BR>
for the individual, is a major consideration in the design and conduct<BR>
of the course.<BR>
<BR>
I look forward to exchanging ideas with other educators who have<BR>
addressed similar problems in science and engineering education.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
