<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Leal Filho abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Training of engineers for sustainable development: Results of an assessment
of provisions on environmental engineering in European countries</H3>
<BR>
Walter Leal Filho<BR>
European Research and Training Centre on Environmental Education<BR>
Department of Ecology and Environmental Education<BR>
University of L&Uuml;neburg<BR>
Wilschenbrucher Weg 86, 21335 L&uuml;neburg, Deutschland<BR>
TEL: +49 4131 714 202, FAX: +49 4131 714 373 / 714 200<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
It is widely acknowledged that all professions have an impact on <BR>
the environment, although the extent of such an impact varies <BR>
according to the way the work they entail is undertaken. It is<BR>
also acknowledged that such an impact may be minimized by<BR>
raising awareness on the environment, and by introducing <BR>
environmental components as part of professional training.<BR>
Among the pool of professions, the introduction of environmental<BR>
components in the context of the training of engineers is seen as <BR>
an important procedure, especially when it is taken into account<BR>
that the design of buildings and structures, the construction<BR>
of machines and the preparation of development plans can<BR>
potentially cause substantial environmental damages.<BR>
<BR>
As the development of environmental engineering or the training of<BR>
engineers for sustainable development needs to take place on a sound basis,
<BR>
the Programme for Environmental Engineering in Europe (PREENE)<BR>
was designed. Phase 1 of the PREENE project envisaged a survey<BR>
of training provisions and an analysis of training needs and this paper<BR>
presents the results of a survey of training provisions performed among<BR>
a sample of around 3,000 people and institutions from across Europe. Training<BR>
needs were identified and items where PREENE action should be<BR>
focused are listed.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws14edusus.html#anchor725542">workshop 1.4
page</A>.<BR>
