<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Lotter abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Personal environmental impact accounting PEIA software:<BR>
Developing the individual's sense of connection to the Earth</H3>
Don Lotter<BR>
Graduate Group in Ecology<BR>
University of California at Davis<BR>
605 Sunset Ct., Davis, CA 95616 , USA<BR>
TEL: +1 916 756 9156, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:dwlotter@dcn.davis.ca.us">dwlotter@dcn.davis.ca.us</A><BR>
WWW: <A HREF="http://wheel.dcn.davis.ca.us/go/earthaware">http://wheel.dcn.davis.ca.us/go/earthaware</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Personal environmental impact assessment (PEIA), which<BR>
quantitatively relates an individual's lifestyle to the local, regional,<BR>
and global environment, is potentially an important step in the<BR>
development of effective tools for sustainable living systems.<BR>
EarthAware, a recently developed graphical PC software program, will be<BR>
demonstrated and the strengths as well as challenges of the PEIA<BR>
approach presented.<BR>
<BR>
Presentation Description: Recently developed software for personal<BR>
environmental impact assessment (PEIA), in which individuals identify<BR>
and quantify their direct and indirect linkages to the biosphere, is<BR>
potentially an important step in the development of effective tools for<BR>
moving toward sustainable living systems. PEIA is effective because it<BR>
prompts an individual or household to quantify all of their interactions<BR>
with the earth, both indirect (via consumerism) and direct, and then<BR>
correlates those quantities to a tangible environmental &quot;score.&quot;
The<BR>
environmental score can be used to set goals and to compare and contrast<BR>
lifestyles. In economist's terms, the PEIA process is an &quot;externality&quot;<BR>
accounting system, a system for accounting for the costs of consumption<BR>
that are not included in the market system.<BR>
<BR>
EarthAware software, and its predecessor, EnviroAccount (1992), both<BR>
developed by University of California ecology graduate student Donald<BR>
Lotter, are being used in over 400 high schools, universities, museums,<BR>
environmental centers and homes around the US and the world. EarthAware<BR>
evaluates an individual or a household in six areas: 
<OL>
  <LI>Home Energy and Utilities, 
  <LI>Transportation, 
  <LI>Consumerism, 
  <LI>Waste, 
  <LI>Advocacy, and 
  <LI>Land Use/Family Planning. 
</OL>
<BR>
EarthAware is designed to both educate as well as catalyze lifestyle<BR>
change. Each topic in the audit is accompanied by supportive<BR>
informational resources as well as links to the World Wide Web which<BR>
augment the subject in question. EarthAware connects to the the World<BR>
Wide Web via the user's Internet link which enables immediate and<BR>
up-to-date consumer and environmental information.<BR>
<BR>
The EarthAware analysis, both on screen and printed, outputs: - a score<BR>
consisting of Impact and Action points, - a humorous rating ranging from<BR>
Eco-Titan to Eco-Tyrannosaurus rex, - a personal carbon dioxide budget<BR>
(kg CO2 per year) which relates the user's energy use to global warming,<BR>
- charts and graphs.<BR>
<BR>
In the proposed session, the PEIA process will be demonstrated using<BR>
EarthAware software projected onto a screen. Critical and challenging<BR>
areas of the PEIA process will be discussed.<BR>
<BR>
For further information please check the <A HREF="http://wheel.dcn.davis.ca.us/go/earthaware">EarthAware
World Wide Web page</A>.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws14edusus.html#anchor725542">workshop 1.4
page</A>.<BR>
