</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Wals abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Environmental education for empowerment: educational pathways towards
sustainability</H3>
<BR>
Arjen E.J. Wals<BR>
Department of Education, Wageningen Agricultural University<BR>
P.O. Box 8130, 6700 EW Wageningen, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 317 484 184, FAX: +31 317 484 763<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:awals@igc.apc.org">awals@igc.apc.org</A> or <A HREF="mailto:Arjen.Wals@alg.ao.wau.nl">Arjen.Wals@alg.ao.wau.nl</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
This paper will discuss an alternative approach to environmental<BR>
education which combines elements of action research and community<BR>
problem solving (AR&amp;CPS). The underlying assumptions of &auml;&Ouml;small<BR>
AR&amp;CPS will be highlighted and the evolution of the model since its<BR>
inception in Michigan in 1987 will be discussed and illustrated by its<BR>
various uses in school-based environmental education (Stapp et al.,<BR>
1996).<BR>
<BR>
A main thesis is that environmental education can be a catalyst of<BR>
sustainable development in local communities as long as it is recognized<BR>
that communities have different challenges and needs (Wals, in press).<BR>
Froma perspective of sustainable development environmental education<BR>
can be broadly defined as the process that enables students and teachers<BR>
to participate in the planning, implementation, and evaluation of<BR>
educational activities aimed at resolving an environmental issue that<BR>
they themselves have identified. What an &quot;environmental issue&quot;
is, then,<BR>
depends on the perceptions and earlier experiences of the learner as<BR>
well as the context in which education takes place.<BR>
<BR>
The argument for including problem-solving and action-taking in<BR>
environmental education is threefold. First, one could argue that many<BR>
young people, as is the case with many adults, are overwhelmed by<BR>
environmental, including social, problems as a result of their personal<BR>
exposure to these problems in real-life, for instance, through the ever<BR>
present media. It is important to help students explore environmental<BR>
issues and to provide them with an understanding of the nature and the<BR>
complexity of these problems. However, environmental education should<BR>
not be limited to this for it then could easily feed feelings of apathy<BR>
and powerlessness. By bringing in the action-taking component students<BR>
can, under certain conditions, begin to take charge of some of these<BR>
issues and develop a sense of power and control. This sense of power and<BR>
control is an essential ingredient of empowerment which here is defined<BR>
as the feeling of power and control one experiences when influencing or<BR>
shaping the world of which one is part.<BR>
<BR>
A second argument for including action-taking in an environmental<BR>
education project has its roots in experiential learning thought: one<BR>
never comes to fully understand a problem with all its nuances and<BR>
complexities until one fully immerses oneself into the problem,<BR>
identifies all the players and begins to work within the 'force field'<BR>
or field of interferences towards a joint solution. On the same token<BR>
one could say that we may never really understand the problem until we<BR>
start to actually implement some potential solutions.<BR>
<BR>
Finally, it could be argued that without the ability and willingness to<BR>
act it is impossible to participate in or, rather, to contribute to a<BR>
democratic society. As Jensen and Schnack (1994) point out a concern for<BR>
the environment should be connected to a concern for democracy.<BR>
<BR>
In short, environmental education should be a learning process that<BR>
seeks to enable participants to construct, transform, criticize, and<BR>
emancipate their world in an existential way. Construct in the sense of<BR>
building upon the prior knowledge, experiences and ideas of the learner.<BR>
Transform in the sense of changing, shaping, influencing the world<BR>
around them, regardless of scope or scale. Criticize in the sense of<BR>
investigating underlying values, assumptions, world views, morals, etc.,<BR>
as they are a part of the world around the learner and are a part of the<BR>
learner her/himself. Emancipate in the sense of detecting, exposing and,<BR>
where possible, altering power distortions that impede communication and<BR>
change.<BR>
<BR>
Key references: 
<OL>
  <LI>Bardwell, L.V., Monroe, M.C. &amp; M.T. Tudor (1994) Environmental
Problem Solving: theory, practice and possibilities in environmental education.
Troy, Ohio, NAAEE. 
  <LI>Jensen, B.B. &amp; K. Schnack (eds) 1994. Action and action competence
as key concepts in critical pedagogy. Didaktische studier, Volume 12. Kopenhagen,
Royal Danish School for Educational Studies. 
  <LI>Stapp, W.B., Wals, A.E.J. &Ouml;&amp; Stankorb. S. (1996) Environmental
education for empowerment: action research and community problem solving.
Iowa, Kendall/Hunt Publishing. 
  <LI>Wals, A.E.J., Beringer, A. &amp; W.B. Stapp (1990) Education in Action
a Community Problem Solving Program for Schools. Journal for Environmental
Education, 21; 4, 13-20. 
  <LI>Wals, A.E.J. (1994) Pollution Stinks! Young adolescents' perceptions
of nature and environmental issues with implications for education in urban
settings. Academic Book Center, ABC, De Lier. 
  <LI>Wals, A.E.J. (in press) Back-alley sustainability and the role of
environmental education. Local Environment, 1 (3). 
</OL>
<BR>
