<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Knapen abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Sustainable development in practice at the University of Nijmegen</H3>
Marjo J. Knapen<BR>
Department of Environmental Studies, Faculty of Science<BR>
University of Nijmegen<BR>
Toernooiveld 1, 6525 ED Nijmegen, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 24 365 2923, FAX: +31 24 355 3450,<BR>
E-MAIL: mknapen@sci.kun.nl<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
In Agenda 21 of the World Conference on Environment and Development in<BR>
Rio de Janeiro in 1992 the United Nations recommended the integration of<BR>
the subjects Environment and Development in education and research<BR>
programmes. Rectors of European Universities have elaborated the<BR>
intentions of Agenda 21 in the university charter for sustainable<BR>
development, also called COPERNICUS (CO-operation Programme in Europe<BR>
for Research on Nature and Industry through Coordinated University<BR>
Studies).<BR>
<BR>
The charter contains ten principles of action on sustainable development<BR>
in research, education and management. The Rector of the University of<BR>
Nijmegen signed the COPERNICUS charter in 1993. Some principles of<BR>
action were already implemented then. In 1992 the university made an<BR>
Environmental policy plan. By doing so the university showed commitment<BR>
to the principle and practice of environmental protection and<BR>
sustainable development. Projects were started to list and reduce the<BR>
pollution from laboratories and offices of the university. Sustainable<BR>
consumption patterns and an ecological lifestyle were promoted. For<BR>
example canteens don't sell their products in plastic anymore and all<BR>
the paper that is used at the university is recycled, even the official<BR>
letter paper and envelopes.<BR>
<BR>
Official environmental education programmes for students were started in<BR>
1991, but already in 1979 the first interdisciplinary environmental<BR>
education modules were taught. Environmental research was first<BR>
developed within different disciplines, like Biology and Urban and Rural<BR>
Planning. In 1991 departments for environmental research were founded<BR>
within the Faculty of Science and the Faculty of Policy Sciences. The<BR>
University Centre of Environmental Sciences was also founded in 1991 to<BR>
coordinate environmental education and research.<BR>
<BR>
To implement the Charter for sustainable development at the University<BR>
of Nijmegen a project was started in Februari 1996. The goal of this<BR>
project is to develop a feasible plan of action to implement all of the<BR>
principles of action of the charter at the university. To be able to<BR>
determine the progress of the implementation, the charter is first<BR>
transposed in measurable principles of action. Secondly the networks of<BR>
research and education at the university are to be listed and the<BR>
situation at other universities is looked at. Then an ideal picture of<BR>
sustainable development in education, research and management at the<BR>
university will be drawn.<BR>
<BR>
During the whole project communication with managers, teachers,<BR>
researchers and students is important. The actual state of the<BR>
implementation of sustainable development will also be drawn. Finally<BR>
the ideal picture will be compared to the actual situation and a<BR>
feasible plan of action will be developed and presented to the board of<BR>
the university. The project is guided by a COPERNICUS working group<BR>
chaired by the Rector of the university; members are the chairman and<BR>
the coordinator of the University Centre of Environmental Studies, the<BR>
environmental management coordinator, the chairperson of the Faculty of<BR>
Arts and a student.<BR>
<BR>
During the workshop the situation at the University of Nijmegen will be<BR>
drawn and the measurable principles of action and the ideal picture of<BR>
sustainable development at a university will be presented. Finally the<BR>
plan of action for a university like Nijmegen, with a large diversity of<BR>
education and research programmes will be shown and discussed.<BR>
<BR>
