<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: van der Loo abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Education for sustainability: experiences from the EPCEM</H3>
<BR>
Frans A. van der Loo and Egbert Tellegen<BR>
Interfaculty Department of Environmental Science IVAM <BR>
Universiteit van Amsterdam<BR>
Nieuwe Prinsengracht 130, 1018 VZ Amsterdam, Nederland <BR>
TEL: +31 20 525 6206, FAX: +31 20 525 6272,<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:linpi@ivip.frw.uva.nl">linpi@ivip.frw.uva.nl </A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Introduction<BR>
<BR>
The Brundtland report &quot;Our common future&quot; (1987) calls for a<BR>
strengthening of international cooperation, as one of the required steps<BR>
towards sustainable development. Since 1992 the European Postgraduate<BR>
Course in environmental management (EPCEM) contributes to this very<BR>
goal. The EPCEM, a one-year full-time Master Training is organised by a<BR>
joint venture of Dutch universities and was originally meant for<BR>
participants from Central and Eastern European countries. An advisory<BR>
network of universities in Central and Eastern Europe has been<BR>
established. The course was based on the expertise built up in an<BR>
equivalent postgraduate course for Dutch participants (UBM) since 1987.<BR>
Gradually the interaction between the two courses has intensified and<BR>
from 1995/96 on there is just one integrated international course for<BR>
participants from all over Europe. Participants from various countries<BR>
and with varying disciplinary backgrounds work and learn together. This<BR>
paper will report on the highlights and pitfalls of this (geographically<BR>
and disciplinarily) transboundary education for sustainability,.<BR>
<BR>
Features<BR>
<BR>
Strong features of EPCEM are: international and interdisciplinary.<BR>
Participants from various countries and from various disciplinary<BR>
backgrounds work and learn together during a 10-months curriculum, The<BR>
postgraduate training focuses on the practice of environmental policy or<BR>
management; EPCEM prepares graduates to participate in environmental<BR>
policy making and to cooperate with experts in multidisciplinary teams.<BR>
Cooperation in working groups, active participation in a project team<BR>
and skills trainings (meeting skills, oral presentation, writing,<BR>
project-management) are key-elements of the course. Part of the course<BR>
is a 4-months, international research project (in a multidisciplinary<BR>
team) focusing on an environmental issue somewhere in Europe.<BR>
<BR>
Lessons learned<BR>
<BR>
This international and interdisciplinary education presents exciting<BR>
experiences. Some of these are mentioned below. A more extensive report<BR>
will be given in the full paper.<BR>
<BR>
&#183;Participants are very eager to work together with people from<BR>
different nationalities. They learn from each other. On the other hand,<BR>
the different backgrounds and traditions pose some problems to smooth<BR>
cooperation.<BR>
&#183; With respect to the participative attitude, there are big differences<BR>
among participants. Those from Eastern Europe are less familiar with<BR>
this participative type of education than those from e.g.&uuml;the<BR>
Netherlands.<BR>
&#183;Gradually during the course most participants start appreciating this<BR>
method greatly.<BR>
&#183; During their academic education most people are trained to make<BR>
individual studies and reports. Working in a project team with shared<BR>
responsibility, resulting in one joint policy report, apparently<BR>
requires very different skills.<BR>
&#183;Running international projects is challenging but complicated as well.<BR>
&#183;Understanding each others different historical, cultural and<BR>
environmental contexts throughout Europe is a great contribution to<BR>
sustainability.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws14edusus.html#anchor725542">workshop 1.4
page</A>.<BR>
