<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Bitzer et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Limits to Growth -- Coping with the consequences</H3>
<BR>
J&uuml;rgen Bitzer and J&uuml;rgen Blazejczak<BR>
Deutsches Institut f&uuml;r Wirtschaftsforschung<BR>
K&ouml;nigin-Luise-Str. 5, 14191 Berlin, Deutschland<BR>
TEL: +49 30 89 789 359, FAX: +49 30 89 789 200, <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:jblaze@diw-berlin.de">jblaze@diw-berlin.de</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
It is widely accepted that attaining sustainability requires a ceiling<BR>
on the use of natural resources (including the capacity of the<BR>
environment to absorb pollutants) at least in industrialized countries.<BR>
It is also generally accepted that this will have some costs in terms of<BR>
foregone GNP. How much economic growth will slow down depends on the<BR>
extent to which the efficiency of the utilization of natural resources<BR>
can be increased. In our paper we bypass this question. Nor will we<BR>
discuss the relation between conventionally measured economic growth and<BR>
well-being. We rather address the issue what the most important<BR>
consequences of no-growth would be and how economies of industrialized<BR>
countries could cope with them.<BR>
<BR>
This question has been intensively discussed during the seventies and<BR>
eighties. The outcome suggested rather severe consequences in particular<BR>
for employment, and public finance including the social security system.<BR>
<BR>
This debate focused on a deliberate restriction of growth, however. It<BR>
thus couldn't take account of endogenous mechanisms working towards<BR>
mitigating unwarranted consequences.<BR>
<BR>
Our paper argues that the utilization of economic instruments for<BR>
attaining sustainability incentives will endogenously trigger mechanisms<BR>
which will counteract negative consequences of lower GNP growth. We<BR>
illustrate our argument by characterizing the forces operating towards a<BR>
lower increase of labor productivity if a shift of relative prices, e.g.<BR>
through eco-taxes, creates incentives to concentrate on increasing<BR>
material and energy instead of labor efficiency.<BR>
<BR>
We conclude that systematically searching for endogenous mechanisms and<BR>
developing possibilities to strengthen them may remove an important obstacle<BR>
to attaining sustainability.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws21ecodim.html#anchor46883">workshop 2,1
page</A>.<BR>
