</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Ermolenko abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Structural ecological and economic optimisation as means of sustainable
development</H3>
<BR>
Boris V. Ermolenko<BR>
Associate Professor, Head of the Ecological Economics Research Laboratory<BR>
Industrial Ecology Department<BR>
D. Mendeleyev University of Chemical Technology<BR>
9 Miusskay sq., Moskwa, 125047, Rossia<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:ermo@mhti.msk.su">ermo@mhti.msk.su</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Without radical change in the structure of production there is<BR>
no chance of achieving a stable ecological and economic situation in<BR>
Russia. This goal can be achieved in various ways. Each variant can<BR>
differ from an alternative one in the composition of the natural<BR>
resources used, the level of resource and power consumption and saving,<BR>
the composition of harmful substances and level of contamination of the<BR>
environment, the duration of the production-economic-technological<BR>
cycle, the quality of the products, the territorial location of the<BR>
production objects, etc.<BR>
<BR>
The problem of structural ecological and economic optimisation can<BR>
be formulated as follows. Select:<BR>
<BR>
&#183; the composition of production-economic-technological schemes<BR>
determining the structure of the economy and ensuring the required<BR>
volumes of manufacturing the products;<BR>
&#183; the directions, volumes, and dynamics of making investments into<BR>
the development of technology, environment-protecting activities, and<BR>
infrastructure;<BR>
&#183; the volumes of consumption of resources, production of products and<BR>
intermediates for each scheme ensuring a transition to a stable state of<BR>
the ecological and economic system with the minimum consumption of<BR>
natural resources and action on the environment (when there are<BR>
limitations on the reserves of resources and level of contamination).<BR>
<BR>
The problem can be reduced to one of mathematical programming in a<BR>
multilevel quasi-dynamic formulation. At the global level, the<BR>
optimisation model is based on a matrix model of the interindustry<BR>
balance in a group assortment with the inclusion of an ecological and<BR>
environment-protecting blocks. The models of the branch of industry<BR>
level are formed as ones of the linear programming with variables<BR>
corresponding to the specific kinds of products manufactured at specific<BR>
enterprises according to one of alternative technologies. The<BR>
characteristics of the model for a regional level are consideration of<BR>
the territorial, ecological, and economic limitations. At an enterprise<BR>
level, it will be possible to solve problems of operative planning and<BR>
control with the restrictions obtained in solving the problems of the<BR>
industry and regional levels.<BR>
<BR>
An especially significant economic and ecological result can be<BR>
obtained for multi-assortment branches of chemical industry (of organic<BR>
intermediates and dyes, chemical means of plant protection, drugs,<BR>
chemical reagents, etc.).<BR>
<BR>
Blocks of suppliers of resources, manufacturers and consumers of<BR>
products are singled out. Each block includes restrictions on the volume<BR>
of products, their consumer characteristic, the use of technological<BR>
equipment, the consumption of raw materials, fuel and energy, the<BR>
possibilities of using equipment for environmental protection, the level<BR>
of maximum permissible discharges of contaminants, the possibilities of<BR>
burial, storage, destruction of solid wastes, the capital investments in<BR>
production and environment protection, etc.<BR>
<BR>
The maximum ecological and economic benefits for national economy<BR>
might be used as the main criterion of optimisation.<BR>
<BR>
The model of the system is reduced to a model of linear programming.<BR>
For non-linear models, algorithms of consecutive linearization and<BR>
stepwise solution of linear tasks are proposed. To avoid a large<BR>
dimension, methods of decomposition and aggregation of the models with a<BR>
view to the specific nature of the objects and problems being solved<BR>
were developed.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws21ecodim.html#anchor46883">workshop 2,1
page</A>.<BR>
