<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Duijnhouwer abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Strategies for sustainable resource management</H3>
<BR>
Frans Duijnhouwer<BR>
RMNO <BR>
P.O. Box 5306, 2280 HH Rijswijk, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 70 336 4318, <BR>
FAX: +31 70 336 4300, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:RMNO@xs4all.nl">RMNO@xs4all.nl</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
This paper describes elements of a strategy for sustainable resource<BR>
management. The paper starts with a brief introduction and a description<BR>
of some basic concepts. Next it describes some global trends in<BR>
resource use. Finally it will focus on some possible strategies for<BR>
resource management.<BR>
<BR>
1. Introduction<BR>
<BR>
For decades, natural scientists, economists and others have discussed<BR>
the question of the likelihood of the exhaustion of resources. These<BR>
discussions mostly focused on non-renewable resources. Only recently has<BR>
much more attention been paid to renewable resources and to<BR>
environmental resources in the form of sinks which the environment<BR>
provides for waste and pollution. Moreover much more emphasis is being<BR>
put on the use of resources in relation to the links between different<BR>
phases of production and consumption both in the North as well as in the<BR>
South. Nevertheless, the key question that remains is whether current<BR>
trends in resource use are likely to lead to an exhaustion of either<BR>
renewable and non-renewable resources or the capacity of the environment<BR>
to collect waste and accumulate pollution. The next question is what<BR>
sustainable development means in terms of levels of use of resources and<BR>
appropriate management schemes; the answer to these questions of course<BR>
will differ in cases where (essential) resources are in jeopardy of<BR>
being depleted, as oppose to other cases where the risk is not present.<BR>
But questions of management and optimum use pertain to renewable<BR>
resources as well.<BR>
<BR>
2. Concepts<BR>
<BR>
For a fruitful (international) discussion on sustainable resource<BR>
management and resource use it is essential to agree on some basic<BR>
concepts like sustainability and resources. UNCEDs interpretation of<BR>
sustainable development has forged strong links between environmental<BR>
protection, social equity and economic growth. However, there is<BR>
disagreement among experts on the consequences of this approach for<BR>
sustainable management.<BR>
<BR>
Resources include depletable, renewable (wood, food etc.) and non-<BR>
renewable (minerals, fossil energy, biological diversity) resources.<BR>
Besides these flows coming from sources in the natural environment, the<BR>
environment also provides (passive and active) sinks (environmental<BR>
resources like clean water and clean air) in which waste and pollution<BR>
can collect and accumulate.<BR>
<BR>
3. Trends in resource use<BR>
<BR>
The combination of economic growth and population growth has increased<BR>
resource use very rapidly over the past half century and especially over<BR>
the past 25 years. The current use of most resources is very unequally<BR>
distributed between the rich and the poor part of the world and among<BR>
rich countries as well. However, the trends in growth rates of the use<BR>
of most resources in the North and the South is the opposite of the<BR>
present consumption patterns, namely increasing growth rates in the<BR>
South and stabilizing or declining growth rates in the North.<BR>
<BR>
4. Strategies<BR>
<BR>
The current trends in resource use should be designated as<BR>
unsustainable. We have to come to grips with the nature and<BR>
characteristics of this overexploitation and resulting degradation.<BR>
Major elements of such strategies are integrated chain management and<BR>
trade and other policy instruments.<BR>
<BR>
Integrated chain management<BR>
<BR>
The management of resources is turning from supply management towards<BR>
life-cycle and cascade-based analysis management. All stages of the<BR>
life-cycle of primary materials have to be considered to achieve<BR>
efficiency improvements, the prevention of emissions and waste and<BR>
the increase of recycling possibilities.<BR>
<BR>
Trade and other policy instruments<BR>
<BR>
International trade divorces the consumption of products from the local<BR>
environmental damage associated with their production. Environmental<BR>
damage is usually not reflected in international market prices. In<BR>
developing countries this was partly because internalisation of<BR>
environmental costs would increase production costs without any parallel<BR>
increase in world market prices, since producers were largely the price<BR>
takers. International Commodity-Related Environmental Agreements,<BR>
eco-labelling, environmental taxes, property rights, resource pricing,<BR>
user charges are possible instruments.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws21ecodim.html#anchor1111591">workshop 2,1
page</A>.<BR>
