<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Rosewarne et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Towards a managed international trade for sustainable development: A
critique of ecological economic interventions</H3>
<BR>
Stuart Rosewarne<BR>
Department of Economics, The University of Sydney<BR>
NSW 2006, Australia<BR>
TEL: +61 2 351 2492, FAX: +61 2 552 1118<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:stuartr@bullwinkle.econ.su.oz.au">stuartr@bullwinkle.econ.su.oz.au</A><BR>
<BR>
Michel Damian<BR>
Institut d'Economique et de Politique de l'Energie <BR>
Universit&eacute; Pierre Mend&egrave;s France,<BR>
UFR Facult&eacute; des Sciences Economiques<BR>
1241, rue des R&Eacute;sidences, PB 47, 38040 Grenoble Cedex 9, France<BR>
TEL: +33 76 82 54 58, FAX: +33 76 82 59 95 <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:calvert@grenet.fr">calvert@grenet.fr</A> or <A HREF="mailto:Mauvy@grenet.fr">Mauvy@grenet.fr</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Ecological economists have begun to formulate a penetrating critique of<BR>
orthodox economics that the liberalisation of global trade engenders<BR>
unambiguous environmental benefits. The critique is wide ranging, taking<BR>
issue with some of the fundamental premises of the conventional theory<BR>
of free trade. These include the notions: that freer trade generates<BR>
economic benefits, and that the associated economic growth is equivalent<BR>
to welfare enhancement; that economic growth provides a more substantial<BR>
foundation for addressing environmental problems; that comparative<BR>
advantage spawns a specialisation in resource utilisation that is more<BR>
efficient and, therefore, better for the environment; that the greater<BR>
specialisation associated with market liberalisation provides an impetus<BR>
to the economic growth of the developing countries which will enable<BR>
these countries to escape the currently ecologically unsustainable<BR>
economic practices.<BR>
<BR>
Contra the policy prescriptions of the free trade advocates, ecological<BR>
economists have argued the case for managed solutions formed around a<BR>
broadly defined conception of sustainable development. These include:<BR>
the more systematic and universal internalisation of environmental<BR>
costs, including the hidden cost of transport associated with<BR>
international trade and the abolition of all environmental subsidies; a<BR>
more critical scrutiny of the (environmental) bases of comparative<BR>
advantage and checks on international capital flows as well as<BR>
regulating transnational corporations; limits on economic growth and an<BR>
emphasis upon a more qualitative development path that ensures the<BR>
sustainability of the developing economies; a much greater degree of<BR>
national economic self-sufficiency and a diminished focus on<BR>
international trade; and, institutional mechanisms in both national and<BR>
international arenas that ensure the fulfilment of these general policy<BR>
recommendations. The ecological economists approach is represented as a<BR>
balanced solution to the unsustainability of current global economic<BR>
relations.<BR>
<BR>
It is balanced insofar as it does seek to carve a middle ground<BR>
between a system of unregulated global trade and relatively<BR>
self-contained national economies by laying the foundations for a<BR>
regulated international trading system that endows nation-states and<BR>
national communities with an enhanced authority over domestic affairs.<BR>
Yet the principal contention of this paper is that the critique,<BR>
while representing a radical challenge to the orthodoxy, does not go<BR>
far enough in its critique. This paper seeks to explore this concern<BR>
in the context of the status of the national economy in the<BR>
international political economy and what this means for the management<BR>
of sustainability. There are two dimensions upon which we will focus.<BR>
<BR>
The first addresses the issue of securing global sustainability while<BR>
ensuring that the foundations for national economic self-sufficiency are<BR>
secured for all of the constituent components of the international<BR>
polity. This is a question that seeks to take up the issue of the<BR>
sustainability of national economies by addressing the issue of global<BR>
resource allocation within a framework of equity considerations. The<BR>
second explores the adequacy of recommended national management<BR>
strategies by focusing on the failure of the ecological economists to<BR>
examine the institutional bases for valuing the economic process. Here<BR>
we are concerned with scrutinising the principal institutional edifices<BR>
around which the economic process is organised. We develop a critique of<BR>
the form of the state and its place in economic management. We address,<BR>
as well, the continued emphasis upon economic valuations of processes<BR>
that are not organised within the market, alongside an appreciation of<BR>
the constitution of the economic process as capital. We show how this is<BR>
predominantly organised institutionally, and how this circumscribes the<BR>
definition of what is to be valued.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
