<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Aubauer abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Indispensable components of a sustainable economic and law politics</H3>
<BR>
Hans P. Aubauer<BR>
Institut f&uuml;r Materialphysik der Universit&auml;t Wien<BR>
Boltzmanngasse 5, 1090 Wien, &Ouml;sterreich<BR>
TEL: +43 222 313 67 / 3240, +43 40 789 41, <BR>
FAX: +43 1 31 31 00 183 <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
A &quot;sustainable development (SD)&quot; is seen here as the<BR>
development of the present state of society and economy<BR>
to an indefinitely sustainable state. From this, the goals of SD are derived.<BR>
They are equivalent to a reduction of the consumption of energy<BR>
and matter as well as the utilisation of soil to rates,<BR>
that can be sustained indefinitely. This reduction is performed within <BR>
an optimal period, that can be derived from the need that present <BR>
economicprofits are not gained at thecost of future ones. An <BR>
attempt is madeto solve the conflicts between these goals of SD <BR>
and those of present economic politics, especially economic growth.<BR>
<BR>
The goals of SD can be pursued within a democracy by changing<BR>
the economic and legal frame, within which companies and individuals<BR>
are embedded. Those changes should bring their own interests in accord <BR>
with the goals of SD. The indispensable components of these changes <BR>
are derived.<BR>
<BR>
These components contain a complete step-like transition of the present<BR>
taxation of labour and profits to those of the consumption of energy,<BR>
matter and the utilisation of soil within the optimal period.<BR>
Proposals are presented, in order to avoid disadvantages for the energy-,<BR>
matter-, and soil-intensive production, as well as for those with<BR>
lower incomes.<BR>
<BR>
Thereby answers to the following questions are attempted:<BR>
<BR>
&#183;How is it possible to change an industrialised country<BR>
(or region) to sustainable state, if the surrounding world continues<BR>
to develop towards an ecological breakdown?<BR>
<BR>
&#183;Does the SD of a region without co-operation of the<BR>
rest of the world necessarily lead to a drop of material income, or<BR>
quality of life?<BR>
<BR>
&#183;How does the scenario of sustainable state look like?<BR>
<BR>
&#183;What global effects follow from an exclusive transition of a<BR>
small industrialised region to sustainability? Are there any?<BR>
<BR>
&#183;How to modify the treaty of the European Union (EU),<BR>
that of the World Trade Organisation (WTO) and the General<BR>
Agreement of Tariffs and Trade (GATT), in order to incorporate<BR>
the indispensable components of a sustainable economic and law<BR>
politics?<BR>
<BR>
&#183;How to avoid the &quot;tragedy of the commons&quot; with the aid of
the<BR>
&quot;polluter pays principle&quot;?<BR>
<BR>
&#183;How to establish the efficacy of the &quot;invisible hand&quot; by
Adam<BR>
Smith?<BR>
<BR>
&#183;Is there an &quot;optimal&quot; population density? If yes, how is
it<BR>
achievable?<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws21ecodim.html">workshop 2,1 page</A>.<BR>
