<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Beetstra abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3><BR>
Beyond LCA: sustainability analysis of buildings. Towards a broad and practical
method for a comprehensive sustainability analysis of a building, including
its sites' aspects on the basis of a limited set of objectively computable
indicators</H3>
<BR>
Ferdinand Beetstra<BR>
University Centre for Building Development, BPU<BR>
Eindhoven University of Technology<BR>
P.O. Box 513, 5600 MB, Eindhoven, Nederland<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:f.f.beetstra@bpu.tue.nl">f.f.beetstra@bpu.tue.nl</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Key Words: LCA, indicators, material flows, environmental impact, <BR>
sustainable building <BR>
<BR>
Each year 3 billion tons are transformed into foundations, walls, floors<BR>
and roofs. These huge material streams change landscapes drastically, <BR>
use up nature and living space, and as a consequence bring about a <BR>
serious degradation and transformation of ecosystems.<BR>
<BR>
But how much of an environmental burden is a building? And what is the<BR>
impact of an &quot;environmentally friendly&quot; measurement on the environmental<BR>
load? The lack of a tool that indicates how much of a burden a building<BR>
induces is an important obstacle to making better designs and<BR>
maintenance decisions from an environmental perspective. The<BR>
environmental impact of all the material streams and other environmental<BR>
inputs and outputs for products could be determined in principal by<BR>
means of an environmental life-cycle assessment methodology - &auml;&Ouml;small<BR>
LCA -. With the LCAs there still are many problems, however,<BR>
in relation to the assessment of the use and consumption of (nature)<BR>
space and land, and regarding the acquiring of objective input data.<BR>
Furthermore the environmental impact induced by a building is far more<BR>
than the sum of the materials. Considering the problems surrounding the<BR>
definition of physical, measurable environmental measures for many<BR>
relevant effects, a broad environmental assessment of a building is -<BR>
for the time being - not possible with LCA.<BR>
<BR>
For clients and designers in the building trade, it would be useful if<BR>
the environmental impact induced by a building could be represented<BR>
by a well-defined environmental profile. Such a profile has to be<BR>
composed of a limited set of objective, quantitive and verifiable <BR>
indicators, in which each indicator encompasses a certain part of <BR>
the sustainability spectrum or environmental impact. We believe that <BR>
an integral environment profile could consist of a set of eight <BR>
indicators: 3 site oriented, 3 building oriented, and 2 aimed at <BR>
building parts.<BR>
<BR>
A. Site oriented: use of space, oxygen balance and accessibility.<BR>
B. Building oriented: water balance, energy balance and Sick Building <BR>
Syndrome.<BR>
C. Building part and material oriented: material use balance and reuse <BR>
balance.<BR>
<BR>
A comparison between the proposed set and LCA indicates, that<BR>
all relevant LCA aspects have been incorporated in the set.<BR>
However, by contrast the environmental aspects that are connected to<BR>
four indicators, i.e.&uuml;use of space, oxygen balance, accessibility,
water<BR>
balance, cannot be worked out adequately in a LCA for<BR>
buildings. Furthermore, the LCA pays no attention to the<BR>
physical aspects that influence the human well-being in a building. An<BR>
environmental valuation with the proposed method therefore has a larger<BR>
assessment area than that is covered with conducting LCA<BR>
nowadays, gives more insight in the environmental load aspects and is<BR>
more practical.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
