<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: B&ouml;hm abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3><BR>
&quot;Urban structural units survey&quot; as a tool for designing spatial
strategies for environmental management</H3>
<BR>
Peter B&ouml;hm<BR>
UFZ Centre for Environmental Research Leipzig-Halle<BR>
P.O. Box 2, 04301 Leipzig, Deutschland<BR>
FAX: +49 341 235 2534, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:pboehm@pro.ufz.de">pboehm@pro.ufz.de</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
If we are striving for a sustainable common future, as pleaded by the<BR>
Brundtland Comission (1987), then we have to develop strategies for a<BR>
ecologically sound urban development. Conceptions for an enduring success<BR>
of city-planning demand an early discerning of conflicts and their<BR>
solutions, i.e.&uuml;far-seeing strategies, patterns and models for an effective<BR>
economical and ecological management, and the design of attractive and<BR>
healthy cities.<BR>
<BR>
Various researchs take the typical modifying effects of land utilization<BR>
pattern on the abiotic, biotic, cultural and social environment into<BR>
account. Hence, form of land use and structural state of the urban area
are<BR>
indicators for the ecological state and can therefore be used as reference<BR>
units for environmental characteristics. Urban structural units are<BR>
compatible to administrative works and action strategies. Hence, urban<BR>
structural units can be a useful tool for planners for the identification<BR>
of conflicts and deficits in the environmental state of areas, and for the<BR>
design of action plans.<BR>
<BR>
The approach &quot;urban structural units survey&quot; as a universal tool
for<BR>
designing spatial strategies for sustainable human settlement management<BR>
was tested for Leipzig (Germany) and Mendoza (Argentina). The concept<BR>
consists of various steps:<BR>
spatial analysis of structural units / indicator analysis / defining<BR>
environmental aims / recommendations for urban planning strategies.<BR>
A high level of abstraction of the methodology provides compatibility and<BR>
comparability, and hence an global and general applicability of the<BR>
methodology.<BR>
<BR>
The spatial analysis of the cities was completed by defining and mapping<BR>
structural units (green, residential, business area) with aero-photographs<BR>
(Leipzig) and remote sensing analysis (Mendoza) In the next step, the<BR>
ecologically characterization of the structural units, a quantitative and<BR>
qualitative analysis of typical patterns by means of indicators was<BR>
designed. The most appropriate set of indicators was specified. Case<BR>
studies of selected representative cells of structural units were carried<BR>
out to investigate the units in detail.<BR>
<BR>
On the basis of the indicator data, the environmental state of the<BR>
structural units was evaluated. The evaluation pointed out areas of<BR>
deficits and conflicts and lead to the design of regionalized environmental<BR>
aims for selected patterns. The results will be integrated to a concept
for<BR>
a sustainable development for each city (e.g.&uuml;Environmental Aims of
the<BR>
Municipality of Leipzig). Action strategies for the optimization of the<BR>
ecological state can so be proposed. The ultimate aim is a set of<BR>
recommended measures, transferable to government agencies for urban<BR>
environmental management, to contribute it to an environmentally sound<BR>
development at the level of each evolving urban structural unit.<BR>
<BR>
The urban structural units can be a useful tool for planners for the<BR>
identification of conflicts and deficits in the urban environmental state.<BR>
The designed methodological approach is not only locally, but globally<BR>
applicable. A set of recommendations and strategies, transferable to the<BR>
local government agencies for a sustainable urban environmental management<BR>
can be designed.<BR>
<BR>
Reference:<BR>
J. Breuste, Project Area of Urban Landscapes, UFZ Centre for<BR>
Environmental Research Leipzig-Halle Ltd, Subproject ENV 13b: Urban<BR>
bioclimatic factors and their impact on sustainable urban development<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws22criind.html#anchor76368">workshop 2,2
page</A>.<BR>
