<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: M&uuml;ndl et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>The Human Development Index HDI (1)</H3>
by Joachim H. Spangenberg<BR>
Wuppertal Insitute for Environment, Climate, Energy<BR>
D&ouml;ppersberg 19, D-42103 Wuppertal<BR>
Tel: +49-202-2492-128, -179 (Secr.), -138 (Fax)<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:J.Spangenberg@mail.wupperinst.org">J.Spangenberg@mail.wupperinst.org</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Draft of a paper to be presented at the International Conference on &quot;Challanges
of Sustainable Development&quot; Amsterdam, August 23rd <BR>
<BR>
Unemployment and social security, health and life expectancy, access to
housing, clean water, food, education investments, gender equity, income
distribution,...all these are indicatore of social development. The UN Development
Program UNDP, however, has undertaken to develop one indicator of human
development, the HDI, which can at first glance indicate progess or decline
in human (social) development.<BR>
<BR>
It includes two main features fom the broad spectrum of social indicators:
education (measured by the literacy rate) and health (measured by the life
expectation), linking them with a more economic indicator: average per capita
income. The simplicity of the HDI and its extensions (gender and income
distribution adjusted HDI) can be used to compare progress countrywise and
develop rankings. One result which got a significant press coverage earlier
this year was the weakening and complex relationship between GDP growth
and human development, as evaluated in detail in the HDR 1996 (2). The HDI
itself was designed to be a modification of the GNP, highlighting the human
resources needed for development (3 ). Its main target group are developing
countries, although the HDI ranking has been informativen and thus quite
disturbing for many OECD.<BR>
<BR>
The first published Human Development Report (HDR) published in 1990 (4)
defined human development as 'a process of enlarging people's choices or
enabling people to have wider choices' - a framework explicitly realizing
that human development cannot be promoted by a single-minded pursuit of
economic growth alone. In 1994 the HDR team defined 'Sustainable Human Development',
as: '...development that not only generates economic growth but distributes
its benefits equitably; that regenerates the environment rather than destroying
it; that empowers people rather than marginalizing them. ... It is development
that is pro-people, pro-nature, pro-jobs and pro-women.'<BR>
<BR>
This development, as measured by the HDI, is integrating three key components
into a one single composite human development index. For each of the components
a relative minimum is set (the minimum of the past 30 years) as well as
a maximum (a maximum expected for the next 30 years), so that the current
situation in each country can be expressed by a figure between zero and
one. The average of three factors gives the final HDI: 
<UL>
  <LI>Longevity (as measured by life expectancy at birth, minimum 25 years,
maximum 85 years), 
  <LI>Knowledge (as measured by two educational stock variables: adult literacy
beween 0% and 100% and mean years of schooling, with a minimum of zero nad
a maximum of 15 years. The measure of educational achievement is adjusted
by assessing a weight of two-thirds to literacy and one-third to mean years
of schooling). 
  <LI>Standard of living (as measured by purchasing power, based on real
GDP per capita adjusted for the local cost of living and resulting in purchasing
power parity Dollars (PPP$) with the minimum set at 200 PPP$ and the maximum
at 40,000 PPP$. Then the calculation is based on the innovative idea to
produce a yardstick more comprehensive than GNP alone for measuring country
progress, based on the premise of diminishing returns from income for human
development. The higher the income relative to the global average income
of 5,120 PPP$, the more sharply the diminishing returns are calculated by
an increasing devaluation rate at which the income is taken into account
for calculating the Standard of living). 
</UL>
The bottleneck for the construction of one single HDI was to find a common
measure for the socio-economic &quot;distance to target&quot; in these very
different areas of development politics. With the minima and a maxima set
for each dimension the HDI shows where each country stands and, based on
fixed sets of standards also permits measuring progress made so far.(5)<BR>
<BR>
Since national averages tend to hide internal disparities, the HDR team
has since 1991 produced adjusted HDIs, the most important being the ones
reflecting gender imbalances and income disparities.(6) Although all counties
face devaluation of the HDI when gender disparities are taken into account,
the different degree of discrimination in different counties changes the
ranking significantly: Japan goes down 16 positions, Switzerland 15, Canada
8. Other countries go up the ranks: Sweden by threee, Denmark by 11 and
Finland by 13 places.<BR>
<BR>
Similar developments can be seen in the income-disparities adjusted HDI:
all counties are devaluated, but the ranking changes: Belgium goes up by
ten, Germany by seven places; Canada and Switzerland fall back by seven
places.<BR>
<BR>
Table: HDI ranking of European countries 1992
<PRE>Country		HDI Rank	HDI Rank 	Gender adjusted	Income disparities
				minus GNP/cap	HDI rank	adjusted 
				rank( )				HDI rank
	
Switzerland	2		-1		17		9
Sweden		4		0		1		2
Norway		5		0		2		6
France		6		7		5		7
Netherlands	9		7		10		5
United Kingdom	10		9		11		8
Germany		11		1		13		4
Austria		12		2		14		-
Belgium		13		2		16		3
Iceland		14		-6		6		-
Denmark		15		-8		4		15
Finland		16		-10		3		12
Luxembourg	17		-15		20		-
Ireland		21		6		24		-
Italy		22		-5		18		19
Spain		23		0		23		22
Greece		25		10		26		-
Czechoslovakia	27		29		17		-
Lithuania	28		35		-		-
Estonia		29		14		-		-
Latvia		30		17		-		-
Hungary		31		24		-		31
Russia		34		14		-		-
Belarus		40		9		-		-
Malta		41		-9		-		-
Portugal	42		-4		37		-
Ukraine		45		23		-		-
Bulgaria	48		28		-		-
Poland		49		30		-		44
Armenia		53		20		-		-
Georgia		66		14		-		-
Azerbaijan	71		21		-		-
Romania		72		17		-		-
Moldova		75		6		-		-
Albania		76		10		-		-</PRE>
<BR>
Source: Human Development Report 1994<BR>
<BR>
Additionally, each year in the reports there is another focus - e.g. in
1991 a Human Freedom Index = HFI, in 1992 a Political Freedom Index = PFI,
in 1994 selected indicators of human security, and in 1996 the focus is
on economic growth and human development. Besides the HDI and these additional
indicators the Human Development Reports contain a very broad spectrum of
statistical data and evaluations (8),which gives them a unique value as
a basis for further discussion.<BR>
<BR>
Since the first publication of the HDI, there is a lively discussion (the
criticism being both scientific and political) of the whole approach.(9)
- in particular OECD countries feel that its sensitivity for the different
situations of industrialised countries is unsatisfactory. However, despite
all possible weaknesses the HDI is a very stimulating and provocative proposal
to the international debate and offers a lot of food for thought as well
a a cornucopia of concrete data about real wealth and sustainable human
development beyond GNP on a world wide scale.<BR>
<BR>
Notes:<BR>
<BR>
1. Parts of this presentation are based on a contribution of E.K.Seifert
for the study J.H.Spangenberg (Ed.), Towards Sustainable Europe, Luton et
al. 1995<BR>
2. UNDP (ed.), Human Development Report 1996, New York 1996<BR>
3. Their importance is increasingly acknowleged by institutions like the
World Bank<BR>
4. The first HDI 1990 was published under the guidance of Mahbub ul Haq,
former minister of Planning and Finance in Pakistan. The fifth report was
published in June 1994.<BR>
5. For further technical details and a discussion of the pros and cons of
such a procedure, see HDR 1994, p. 91 ff., especially 108 ff. <BR>
6. Regional disparities have been analyzed for a lot of Third World counties
and for Canada, Germany and Poland. For the US significant differences have
been found according to gender and ethnic group, for Turkey according to
gender and Region.<BR>
7. A positive figure indicates that the HDI rank is above the rank according
to GNP/cap, a negative figure indicates the opposite.<BR>
8. To give a proper impression on the valuable contents of these reports
for many other purposes, the 1996 report for examples contains some 90 pages
of &quot;Human Development Indicators&quot; (including a key to indicators)
with 48 tables full of details for all, industrial and or developing countries
of the whole world - this periodical &quot;annex&quot; is a unique source
of statistical information about the world development and it is quite impossible
to show the whole richness here.<BR>
9. See for example A.C. Kelley: The Human development Index: Handle with
Care, in: Population and Development Review 17(2), p. 315-24. Even though
the focus of the HDI is oriented towards &quot;Third World&quot; development
issues, the HDI was critical evaluated for example from South-America concerning
its possible (not actual) allocative implications in international development
policies and financing.<BR>
