<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Hovanov abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>General indices technique for sustainability</H3>
N. Hovanov, Y. Fedotov and V. Zakharov<BR>
Hovanov, N.Fedotov, Y.Zakharov V.<BR>
Faculty of Applied Mathematics and Processes of Control<BR>
St. Petersburg University<BR>
Bibliotechnaya, 2, St. Petergof,<BR>
St. Petersburg, 198904, Rossia<BR>
FAX: +7 812 218 1346, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:vvzakh@robot.apmath.spb.su">vvzakh@robot.apmath.spb.su</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The present problem of complex systems multi-attribute estimation may be<BR>
radically simplified by using a general indices technique. We show in<BR>
this paper that this technique provides sustainable development<BR>
analysis, decision making in environmental policy coordination, complex<BR>
projects quality evaluation, etc., with the possibility of working<BR>
accurately with any nonnumerical, imperfect or incomplete data.<BR>
<BR>
The technique discussed is based on a methodology of Analysis and<BR>
Synthesis of Parameters under Deficiency (ASPID) developed in<BR>
St.&uuml;Petersburg University. The main idea of ASPID-methodology consists<BR>
in stochastic modelling of the uncertainty which usually exists in<BR>
decision-making processes. An especially high level of uncertainty comes<BR>
to light in subjective evaluation of the meaning of different factors<BR>
for the general estimation of the complex object under investigation.<BR>
The role of this complex object may be played by a large technical<BR>
system, by a variant of multicriteria choice of a decision, by an expert<BR>
committee's collective decision, by a variant of resources distribution,<BR>
etc.<BR>
<BR>
The stochastic fields and processes used for uncertainty modelling are,
in<BR>
their turn, treated by methods of mathematical combinatorial analysis.<BR>
These methods allow the development of a flexible system of algorithms<BR>
which comprise the decision support system's shell TURBO-GINGER<BR>
(General Indices Generator).<BR>
<BR>
The TURBO-GINGER permits one to normalize the initial characters of<BR>
evaluating the complex object. This normalization gives the possibility
of<BR>
unification for diapasons of initial character variances and allows to<BR>
compare the weights of different characters in general estimation of the<BR>
complex object.<BR>
<BR>
The next step consists in numerical representation of a decision-maker's<BR>
ordinal information about comparative meaning (weight-coefficient) of a<BR>
complex object's separate parameter. This &quot;numerical representation&quot;<BR>
permits the visualization of uncertain decision maker's comparative<BR>
judgements for their clear manifestation and precise correction.<BR>
<BR>
Having the information about normalized initial characters and weight<BR>
coefficients restrictions, the ASPID-3 <BR>
program forms general estimations<BR>
of investigated complex objects and evaluates the reliability of these<BR>
estimations.<BR>
<BR>
The flexible and high-developed TURBO-GINGER may be used for<BR>
decision-making under uncertainty in many fields of applied operational<BR>
research such as investment planning, consumer choice forecasting,<BR>
diagnostic processing in medicine, pattern recognition, quality and<BR>
efficiency evaluation, expert decision-making under informational<BR>
deficiency, etc. The best results of TURBO-GINGER use are attained<BR>
in connection with a knowledge data base. So our system is developed in<BR>
relation to any specific field of use for every customer who can work<BR>
with his own data base.<BR>
In any list of the GINGER <BR>
applications the following items must be named:<BR>
<BR>
&#183;Large-scale technical systems efficiency measuring.<BR>
&#183;Multicriteria evaluation of development alternatives.<BR>
&#183;Multigoal optimization under uncertainty.<BR>
&#183;Synthesizing an expert-committee's opinions.<BR>
&#183;Choice of multi-factor alternatives for a project.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws22criind.html#anchor3741133">workshop 2,2
page</A>.<BR>
