<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Hunhammar abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3><BR>
To operationalise sustainable development with top-down and bottom-up approaches</H3>
Sven Hunhammar<BR>
Natural Resources Management<BR>
Department of Systems Ecology,<BR>
Stockholm University<BR>
P.B.&uuml;Box 2142, 103 14 Stockholm, Sverige<BR>
TEL: +46 8 402 3808, FAX: +46 8 402 3802, <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:svenh@system.ecology.su.se">svenh@system.ecology.su.se</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Sustainable development is an equitable development that can proceed in<BR>
the very long term. With the commonly used broad definitions, almost<BR>
every problem area is included in sustainable development. However,<BR>
several actors with contradictory objectives use the concept and give it<BR>
different meaning. One way to deal with these problems is to clarify the<BR>
components of the concept, rather than stress the aggregated definition.<BR>
In this way the concept will become operationalised and concrete.<BR>
<BR>
The purpose of operationalising the concept is to be able to judge<BR>
alternative developments or make priorities between problem areas.<BR>
<BR>
This paper suggests that the iteration between top-down and bottom-up<BR>
approaches is one way to operationalize sustainable development. By<BR>
top-down, in this context, is meant to make definitions and principles<BR>
more and more detailed to reach the level of criteria and indicators.<BR>
This is a goal oriented approach. Bottom-up, on the other hand, is to<BR>
start dealing with unacceptable situations and aggregate them into<BR>
larger complex. This is a problem oriented approach.&Auml;5pt<BR>
Three main components are commonly stressed to explain sustainable<BR>
development:<BR>
<BR>
&#183; Ecological aspects. The carrying capacity of ecosystems and<BR>
limited resource availability are serious constraints for an expanding<BR>
human activity.<BR>
&#183; Inter-generational equity. Preserve ability and resources for<BR>
future generations is a central equity issue.<BR>
&#183; Intra-generational equity. A fair distribution of resources<BR>
within our current generation is an indispensable requirement of<BR>
sustainable development.<BR>
&#183; Quality-of-life. Sometimes a fourth component is mentioned: an<BR>
improvement or maintenance in the quality of human life, rather than<BR>
just sustaining the existence of life.<BR>
<BR>
At this aggregated level, the components are straightforward. However,<BR>
the concept has to be defined in more detail to serve as an analytical<BR>
tool, to support the formulation of criteria and indicators and to find<BR>
solutions.<BR>
<BR>
A number of other issues has to be analysed, for example:<BR>
<BR>
&#183; Time frame. For how long is sustainable development supposed to<BR>
last, for ever?<BR>
&#183; Geographic area. Sustainable development is a global concept.<BR>
How is it divided into local areas. Can a local area at all be regarded<BR>
as sustainable?<BR>
&#183; Distribution of carrying capacity. The world's ecosystems can<BR>
sustain a certain amount of human activity. How is that activity<BR>
allocated and distributed; within our generation; between different<BR>
sectors; future generations; should historical environmental loads be<BR>
accounted for?<BR>
&#183; Goal or direction. Is sustainable development a state that can<BR>
be achieved, a minimum level or a direction? Does the speed of change<BR>
matter?<BR>
<BR>
Some concrete examples from the transportation sector are taken to<BR>
illustrate the issues and two approaches. One necessary, but not<BR>
sufficient, component of sustainable development is a sustainable<BR>
transportation system.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws22criind.html#anchor3755072">workshop 2,2
page</A>.<BR>
