<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Quick abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3><BR>
Towards a sustainable energy future</H3>
<BR>
Martin Quick<BR>
Energy Consultant<BR>
The Old Rectory, Walkley Hill, Stroud, <BR>
Gloucestershire GL5 3TY, UK<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The present way we produce and use energy is unsustainable, both due to<BR>
limitations of fuel resources and due to limits on the capacity of the<BR>
environment to absorb the emissions from our main energy sources.<BR>
<BR>
Readily available low cost supplies of gas, and particularly oil, are<BR>
likely to be severely depleted within the next few decades. Although<BR>
coal stocks are much greater, any major increase in the exploitation of<BR>
coal would worsen the already potentially disastrous consequences of<BR>
greenhouse gas warming, to which CO2, resulting from the use of fossil<BR>
fuels, is the main contributor.<BR>
<BR>
This paper argues that if international agreement is to be reached on<BR>
limiting climate change effects, the industrialised countries will have<BR>
to commit themselves to much more stringent reductions on greenhouse gas<BR>
emissions than are currently foreseen. Only by such a commitment by the<BR>
industrialised countries can countries whose economies are now<BR>
developing be expected to ensure that their development is in a way<BR>
which does minimum damage to the global environment.<BR>
<BR>
The technology exists to provide a given level of service with<BR>
greatly reduced energy input, and relatively minor changes in the<BR>
way of life in the industrialised countries can give further<BR>
reductions. Given such reductions in energy demand, a significant<BR>
fraction of these needs can be met by renewable sources, thus giving<BR>
a larger reduction in CO2 emissions. Such an approach is beneficial<BR>
in creating employment. Greater local autonomy in energy can reduce<BR>
the susceptibility of societies to instabilities from whatever cause.<BR>
It would also reduce the risk of conflicts over diminishing resources.<BR>
<BR>
Development of energy efficient technologies and renewables<BR>
should be done in a partnership between industrialised countries<BR>
and counties which are now developing. Also, collaboration with<BR>
the present oil producing states, many of which have good potential<BR>
for exploiting solar energy, could be a means of ensuring that they see<BR>
a satisfactory long term future when the rate of oil exploitation slows<BR>
down.<BR>
<BR>
The paper discusses the institutional and economic changes<BR>
desirable to bring about the necessary changes, and some of the<BR>
problems that will need to be resolved, particularly when issues of<BR>
energy production conflict with other needs.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws24manmat.html#anchor3909193">workshop 2,4
page</A>.<BR>
