<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Masera abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3><BR>
Energy for sustainable development in the third world</H3>
Omar Masera<BR>
Center of Ecology, M&eacute;xico <BR>
Apartado Postal 158, Patzcuaro, 61609 Michoacan, M&eacute;xico<BR>
TEL/FAX: +52 434 23216, <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:omasera@miranda.ecologia.unam.mx">omasera@miranda.ecologia.unam.mx</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Energy is an essential component of human and economic<BR>
development. The services energy makes possible such as cooking,<BR>
heating, lighting, etc. are associated with large improvements<BR>
in the living and health conditions of people. A sustainable<BR>
energy system may be defined as having five basic attributes: <BR>
<BR>
&#183; productivity (efficiency), <BR>
&#183;stability, resilience and reliability, <BR>
&#183;adaptability, <BR>
&#183;equity, and <BR>
&#183;self-reliance. <BR>
<BR>
Examination of the current pattern of energy use in the Third<BR>
World shows that we are far away from fulfilling these<BR>
attributes. So far, energy use is mostly wasteful and<BR>
inequitable. While most people, particularly within the rural<BR>
sector, still do not fulfill their basic energy needs, there are<BR>
elites that consume equal or more energy per capita than people<BR>
in the industrialized countries. We increasingly depend on non<BR>
renewable energy sources (specifically fossil fuels). Energy<BR>
supply is many times unreliable and associated with severe<BR>
environmental problems. Finally but not last, the dominant<BR>
paradigm in energy planning has promoted the development of<BR>
centralized, large scale energy facilities, favoring the growth<BR>
of megacities over the rural sector.<BR>
<BR>
If energy is to truly contribute to sustainable development, deep<BR>
changes are needed. These changes include, among other things:<BR>
<BR>
(a) a reorientation of the pattern of technology research and<BR>
development, favoring renewable and decentralized energy sources<BR>
over fossil fuels; <BR>
(b) a shift in the dominant paradigm of<BR>
energy planning, which stresses the increase of energy supply,<BR>
to focusing on energy end uses and services; <BR>
(c) new institutions that effectively promote renewables, assuring their<BR>
adequate funding and a fair competition with fossil fuel and<BR>
nuclear energy; <BR>
(d) promoting the diverse renewable energy<BR>
sources, developed at the different scales and adapted to the<BR>
local ecological and cultural conditions. High priority deserves<BR>
the promotion of alternatives that maximize income and<BR>
employment generation in the rural and informal sectors. <BR>
<BR>
Moving towards a more sustainable pattern of energy use is not a<BR>
task of the Third World alone but an urgent priority for<BR>
industrialized countries as well. Sustainability will only be<BR>
achieved by building a true and long-lasting partnership between<BR>
both regions.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
