</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Moll abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3><BR>
Towards sustainable use of resources: different analytical approaches responding
to different system levels</H3>
Henri C. Moll<BR>
Centre for Energy and Environmental Studies IVEM<BR>
State University of Groningen<BR>
Nijenborgh 4, 9747 AG Groningen, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 50 363 4607, FAX: +31 50 363 7168,<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:H.C.Moll@fwn.rug.nl%20">H.C.Moll@fwn.rug.nl </A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The pursuit of sustainability of the global community ultimately <BR>
affects all production and consumption patterns and all technological <BR>
and social systems resulting in these patterns.<BR>
Such a far-reaching enterprise is too complex to start with, without <BR>
judgements about the sustainable character of practical measures to <BR>
change the present metabolic processes of households, industrial <BR>
sectors, specific countries and the global community. Even if such <BR>
sustainability judgements are possible, new problems arise. The mutual <BR>
interaction between specific measures may eclipse the individual <BR>
contribution of a measure with regard to sustainability. Also the <BR>
division of the global society in different levels may create problems <BR>
such as: how to define sustainability on a specific level and how to <BR>
guar- antee that the sum of all subsystems being sustainable will <BR>
result in a sustainable global system. <BR>
<BR>
An analytical approach may mitigate these dilemmas. First a <BR>
distinction is made between different levels: the macro-level <BR>
addressing global processes with long time constants, the micro-level <BR>
with a local or sectoral scope and a short time-horizon, and in <BR>
between the meso-level describing processes on a national or regional <BR>
scale and with a time-horizon of about one generation. The mitigation <BR>
of resource depletion by substitution to renewable resources and the <BR>
prevention of climate change are examples of sustainability issues at <BR>
the macro-level. The improvement of reuse and recycling of material<BR>
flows and surface water at the meso-level by the design of quality <BR>
cascades may contribute to a development towards sustainability. The <BR>
design of green processes, green products and green services are <BR>
approaches based at the micro-level. <BR>
<BR>
The adjective 'sustainable' (and its derivatives) to its fullest <BR>
extent is only attributable to the global system. Judgements about <BR>
'sustainable development' can be derived from System Dynamical <BR>
studies. Subsystems may be considered to be sustainable if these <BR>
systems proceed in accordance with more general sustainability and if <BR>
these subsystems do not limit the potential of other subsystems to <BR>
develop also towards sustainability. The methodology of Substance Flow <BR>
Analysis (SFA) can be applied to evaluate different approaches to<BR>
improve the performance of the 'material delivery system', followed by <BR>
a an assessment of its consequences for the global issues e.g. <BR>
resource depletion and emission of greenhouse gases. The methodology <BR>
of Life Cycle Analysis (LCA) can be applied to compare environmentally <BR>
different products and services in order to 'green' production and <BR>
consumption. Afterwards, the conclusions of a LCA should be evaluated <BR>
in a global context by an analysis of the consequences of a global <BR>
implementation of the 'greenest' alternative. <BR>
<BR>
Examples of these methodologies are presented in the context of a <BR>
comparative evaluation of advances towards sustainability: System <BR>
Dynamic study at the macro-level, SFA at the meso-level and LCA at <BR>
the micro-level. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
