<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Lal abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<STRONG>SOIL PHYSICAL MANAGEMENT FOR SUSTAINING<BR>
AGRICULTURAL PRODUCTION IN THE TROPICS</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
Rattan Lal<BR>
School of Natural Resources, The Ohio State University<BR>
Columbus, Ohio 43210, USA<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
ABSTRACT<BR>
<BR>
Tropical regions cover about 4.9 billion ha of the land surface, of<BR>
which 6 soil orders occupy 86.5 per cent of the total land area. These<BR>
soil orders are: Alfisols (16.2%), Aridisols (18.4%), Entisols (10.2%),<BR>
Inceptisols (8.1%), Oxisols (22.5%), and Ultisols (11.1%). Principal<BR>
soil physical constraints for sustaining agricultural production in the<BR>
tropics are accelerated soil erosion; soil structural decline leading to<BR>
crusting, compaction and hardsetting; drought; shallow effective rooting<BR>
depth; trafficability; high soil temperature, and soil salinity.<BR>
<BR>
In addition to adverse effects on agricultural productivity and<BR>
sustainability, these soil physical constraints also affect<BR>
environmental quality with detrimental impact on water quality and<BR>
greenhouse gas emissions. There are a wide range of proven technologies<BR>
and examples of their successful applications in alleviating<BR>
soil-related constraints, enhancing agricultural production, improving<BR>
water quality, and mitigating the greenhouse effect. These technologies<BR>
exist for all principal soil orders in major tropical agroecoregions,<BR>
although site-specific adaptation and fine-tuning is needed.<BR>
<BR>
Relevant technologies for soil physical management include conservation<BR>
tillage, mulch farming, cover crops, multiple cropping, agroforestry,<BR>
nutrient cycling, management of soil biota, and judicious use of<BR>
chemical fertilizers and amendments. Successful application of these<BR>
technologies, through farmer-participation and community involvement,<BR>
can enhance and sustain production and improve environment. There is an<BR>
urgent need to encourage widespread adoption of these technologies<BR>
through identification of policy issues and strengthening of<BR>
institutional support.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws26susagr.html#anchor1463063">workshop 2,6
page</A>.<BR>
