<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Rosemeyer abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Challenges to Sustainable Agriculture in Central America</H3>
Martha E. Rosemeyer, Cornell University and University of Costa Rica<BR>
<BR>
Currently agriculture in developing countries faces the dual<BR>
challenge of sustainability and further production increases on a<BR>
degrading land base. In Central America, high rates of<BR>
population growth and expansion of crops for export on flat lands<BR>
have forced small farmers into largely unsustainable hillside<BR>
production of crops for national consumption. An average of 65%<BR>
of the area devoted to corn and beans is on hillsides in Central<BR>
America. There is little flat land (e.g., in Costa Rica only<BR>
24%) and these areas are generally controlled by larger farmers<BR>
and multinational companies in the production of bananas, coffee,<BR>
cattle and pineapple for export. In order to service the<BR>
national debt, exportation has been encouraged by government<BR>
incentives as part of the policy of structural adjustment<BR>
required to obtain loans from the International Monetary Fund.<BR>
<BR>
None-the-less, 30% of Costa Rica's beans are sustainably<BR>
produced on slopes and it is possible to increase yields.<BR>
Mulches of secondary growth vegetation have traditionally been<BR>
used in bean and corn slash mulch systems, preventing sheet<BR>
erosion and avoiding soil fertility and toxicity problems.<BR>
Research over the last 10 years to increase yields while<BR>
maintaining the sustainable aspects of the system, has found that<BR>
phosphorus (P) fertilizers can be added to the mulch, resulting<BR>
in greater efficiency of P use than in soil-based systems.<BR>
Yields of beans have increased on hillsides where mixed species<BR>
of nitrogen-fixing trees in rows (alley cropping) have been<BR>
introduced into the slash mulch system as a more affordable input<BR>
for farmers. Trees in cropping systems also prevent land<BR>
slippage. Both sustainability and increased production are<BR>
possible in these systems, but whether mulches can be applied on<BR>
a large scale, to other crops and in different climatic zones<BR>
needs further evaluation.<BR>
<BR>
Closure of nutrient cycles remains a challenge in both<BR>
developed and developing countries. Sewage from most Central<BR>
American cities, including San Jose, Costa Rica, is not treated<BR>
before dumping into a nearby body of water. Organic debris are<BR>
not separated from city garbage. Both sewage and organic garbage<BR>
must be composted and applied to crop lands to close nutrient<BR>
cycles. Although technologies are known, government funds to<BR>
encourage long range projects such as this are even more scare<BR>
under structural adjustment and the business community has not<BR>
yet embraced this opportunity.<BR>
<BR>
Even the &quot;greenest&quot; country in Central America, Costa<BR>
Rica, is facing both technological challenges in sustainable<BR>
agriculture (due to lack of research/extension funding), and<BR>
financial challenges under structural adjustment. The<BR>
rise of sustainable development as a goal gives developing<BR>
countries an opportunity to rethink what development means for<BR>
their country and culture. However, in many countries this<BR>
important process is being truncated by the immediate demands of<BR>
structural adjustment and short term free market goals which do<BR>
not recognize long term environmental impacts. If structural<BR>
adjustment could include environmental parameters, rewarding the<BR>
expansion of sustainable agricultural systems for local<BR>
consumption and export crops, as well as encouraging closure of<BR>
nutrient cycles, we could further meet the challenge of<BR>
sustainable development.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
