<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Ohlander et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Strategies and visions for ecologically adapted agricultural systems</H3>
Lars Ohlander<BR>
Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences (SLU)<BR>
Department of Crop Production Science<BR>
P.O. Box 7043, 750 07 Uppsala, Sverige<BR>
FAX: +46 18 67 2909, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:Lars.Ohlander@vo.slu.se">Lars.Ohlander@vo.slu.se</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Charlotte Lagerberg and Ulla Gertsson<BR>
Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences (SLU)<BR>
Department of Horticulture<BR>
P.O. Box 55, 230 53 Alnarp, Sverige<BR>
FAX: +46 40 46 0441, <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:Lotta.Lagerberg@tv.slu.se">Lotta.Lagerberg@tv.slu.se</A>,
<A HREF="mailto:Ulla.Gertsson@tv.slu.se">Ulla.Gertsson@tv.slu.se</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Through a creative combination of scientific knowledge, technology,<BR>
experience and common sense, it is possible to design agricultural<BR>
systems that both support and apply the maintaining work of the global<BR>
ecosystem. This hypothesis may serve as an overall guide for the work of<BR>
creating sustainable agricultural systems.<BR>
<BR>
Natural ecosystems are often sustainable while our present agricultural<BR>
systems are not. Each interference with the natural succession, such as<BR>
harrowing and ploughing, implies a degradation of resources. If the<BR>
agro-ecosystems were designed to mimic the natural ecosystems and less<BR>
effort put into physical interference, it might be possible to create an<BR>
agricultural system that uses less inputs, produces enough food and<BR>
other desired products, and still proves sustainable in a longer time<BR>
perspective (Soule &amp; Piper 1992). However, in contrast to natural<BR>
systems, agro-ecosystems have to support people living outside the<BR>
system. Consequently it is important to consider the agro-ecosystem not<BR>
only on field level, but also at higher hierarchy levels like farms,<BR>
villages and regions (Conway 1986). This calls for a holistic system<BR>
view, as emergent properties of the system do not manifest themselves in<BR>
the isolated parts. The system tends to respond to stimuli as a whole,<BR>
even if the stimulus is only applied to one part of the system.<BR>
<BR>
Agriculture of today may be defined as goal oriented manipulation of<BR>
ecosystems for human gains. Man has thus taken over the responsibility<BR>
for regulating the system according to his needs. Future agricultural<BR>
systems should be aimed at goal-oriented management of sustainable<BR>
ecosystems for human and ecosystem gains. Consequently, man takes over<BR>
the responsibility of not only regulating the system according to his<BR>
needs, but also of supporting the system that serves him and of which he<BR>
is a part. This agricultural man-regulated system is included in the<BR>
larger natural ecosystems which are self-regulating through subsystem<BR>
feedback and larger scale control mechanisms. The agricultural systems<BR>
are open subsystems in the overall global ecosystem. They are connected<BR>
with their surroundings by the throughput of energy, material, services<BR>
and information. Environmental work is the energetic base for the sum of<BR>
activities at all levels.<BR>
<BR>
During the process of self-organization, species and relations are<BR>
selectively reinforced as more energy becomes available to those designs<BR>
that feeds products back into increased production. Characteristic<BR>
ecosystem designs result from self-maximizing energy flow through the<BR>
system (J&ouml;rgensen 1992).<BR>
<BR>
For sustainability and productivity the future society must, to a much<BR>
larger extent than today, be based on recycling. The products of a system<BR>
must be useful for that system, either directly within the system, or by<BR>
feedback through other surrounding systems, otherwise the system will be<BR>
degraded. It is necessary to find methods for evaluation of the external<BR>
energy basis of economies, of both nature and man, so that changes in<BR>
environment and resources can be related quantitatively and their impact
on<BR>
future economies estimated.<BR>
<BR>
References:<BR>
1 . Conway, G.R., 1985. Agroecosystem analysis.<BR>
Agricultural Administration Vol. 20: 31-55.<BR>
2 . J&ouml;orgensen, S.E., 1992. Exergy and ecology.<BR>
Ecological Modelling, 63: 185-214. <BR>
3 . Soule, J.D. &amp; Piper, J.K. 1992. Farming in nature's image:<BR>
an ecological approach to agriculture. pp. 286. USA<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws26susagr.html#anchor1463063">workshop 2,6
page</A>.<BR>
