<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Lechuga et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Population development - environmental relations</H3>
Miguel Lechuga<BR>
National Council of Population<BR>
Angel Urraza 1137, Col. del Valle, M&eacute;xico, D.F. CP 03 100, M&eacute;xico<BR>
FAX: +52 5 575 1907, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:mlechuga@servidor.unam.mx">mlechuga@servidor.unam.mx</A><BR>
<BR>
Olga Lopez<BR>
Instituto Nacional de Salud Publica<BR>
Av. Universidad 655, Col. Sta. Ma. Ahuact., Cuernavaca Morelos CP 62508,<BR>
M&eacute;xico<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:Irios@buzon.main.conacyt.mx">Irios@buzon.main.conacyt.mx</A>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The vague notion that we have about sustainable development, and the<BR>
lack of a complete methodology concerning the dynamics of the relations<BR>
between the three phenomena, population, development and environment<BR>
(thereafter abbreviated PDE), force us to undertake new<BR>
approaches to elucidate characteristics of those relations that apply in<BR>
a general context and those that apply only under specific conditions.<BR>
<BR>
In a heterogeneous country like Mexico with an area of two million km2<BR>
and an enormous variety of economic, ecological and cultural regions, it<BR>
is very difficult to talk about the level of development of the country,<BR>
if we do not reduce this measure to the classical indicators like<BR>
GNP.<BR>
<BR>
Presently it is more and more evident that the &quot;academic&quot; notion
of<BR>
development does not correspond necessarily to the notion that rural<BR>
communities may have about it.<BR>
<BR>
In this essay we analyze the relations between several factors of<BR>
population, development and environment, using classical statistical<BR>
methods, and a new approach to construct an example of PDE<BR>
relations using dynamics models by means of the ITHINK<BR>
software.<BR>
<BR>
We establish several divisions of the country; mapping the distribution<BR>
of life expectancy, mortality by cause of death, and social indicators<BR>
such as the education of women, housing conditions,etc. Our objective is
to<BR>
compare these maps with the economic development regions in which<BR>
Mexico can be divided, and with a map of the levels of marginality.<BR>
<BR>
It appears that the high level of marginality found everywhere in<BR>
the country constitutes a challenge to development. Particularly<BR>
the concentration of high levels of marginality in the rural communities<BR>
produce a closed loop between marginality and demographic slowness,<BR>
which results in high fertility and mortality rates, implying an<BR>
aggravation of poverty and health conditions, which at the same time<BR>
conduces to more marginality.<BR>
<BR>
The development model followed in the past, has shown its inefficiency<BR>
and therefore it is necessary to adopt new strategies toward a better<BR>
distribution of resources and social services. The problem is the<BR>
nonexistence of a methodology for this purpose. One piece of the<BR>
analysis shows that it is undoubtedly necessary to adopt mechanisms<BR>
permitting the communities to express their conception of development,<BR>
their needs and priorities, and valuing their perception of nature and<BR>
their culture.<BR>
<BR>
In the National Council of Population, which is the organism charged<BR>
by the Mexican Government Agency of the Interior, to propose public<BR>
population policies to be taken by the government on this matter, we are<BR>
planning to carry out a study to set out the general and particular<BR>
relations between PDE dynamics. This essay is on the basis of<BR>
this project and attempts to identify critical PDE problems<BR>
toward the elaboration of a comprehensive methodology, which in a<BR>
specific setting, shows the particularities of the relationship between<BR>
the three phenomena. On this perspective we have elaborated an <BR>
ITHINK model of PDE interactions, to study the future impact,<BR>
by means of scenarios, of environmental policies on population dynamics<BR>
and on the economy development.<BR>
<BR>
Even if our model is very simple it shows the power of scenarios as an<BR>
instrument in making predictions. It suggests that we must go deeply<BR>
into PDE relations to produce realistic models.<BR>
<BR>
