<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Singh abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Human potential, livelihood security and anthropogenic stress: challenges
of sustainability in India</H3>
R.B.Singh<BR>
Department of Geography, Delhi School of Economics<BR>
University of Delhi<BR>
Delhi - 110007 India<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Since independence, all development plans in India have given top<BR>
priority to tackling population issues and livelihood security for<BR>
people, particularly the poor. Various development programmes have been<BR>
initiated. This resulted in intensive anthropogenic stress on vulnerable<BR>
geosystems. The Green Revolution in India has attained self sufficiency<BR>
in food production, but there is continuous degradation in soil and<BR>
water resources. About 53% of the geographical areas face soil and land<BR>
degradation problems arising from water and land erosion and various<BR>
processes of land degradation like water- logging, acidity, salinity,<BR>
alkalinity, ravines and shifting cultivation etc. In the green<BR>
revolution states, high intensity of cropping along with relatively high<BR>
consumption of chemical fertilizers have contributed to the deficiency<BR>
of secondary and micro-nutrients which have been limiting the crop<BR>
productivity. Zinc, sulphur and manganese or iron deficiencies are<BR>
generally observed.<BR>
<BR>
The efficiency of nutrient use is higher in Punjab state i.e.&uuml;13 kg<BR>
grain/kg nutrient. The annual soil loss is estimated to be about 16<BR>
metric tonnes per ha/year in Kandi sub-zone-I and sub-zone-III, up to 25<BR>
tonnes/ha/year in Kandi sub-zone-II. About 9&Ouml;% of the cultivated area<BR>
continue to suffer from the problems of salinity and/or sodicity largely<BR>
concentrated in the south-western districts of the Ferozepur, Faridkot<BR>
and Bathinda. The total land degradation problem of Punjab includes<BR>
gullies and ravines with about 0.12 million ha, water-logging in about<BR>
1.1 million ha and alkali soils in about 0.72 million ha. ('Diaraland'<BR>
has torrents(?) under the reverine(???) in about 0.3 million ha. Thus, the<BR>
total area affected by the various kinds of soil erosion and land<BR>
degradation works out to 3.23 million ha, constituting about 44&Ouml;% of
the<BR>
total geographical area of Punjab. The paper also discusses major<BR>
physical, hydrological, chemical and biological constraints relating<BR>
soil and water to ecosystem sustainability.<BR>
<BR>
In the National Land Use Policy outline, watershed management<BR>
programmes and soil conservation activities were taken up in 37<BR>
catchments involving an area of about 86 million ha. The present paper<BR>
highlights the progress of different types of surveys; sample soil<BR>
surveys as well as remote sensing activities. Following the<BR>
recommendations of Agenda 21, many sustainable development issues are<BR>
being incorporated in order to utilise the vast human potential<BR>
available in the country. This includes gender, indigenous knowledge,<BR>
empowerment of people, particularly the poor, and decentralised and<BR>
representative decision making. The objective of such a sustainable<BR>
development policy is to increase human welfare and we must ensure that<BR>
the instruments of such policy are used in ways which act to increase<BR>
human potential and human happiness.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws26susagr.html#anchor1463063">workshop 2,6
page</A>.<BR>
