<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Mathes abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Ecological animal breeding: An approach to holistic criteria</H3>
Maite Mathes<BR>
Working Group of Critical Veterinarians (AGKT), and<BR>
Working Group for Caring Economy (AG Vorsorgendes<BR>
Wirtschaften) <BR>
<BR>
Working fields: population genetics, ecology, feminism<BR>
<BR>
Schwesternhausstr. 10 / 64, 30173 Hannover, Deutschland<BR>
from June 1996 on: Liebigstr. 2, 30163 Hannover, Deutschland<BR>
FAX: via I&Ouml;W Hannover: +49 511 164 0344 <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:mmathes@zucht.tiho-hannover.de">mmathes@zucht.tiho-hannover.de</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Breeding is always a mighty and powerful intervention in the evolution<BR>
of species and its rhythms - so some people may conclude that it can<BR>
never be ecological. Indeed, ecological animal breeding is a complex<BR>
problem and so some structure might be helpful to define this term: the<BR>
four paradigms of environmental protection and the three<BR>
action-principles of &quot;Caring-Economy.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The four paradigms of environmental protection check for<BR>
environmental aspects. Examples for practical conclusions about<BR>
animal breeding are given:<BR>
<BR>
1. Reduce toxic releases - Animals should have a good constitution to<BR>
be resistant to diseases to reduce the need of medicine.<BR>
2. Maintain the natural equilibrium - Animals should be adapted to<BR>
their local environment, eat local fodder and the manure should fit into<BR>
the local environmental circles. <BR>
3. Watch entropy and conserve resources - The efficiency (e.g.&uuml;meat<BR>
production per unit energy needed to produce the fodder) of the animal<BR>
should be good and the needs for housing should be low.<BR>
4. Maintain conviviality - The animal should be healthy in the<BR>
definition of the WHO - that means its hereditary features should allow<BR>
for well-being.<BR>
<BR>
Furthermore we want animal breeding to be useful for a satisfying and<BR>
good life. To evaluate this point I suggest consulting the three<BR>
action-principles of &quot;Caring Economy,&quot; because this feministic
concept<BR>
of sustainable development includes productive work as well as the large<BR>
and mostly forgotten field of reproductive work - and animal breeding is<BR>
a big productive business and at the same time very important for<BR>
feeding/reproduction of human beings. These three action-principles are:<BR>
5. Precaution - it means carefulness, including structures that<BR>
tolerate mistakes and slowness for a remaining chance to correct errors.<BR>
It also means circumspection with respect to associated effects -<BR>
therefore only assessable actions are allowed. In animal breeding<BR>
performance should be reached without hormones and without<BR>
gene-technology for the outcome of both technics can not be completely<BR>
assessed.<BR>
6. Cooperation is necessary because all beings share ONE world. It<BR>
needs communication and agreements. The characteristics of the animals<BR>
should be communicatable to people and there should be a dialogue about<BR>
the selection of breeds with e.g. consumer organisations.<BR>
7. Orientation by essentials (of good! life) pays attention to<BR>
material needs and as well to needs for services and to emotional needs.<BR>
The output meat should have a really satisfying taste and the<BR>
consumption value should be high just because in sustainable agriculture<BR>
only a limited number of animals can be produced.<BR>
In Ecological Animal Breeding there are two fields of action:<BR>
The first field is &quot;Breeding for Sustainable Agriculture,&quot; equivalent
to<BR>
the &quot;product,&quot; that means the breeding goals. All of the above
<BR>
examples referred to this point.<BR>
The second field is the way of &quot;production&quot; itself, that should
be<BR>
&quot;Sustainable Breeding.&quot; If you apply the above mentioned criteria<BR>
consequently to the breeding process itself there is one main outcome:<BR>
<BR>
The hardest self-caused problem of intensive farm animal breeding is the<BR>
loss of biodiversity, its very own resource. On the species level there<BR>
is a demand for using more than one breed (for example<BR>
Holstein-Friesians as cows) in daily business and on the breed level of<BR>
giving more animals the chance to become ancestors for future<BR>
generations. Thus in the long term inbreeding and genetic drift will be<BR>
avoided - and options to fulfill different future demands will be kept<BR>
open.<BR>
<BR>
By using the seven-point-check in the two defined action fields<BR>
of animal breeding you will come to several more practical<BR>
conclusions than could be mentioned above - but anyway it may be<BR>
a useful system to put thoughts about this complex problem in<BR>
some order.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws26susagr.html#anchor1463063">workshop 2,6
page</A>.<BR>
