<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Niemczynowicz abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3><BR>
Importance of integration of urban water management with management of societies
</H3>
Janusz Niemczynowicz<BR>
Department of Water Resources Engineering <BR>
University of Lund, P.O. Box 118, 221 00 Lund, Sverige<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:Janusz.Niemczynowicz@tvrl.lth.se">Janusz.Niemczynowicz@tvrl.lth.se
</A><BR>
<BR>
Keywords: global pollution, large cities, urban-rural interaction, water
treatment. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Cities constitute the most important source of global environmental<BR>
pollution. Uncritical application of an old water treatment paradigm in<BR>
cities of developing countries brought disastrous results manifested in<BR>
land degradation, pollution and misery. Most of the problems in<BR>
megacities, i.e.&uuml;cities with more than 10 millions inhabitants, is
water<BR>
related. Water shortage is rapidly growing, and delivery of safe<BR>
drinking water cannot be ensured. In many places municipal and<BR>
industrial wastewater and wastes are disposed of in the natural<BR>
environment without adequate treatment. The present situation with<BR>
respect to pollution of air, land, and water, as well as lack of basic<BR>
water and sanitation facilities in these cities creates living<BR>
conditions that are nothing less than derision of human dignity. Women<BR>
and children suffer most.<BR>
<BR>
Western technologies of sewage treatment are too expensive in terms of<BR>
money, resources and energy to create a viable alternative for most of<BR>
developing countries. They deplete natural resources of the world and<BR>
cause loss of nutrients necessary for food production. They emerged from<BR>
a single-disciplinary approach and the old philosophy of dilution<BR>
resulting in open material flows and global pollution creating a vicious<BR>
circle of losing nutrients and carbon in agriculture, causing land<BR>
degradation, hunger and urban migration. In order to break this circle,<BR>
development of novel approach and new technology in urban water<BR>
management and change to sustainable agriculture is necessary. Problems<BR>
of megacities require efficient regulations and actions to stop further<BR>
population growth and, in water sector, development of alternative<BR>
environmentally friendly and economically efficient methods of water<BR>
conservation and treatment. This cannot be accomplished without local<BR>
initiatives and active participation of the local population.<BR>
Technological change must be accompanied by basic changes in all<BR>
sectors, social and central structures, educational and research<BR>
programs and in lifestyle.<BR>
<BR>
Failure or success of novel systems are dependent on the commitment of<BR>
all involved actors. The role of central and regional organizations<BR>
responsible for management of cities is to facilitate local groups.<BR>
Technical problems can be only solved on the condition that appropriate<BR>
supportive infrastructure is created. The fate of large cities depends<BR>
on whether new technologies such as dry sanitation or, in general, local<BR>
wastewater utilization, is provided with funding and supportive<BR>
institutional infrastructure equal to those that were given to<BR>
traditional sanitation systems. If the new systems are successful,<BR>
the world will have a chance. If they fail, present problems of not<BR>
only poverty and misery of urban population in developing countries, but<BR>
also continuing loss of basic resources for food production will destroy<BR>
the world.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws27manwat.html#anchor4489844">workshop 2.7
page</A>.<BR>
