<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Leuven abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3><BR>
Environmental utilisation space: a useful concept underpinning sustainable
management of river catchments?</H3>
R.S.E.W. Leuven, M.W.H. Thorig, P.H. Nienhuis and B.J. van de Laar <BR>
Department of Environmental Studies, University of Nijmegen<BR>
Toernooiveld 1, 6525 ED Nijmegen, Nederland<BR>
FAX: +31 24 365 3030, E-MAIL: rleuven@sci.kun.nl<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The rivers and flood plains in the Netherlands have been considerably<BR>
modified during the last centuries, due to the impact of flow<BR>
regulation, land reclamation and pollution. The unbalanced hydraulic<BR>
design, pollution and excessive use of river systems have led to a<BR>
situation without healthy, functioning ecosystems. At present Dutch<BR>
policy applies the concept of sustainable development. The prevention<BR>
of further ecological decline and the removal of the obstacles to<BR>
achieving sustained use of river catchments are prominent on today's<BR>
agenda.<BR>
<BR>
Sustained use of river catchments needs a process of change in which the<BR>
exploitation of resources, the direction of investments, the orientation<BR>
of technological developments and the institutional change are in<BR>
harmony and increase the present, as well as the future possibilities of<BR>
accommodating human needs. This process has socioeconomic and ecological<BR>
dimensions which, in practice, are closely related. The concept of<BR>
Environmental Utilisation Space (EUS) refers to the ecological<BR>
dimensions. Ecological sustainability means conservation of nature's<BR>
carrying capacity necessary for socioeconomic activities. The biosphere<BR>
has a limited capacity to meet the demands of human activities and of<BR>
functions of nature. The EUS is that part of nature that can be used in<BR>
an ecologically sustainable way. The ratio between the actual<BR>
environmental use of socio-economic activities and the EUS is a measure<BR>
for ecological sustainability. As long as the EUS is not exceeded, the<BR>
activities considered are ecologically sustainable.<BR>
<BR>
The present paper brings into practice the EUS concept for underpinning<BR>
sustainable management of the Rhine river-estuary continuum in the<BR>
Netherlands. The distance of socio-economic activities to ecological<BR>
sustainability is measured for two cases, i.e.&uuml;the recreational use
of a<BR>
former estuary (Lake Grevelingen) and the multifunctional use of a<BR>
lowland branch (the Waal). The EUS concept is made operational in seven<BR>
steps:<BR>
&#183;Definition of the socioeconomic activities (functions), the<BR>
environmental impacts considered, the geographical system boundaries and<BR>
the time horizon.<BR>
&#183;Classification of environmental use.<BR>
&#183;Narrowing down of spatial units.<BR>
&#183;Quantification of the environmental use.<BR>
&#183;Determination of the EUS.<BR>
&#183;Calculation of the ratios between the environmental use and the EUS<BR>
for each environmental use class for the spatial units and the entire<BR>
system.<BR>
&#183;Presentation of the ratios in radar graphs.<BR>
<BR>
Determination of the EUS can not be done by scientific research only,<BR>
due to scientific uncertainties and different views on nature.<BR>
Consequently, assumptions have to be made regarding the lack of<BR>
scientific knowledge and the future developments. The EUS is therefore a<BR>
best possible estimate of the real carrying capacity of the<BR>
environmental system. Conclusions are drawn concerning the possibilities<BR>
and restrictions of the EUS concept and the options for further<BR>
research.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
