<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Dabrowski abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Adjustment of Polish environmental laws to the free market economy :
Recent developments and prospects for the immediate future </H3>
Wojciech Dabrowski<BR>
Cracow University of Technology<BR>
ul. Warszawska 24, 31-155 Krak&ograve;w, Polska<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:wojtek@aqua.wis.pk.edu.pl">wojtek@aqua.wis.pk.edu.pl</A><BR>
<BR>
Arthur McGarity<BR>
Swarthmore College<BR>
PA 19081-1397, USA <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:amcgari1@cc.swarthmore.edu">amcgari1@cc.swarthmore.edu</A><BR>
<BR>
Wlodzimierz W&ograve;jcik<BR>
Department of Environmental Protection<BR>
and Management<BR>
Academy of Mining and Metallurgy <BR>
Al. A. Mickiewicza 30, 30-059 Krak&ograve;w, Polska<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:wwojcik@uci.agh.edu.pl">wwojcik@uci.agh.edu.pl </A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Poland is making an effort to adjust its environmental laws to a free<BR>
market economy and to the standards required by present members of the<BR>
European Community. Some steps have already been taken such as the<BR>
replacement of stream water quality standards by technology-based<BR>
standards on wastewater treatment. Additional changes are likely, such<BR>
as establishing recommended water quality standards (much stronger than<BR>
the enforced standards) to be met during certain periods of the year.<BR>
These changes of environmental laws in Poland are evaluated with regard<BR>
to the availability and economic feasibility of pollution control<BR>
technology. Also, the positive impacts of new laws on the amounts of<BR>
pollution in the air and water in Poland are discussed, both in general<BR>
and for some of the most polluted parts of the country.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
