<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: W&ograve;jcik abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Ownership and financing of water and wastewater systems in selected
countries</H3>
Wlodzimierz W&ograve;jcik<BR>
Department of Environmental Protection<BR>
and Management<BR>
Academy of Mining and Metallurgy<BR>
Al. A. Mickiewicza 30,<BR>
30-059 Krak&ograve;w, Polska<BR>
FAX: +48 12 33 0717, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:wwojcik@uci.agh.edu.pl">wwojcik@uci.agh.edu.pl</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Water management solutions have a very important impact on efficient or<BR>
non-efficient use of natural and human resources. The usual monopoly<BR>
control of these systems is one of the most important constraints which<BR>
inhibits implementation of competition and open-market rules which make<BR>
systems more efficient. Development of efficient self-supporting water<BR>
and waste water systems varies from country to country. The paper will<BR>
discuss the ownership and financing practices with examples from various<BR>
countries including England, France, Germany, Japan, Poland, Sweden and<BR>
USA. Advantages and disadvantages of various forms of ownership<BR>
will help the reader in reaching a better understanding of the<BR>
historical and current practice in these countries.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
