<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Davidson abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Sustainable transport options for African countries</H3>
Ogunlade R. Davidson<BR>
Department of Mechanical Engineering <BR>
University of Sierra Leone <BR>
Freetown, Sierra Leone <BR>
TEL: +232 22 226 325 / 226 786, FAX: +232 22 224 439 <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Developing adequate and suitable transport systems in African countries<BR>
to cope with future economic and social needs pose serious problems for<BR>
these countries. A large number of them are yet to go through their<BR>
threshold of development and coping with survival needs is paramount.<BR>
African countries as most worldwide have come to rely on petroleum based<BR>
road transport systems that are expensive, infrastructurally demanding<BR>
and environmentally unattractive. In the last two decades, petroleum<BR>
transport fuels have doubled and steadily accounts for 55-60% of the<BR>
total oil use. Over half of these countries have less than 500 km paved<BR>
roads per million people and over a third of these are in poor<BR>
condition. Emissions form existing road transport systems only increase<BR>
local, regional and global environmental concerns. Overcoming these<BR>
dilemmas and developing transport system that are efficient, reliable,<BR>
flexible and sustainable is a major task for authorities in the<BR>
continent.<BR>
<BR>
This paper, after a brief discussion on the dilemmas facing African<BR>
countries describes the situation of the transport sector in the<BR>
continent. This analysis provides the basis to comment on the future<BR>
trends in the transport sector of the region. The technical, economic<BR>
and market potentials of introducing alternative transport options are<BR>
then examined. Options considered include technology and energy<BR>
efficiency improvements. Regulatory measures and other policies to<BR>
support these options are explored, while commenting on possible<BR>
barriers to their introduction.<BR>
<BR>
This paper shows that African countries can provide suitable and<BR>
sustainable transport services for their inhabitants but there is need<BR>
to make major shifts in the present transport sector.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws31tramob.html#anchor206250">workshop 4.1
page</A>.<BR>
