<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Mulder et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Expert opinions on the future prospects for external sources of vehicle
propulsion, results of a Delphi study</H3>
Karel F. Mulder<BR>
Technische Universiteit Delft, Faculteit WTM<BR>
Technology Assessment<BR>
De Vries van Heystplantsoen 2, 2628 RZ Delft, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 15 278 1043/3791, FAX: +31 15 278 3177<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:karel.mulder@wtm.tudelft.nl">karel.mulder@wtm.tudelft.nl
</A><BR>
<BR>
Vincent Marchau<BR>
Faculteit Technische Bestuurskunde, Transport en Logistieke Organisatie<BR>
TEL: +31 15 278 2114, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:vincentm@sepa.tudelft.nl">vincentm@sepa.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
<BR>
Carlo J.T. van de Weijer<BR>
TNO Wegtransport<BR>
P.O. Box 6033, 2600 JA Delft, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 15 269 6375, FAX: +31 15 261 2341<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
This paper presents the results of a Delphi study that was carried<BR>
out between October 1995 and February 1996. The subject of the study,<BR>
external sources of vehicle propulsion, i.e., power or energy supply<BR>
systems outside the vehicle, could lead to a considerable reduction in<BR>
polluting emissions and a more efficient transport system:<BR>
<BR>
First, external propulsion makes possible the use of<BR>
power generation on a larger scale. In practice this leads to<BR>
a much higher efficiency and lower emissions. Moreover, the emission<BR>
of these gases can take place outside metropolitan areas.<BR>
Second, the choice of primary fuel can be flexible and<BR>
varied.<BR>
Third, the vehicles can be lighter. As a rule, the weight<BR>
of the drive system accounts for 20-25&Ouml;% of total vehicle weight. In<BR>
the case of electric vehicles, this can even exceed 50&Ouml;%.<BR>
Finally, when in the long term fossil fuels no longer<BR>
form the main energy source, energy generation within the vehicle<BR>
itself could become far more difficult than it is now. In May 1995,<BR>
six Dutch experts in the area of vehicle propulsion were invited to<BR>
participate in a brainstorming session, during which 14 ideas for<BR>
realizing external propulsion were to be evaluated. The list consisted<BR>
of<BR>
<BR>
&#183;technologies to transmit energy to electric vehicles by direct<BR>
contact<BR>
&#183;technologies to transmit energy to vehicles by means of<BR>
electromagnetic radiation<BR>
&#183;linear engines<BR>
&#183;mechanical technologies to transfer momentum to vehicles<BR>
&#183;technologies to propel vehicles by means of air pressure<BR>
<BR>
Since vehicle technology is developing on a global scale, it was important<BR>
to involve people from all over the world in the evaluation of these<BR>
technologies. A Delphi procedure was chosen for practical reasons as<BR>
well as for its superiority in preventing various undesirable<BR>
social/cultural effects that could disturb the evaluation. In three<BR>
rounds, using feedback loops, 25 experts on vehicle propulsion from<BR>
all over the world assessed the 14 ideas.<BR>
<BR>
The conclusion of the panel was that external propulsion was not<BR>
feasible, except for public transport, or in the case of highly<BR>
specific local circumstances. The main objections to external<BR>
propulsion are the cost of infrastructure, safety problems, limits to<BR>
the mobility of vehicles, and the current low energy prices. In<BR>
general, most technologies were either unsafe, would probably not<BR>
represent improvements in efficiency, or were impracticable. In the<BR>
short term, there is no scope for external propulsion technology. In<BR>
the long run, it remains doubtful whether externally powered<BR>
vehicles will ever play a role in sustainable private transport. The<BR>
panel predicted that vehicle propulsion using biomass derived fuel<BR>
would be feasible in 15-20 years. In the long term, fuel cells could<BR>
also play an important role. Thus, the future transport system would<BR>
probably consist of electric vehicles for short distances, combined<BR>
with internally propelled vehicles (biomass derived fuel or fuel<BR>
cells) for longer distances. If battery performance remains the major<BR>
problem posed by electric vehicles, technologies to supply energy<BR>
to moving vehicles could become important to extend the range of<BR>
electric vehicles. However, in many industrialized areas, households<BR>
might opt for an electric vehicle for short trips and an internal<BR>
combustion engine vehicle for travelling longer distances. External<BR>
propulsion could then play a part in keeping down the number of<BR>
vehicles.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws31tramob.html#anchor206250">workshop 4.1
page</A>.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Last changed: <I>August 14, <EM>1996</EM></I><EM> <BR>
</EM><I>INES Amsterdam pages administrator (<A HREF="mailto:amsterdam-pages@liststar.frt.fy.chalmers.se">amsterdam-pages@liststar.frt.fy.chalmers.se</A>)
</I>
</BODY>
