<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Kemmeren abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Subsidization of parking space in the Netherlands</H3>
Rob Kemmeren<BR>
Domselaarstraat 23-I, 1093 JM Amsterdam, Nederland<BR>
TEL/FAX: +31 20 665 9512 (first phone for fax),<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:kemmeren@pvda.nl">kemmeren@pvda.nl</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The growth in traffic, especially commuter traffic, results in<BR>
increasing levels of congestion and environmental problems. The call for<BR>
more infrastructure is becoming louder and louder, despite evidence that<BR>
the building of more roads provides only temporary relief. In this paper
the<BR>
author argues that in order to discourage the use of the motorcar, a<BR>
coherent parking policy should be implemented in place of the current<BR>
practice of providing parking space according to demand.<BR>
<BR>
In her 'Memorandum on implementing a parking policy' (&quot;Uitvoeringsnotitie<BR>
parkeerbeleid&quot;) the Minister for Transport, Maij Weggen, sums up<BR>
concisely the problems associated with a large number of free parking<BR>
spaces:<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Cars use a lot of public space. For every car, there are on average<BR>
three parking spaces, accounting for a total area of roughly 190 million<BR>
square metres estimated to be worth about 47 billion guilders. Of this<BR>
47 billion guilders, only a small proportion is directly paid for in the<BR>
form of paid parking. By 2010, when there will be approximately 8<BR>
million cars on the roads, the total amount of parking space will be<BR>
worth 75 billion guilders. Even now, the value of the parking space is<BR>
often higher than that of the car parked on it - particularly in urban<BR>
areas&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The large scale creation of this huge amount of parking space was no<BR>
accident. The VNG (The Association of Dutch Municipalities) decreed in<BR>
article 258 parking facilities (&quot;artikel 258 parkeer- en stallinggelegenheid&quot;)
that:<BR>
&quot;1. In case the size or function of a building requires parking or
long<BR>
term storing of motorized vehicles, mopeds or bicycles &Auml;&Ouml;ldots
parking<BR>
space should be adequately provided for.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
This policy has had two important consequences. Firstly, the costs of<BR>
parking space provisions are being ascribed to buildings, rather than to<BR>
transport infrastructure. Secondly, businesses are essentially forced to<BR>
adopt a demand-driven parking space policy: at all times the maximum<BR>
demand for parking space should be met.<BR>
<BR>
Attempts to bring car use under control usually involve some sort of<BR>
pricing policy, the idea being that higher prices lead to less use. A<BR>
prerequisite to make this work properly is of course the fact that all<BR>
costs, including those due to space usage, be taken into account. In<BR>
practice we see that although significantly higher prices do lead to less<BR>
traffic in the short term, it quickly rises back to the previous level.
A<BR>
regulatory policy based upon physical measures and limited parking space<BR>
would be more effective. The state should decide what the maximum level
of<BR>
traffic should be, and on the basis of that decide on the number of parking<BR>
spaces to be made available. The level of car use may then be controlled
by<BR>
varying the price of parking space. When mobility rises, and the demand
for<BR>
parking space becomes too great, the limited number of parking spaces will<BR>
automatically result in much higher prices and reduce mobility.<BR>
<BR>
The article is based upon the views and publications of W. Drees, in<BR>
&quot;Openbare Uitgaven,&quot; 1975 (nr. 7, juni) en 1994 (nr. 2)<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws31tramob.html#anchor206250">workshop 4.1
page</A>.<BR>
<BR>
