<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Bratzel abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Integrated Urban Mobility Management in Berlin: A strategy for sustainable
cities?</H3>
Stefan Bratzel<BR>
Freie Universit&auml;t Berlin, Environmental Policy<BR>
Research Unit<BR>
Malteserstr. 74-100, 12249 Berlin, Deutschland<BR>
TEL: +49 30 7792 250, FAX: +49 30 7762 081,<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:bratzel@zedat.fu-berlin.de">bratzel@zedat.fu-berlin.de</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
1. The Idea and Strategy<BR>
<BR>
The central concern of our Mobility-Management is a reduction of<BR>
commuter car use. To achieve this overall goal we use a twofold<BR>
strategy, which affects the kind of concept we use and the problem<BR>
solving procedure we apply. This strategy was the result of a study we<BR>
conducted in the beginning of the project, that figured out the social<BR>
and political &quot;conditions of success in urban transportation policy.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
2. The Concept<BR>
<BR>
The complete concept consists of four central measurements, that we call<BR>
&quot;corner stones&quot;:<BR>
<BR>
corner stone (1) company-oriented mobility management:<BR>
corner stone (2) public transit<BR>
corner stone (3) parking management<BR>
corner stone (4) institutionalisation of mobility management<BR>
<BR>
3. The Plan of Action<BR>
<BR>
The corner stone company-oriented mobility management for example<BR>
comprises of mobility advisory and &quot;stick and carrot&quot;-measures
for<BR>
employees, intended to generate substantial reductions in commuter car<BR>
use, especially of &quot;lone drivers.&quot; The employees are encouraged
to<BR>
commute by more environmentally compatible modes of transport, such as<BR>
feet, bicycle and public transport. Achieving behavioural changes is a<BR>
difficult task, so we carefully plan several steps of action:<BR>
&#183;A Transportation Situation Assessment<BR>
&#183;A Transportation Action Plan<BR>
&#183;The Implementation of the Plan by an &quot;Employee Mobility Co-ordinator&quot;<BR>
&#183;Evaluation of the Mobility Advisory Process<BR>
<BR>
4. Goals<BR>
<BR>
The goals of the project are on different levels.<BR>
<BR>
First of all we try to ameliorate - on a substantial level - the<BR>
concrete transportation oriented problems in the project area Tiergarten<BR>
(Moabiter Westen). Our measures aim to reduce the &quot;lone drivers&quot;
of<BR>
commuting and thereby lessen the share of private-motorised travel in<BR>
the area. As a &quot;side-effect&quot; of these measures we hope to improve
the<BR>
car-related pollution situation in this area, especially air and noise<BR>
pollution.<BR>
<BR>
The second goal concerns the problem-solving procedure. We try to<BR>
initiate a co-operative process, within which all relevant actors are<BR>
called to participate. This discursive process should promote mutual<BR>
understanding and reliance, whereby a self-dynamism should generate<BR>
policy learning effects. In the end consensual problem solving<BR>
capabilities should be achieved by the participating actors themselves.<BR>
<BR>
Our third goal is located on the institutional level. We will<BR>
generalise and standardise the mobility-management-approach to make the<BR>
concept and the procedure applicable for different users (companies,<BR>
administrations etc.). A usable integrated approach for solving<BR>
transportation-related problems will be drafted. Last but not least we<BR>
will undertake steps toward the institutionalisation of mobility<BR>
management on the political level. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
5. Preliminary results and main problems of the project.<BR>
<BR>
Though the project under discussion is still in an initial phase, progress
is<BR>
already perceptible. After presenting the results of our transportation<BR>
survey, all relevant actors are actively cooperating on the formulation<BR>
and implementation of the concept. Though some obstacles still have to be<BR>
removed, lessons can nevertheless already be drawn from the project.<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws31tramob.html#anchor206250">workshop 4.1
page</A>.<BR>
