<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Marvin abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Dematerialising the City? -- Telematics and the Urban Environment</H3>
Simon Marvin<BR>
Centre for Urban Technology (CUT)<BR>
Department of Town and Country Planning<BR>
University of Newcastle<BR>
Newcastle Upon Tyne, NE1 7RU, United Kingdom<BR>
TEL: +44 91 222 7282, FAX: +44 91 222 8811, <BR>
E-MAIL: S.J.Marvin@ncl.ac.uk<BR>
CUT on the WWW: <BR>
http://www.ncl.ac.uk/$&Ouml;sim$ncut<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
While researchers and policy makers are developing a greater<BR>
understanding of the role of telecommunications in many aspects of urban<BR>
life, the links between the physical environmental problems generated by<BR>
modern urban life and telecoms remain curiously disconnected debates.<BR>
Because of this neglect there are serious difficulties in addressing<BR>
relatively simple questions about the linkages between the<BR>
telecommunications and the urban environment:<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&#183; Do demands for the development of the 'sustainable city' compete<BR>
or coincide with the concept of the 'information city'?<BR>
&#183; Are telecommunications clean, environmentally benign<BR>
technologies that simply substitute information for physical resource<BR>
flows along energy and transport networks?<BR>
&#183; Will the development of virtual cities lead to the dissolution<BR>
of physical cities and their environmental problems?<BR>
<BR>
There are few satisfactory answers to these questions. Almost all the<BR>
research and policy interest in telecommunications has focused entirely<BR>
on their importance in urban economies, social polarisation, urban<BR>
culture and the changing physical form of the city. Likewise the<BR>
environmental sector has focused on the physical problems generated by<BR>
transportation, energy, water and waste networks, industrial production<BR>
and by buildings in the commercial and domestic sectors. There are very<BR>
few examples of research that have explicitly looked at the potential<BR>
connections between the two areas. Instead the vacuum has been dominated<BR>
by a perspective which assumes that telematics are an environmentally<BR>
benign set of technologies that can easily be manipulated to improve<BR>
environmental conditions in modern cities.<BR>
<BR>
This paper will re-connect interest in the creation of the &quot;wired&quot;
and<BR>
&quot;virtual city&quot; together with the development of the &quot;sustainable
city.&quot; <BR>
Adopting a critical perspective the paper argues that there are serious<BR>
tensions between these competing views of urban futures. Telematics and<BR>
telecommunications technologies will not lead to environmentally benign<BR>
cities in which material flows of resources are simply displaced by<BR>
dematerialised electronic flows. Instead urban environmental policy<BR>
needs to recognise the contradictory and complex interactions between<BR>
the physical and electronic city.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws32telsus.html#anchor266684">workshop 3.2
page</A>.<BR>
