<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Ollivier abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Economic and financial practices as regard unequal development</H3>
Marc Ollivier<BR>
CNRS/ISMEA, France<BR>
Les Arnauds, 38220 St Jean de Vaulx, France<BR>
TEL/FAX: +33 76 731 235, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:marc@criss.fr">marc@criss.fr
<BR>
<BR>
</A>The full text of this paper is available on the WWW:<BR>
<A HREF="http://www-com.grenet.fr/inesdev">http://www-com.grenet.fr/inesdev</A><BR>
<BR>
After pointing out the large gap between economic and social practices <BR>
(which characterize the human species since its beginning) and economic
<BR>
and social theories (which are very recent and can be considered as one
of <BR>
these practices since the development of sciences), the paper presents two
<BR>
approaches of the unequal development phenomenon.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
A historical approach<BR>
<BR>
The paper remarks that since the day it appeared on earth the human species
<BR>
has experienced a &quot;sustainable development&quot; because it is still
in existence. <BR>
But this globally &quot;sustainable development&quot; is in fact the result
of an <BR>
infinity of &quot;non sustainable developments&quot; spread over the dimensions
of <BR>
space and time. According to many scientists, the survival of the human
species <BR>
within the terrestrial biosphere could be questionable following several
<BR>
qualitative shifts in its ways of integrating the biosphere, but also because
of the <BR>
fragility of the one and only economic and social system that from this
<BR>
point onward dominates and reunites <BR>
all societies, nations and States of the world. Most analysts recognise
that <BR>
the evolution of the capitalist economic system and the societal practices
<BR>
that go along with capitalism played and still plays a driving role in the
<BR>
relatively recent phenomenon of the globalisation of the economy and accelerated
<BR>
generalisation of the process of unequal development on a planetary scale.
<BR>
The paper distinguishes three &quot;ruptures&quot; which explain the present
situation:<BR>
&#183;the &quot;scientific and technical revolution&quot; and its consequences;<BR>
&#183;the demographic expansion of the human species;<BR>
&#183;the world-wide expansion of the techno-structure rendering socio-economic
<BR>
systems homogeneous through the dynamism of modern capitalism.<BR>
<BR>
These decisive ruptures that portray our epoch in relation to the past <BR>
history of the human species are making way for a situation never seen <BR>
before: the disappearance of all societal diversity within humanity to <BR>
the benefit of a single mode of organisation and a single sample of this
<BR>
dominant mode. One can think by analogy with the problematic of <BR>
biodiversity that there is an enormous risk for <BR>
the future, since facing up to the very great uncertainty of what is to
<BR>
come we find ourselves as put coarsely, <BR>
&quot;with all our eggs in the same basket&quot;. Who can say for sure that
Capitalism, <BR>
the cause of this situation, will be adapted for future conditions of <BR>
reproduction and survival of humanity? This dominant Capitalism, in <BR>
spreading the unequal development phenomena, will it annihilate the <BR>
&quot;socio-diversity&quot; that has until today been an essential element
in <BR>
the reproduction of the human race, or will its evolution allow it to <BR>
maintain this diversity in a world in which the scientific and technical
<BR>
progress picks up speed with no limit seeming to have to produce a <BR>
technically homogeneous economy? <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
A structural approach<BR>
<BR>
The paper insists on four determinant processes generating unequal <BR>
development: the proletarianization of the work force and private sector
<BR>
appropriation of production means, the market expansion and &quot;free&quot;
movement <BR>
of goods and services, the concentration of capital, and the development
<BR>
of financial activities, with legal and illegal aspects (speculation, <BR>
corruption , extension of the mafias).<BR>
<BR>
Conclusions<BR>
<BR>
The paper recalls three preliminary facts: <BR>
&#183;it is impossible to go backwards; <BR>
&#183;it is necessarily on political grounds where sufficient social forces
<BR>
may gather together to bring new behaviour into action, since clearer <BR>
awareness of the problems to be resolved must become manifest at all <BR>
levels of the social fabric, and collective <BR>
initiative is to be taken to overcome these problems. Letting people <BR>
believe that we can progress towards a goal by merely mobilising financial
<BR>
resources and establishing another international bureaucratic structure,
<BR>
as the UNDP proposes, would be to create illusions and waste resources.<BR>
&#183;actions against the inequality of development being politically necessary,
<BR>
they are developed progressively, by much varied routes and levels and with
<BR>
equally different rhythms with respect to the continent or country. Therefore
<BR>
we must not seek to define uniformly for all what steps are to be taken.
<BR>
<BR>
Taking these facts into account, one has to hold out against the idea that
<BR>
ideological pressure and political will of the great economic and financial
<BR>
powers of world capitalism are irreversibly attached to the practices of
<BR>
&quot;laissez-faire policy&quot; so dear <BR>
to the fanatics of &quot;wild&quot; liberalism concerning commercial, monetary
and <BR>
financial matters. The monetary and financial &quot;laissez-faire&quot;
dominant today <BR>
is not less deadly for millions of men, women and children than the production,
<BR>
commerce and consumption <BR>
of heroin or cocaine which have been declared illegal. Thought and regulation
<BR>
in the area of bio-ethics is being developed in numerous countries based
on <BR>
the fact that progress in biology threatens the integrity and dignity of
<BR>
human beings, but is it not <BR>
the same, on a much more massive scale, for financial, monetary and economic
<BR>
techniques? It is therefore necessary and possible to propose a code of
<BR>
economic and financial ethics and a programme of mesures to have this code
<BR>
respected. <BR>
<BR>
Finally, the paper concludes with a set of proposals which have to be <BR>
discussed into the congress workshop &quot;confronting unequal development&quot;.<BR>
&#183; wasting resources in financial speculation has to be fought and reduced
<BR>
to a minimum.<BR>
It seems to us that it is necessary to rely on the technical means that
<BR>
exist in order to limit as much as possible the factors of instability,
<BR>
insecurity and counter-development due to speculation and the volatility
<BR>
of exchange rates:<BR>
&#183;controlling capital flow must be the first of these means of action
<BR>
to be put to work; along with it there should be a tax deducted for <BR>
speculative transactions that generate erratic shifts in exchange rates,
<BR>
which as early as 1978 had already been proposed by Nobel Prize winner J.Tobin.<BR>
&#183;the creation of a stable international monetary system should be <BR>
the following priority goal; this goal equally requires a solid political
<BR>
foundation that cannot be established, as previously, only upon agreement
<BR>
between the same powers. Moreover, <BR>
fluctuating exchange rates are currently a considerable source of profit
<BR>
for very powerful interests.<BR>
&#183; International transfers of unwarranted or fraudulent financial <BR>
resources must be stopped and charged illegal.<BR>
&#183;public and private debts that do not correspond with ordinary <BR>
commercial operations, productive investments must be voided and <BR>
control mechanisms for opening of international credit installed in order
<BR>
to avoid going back to situations of excessive over-endebtedness with no
<BR>
concrete basis; <BR>
&#183;those who are responsible for private capital leakage, illegal or
<BR>
fraudulent in nature, must be pursued and these resources are to be <BR>
restituted to the coffers of their State; <BR>
&#183;&quot;Tax havens&quot; or zones where illegal, fraudulent or criminal
cash <BR>
savings are hidden must be relinquished. They represent the spanner in <BR>
the works causing the current disfunction of the system and one of the <BR>
very efficient means by way of which they<BR>
are allowed to elude all social control. <BR>
&#183;the freedom of commercial exchanges and prices must be regulated,
<BR>
like all liberties. Absolute liberty is not conceivable without total anarchy:
<BR>
all public and individual liberties in existence are guaranteed by very
strict rules. <BR>
This why it is particularly necessary to continuously upgrade the rules
<BR>
of the GATT agreement (today the WTO) <BR>
and the sector-based agreements concerning customs protection, on the one
<BR>
hand by respecting a kind of &quot;subsidiary principle&quot; in regards
to the <BR>
productive systems of various countries, in such a way as to protect the
<BR>
capacities of production that each country is able to run on its own <BR>
without wasting resources, and on the other hand, by being careful not to
<BR>
let monopolies, the dangers of which we are familiar, be created on a <BR>
world-wide scale. <BR>
&#183;the means for planning and strategic investment financing have to
be <BR>
created at an international level. <BR>
The issue here is to go about establishing an economic and social <BR>
&quot;New Deal&quot; on a planetary scale. Articulated with others at the
<BR>
continental and regional levels, such an investment programme could help
<BR>
peoples construct Strategic domains are those of energy, <BR>
urbanisation, housing, drinking water available for everyone, <BR>
basic education and specialised training, and food and public health security.
<BR>
In the fields of production and consumption technologies, this &quot;New
Deal&quot; <BR>
should allow persuing long-term goals capable of ensuring the durability
<BR>
of development: the managing of non-renewable resources with precaution,
<BR>
expanded reproduction of renewable resources, mobilisation of the entire
<BR>
workforce at their level of qualific<BR>
aged at various levels of organisation (from village through to <BR>
international level). <BR>
&#183;Finally, a plan for managing social problems must be organised on
an <BR>
international scale.<BR>
Seen in the context of globalisation, it would then be appropriate to <BR>
organise co-ordination and progressive complementarity between existing
<BR>
systems of social protection in the different countries. This protection
<BR>
has always been considered, no matter what its imperfections were in the
past, <BR>
as an essential factor in the <BR>
security not only of the individuals directly concerned, but also the <BR>
entire social group. <BR>
Today our economic and financial system is spreading over the entire <BR>
earth, and we have technological means and resources more significant <BR>
than ever before available to us; but we are faced with risks on a <BR>
planetary scale. It is therefore necessary that we <BR>
elaborate a system of social protection composed of various levels <BR>
of mutual aid that expresses the down-to-earth, greater than ever need <BR>
for solidarity amongst all individuals and peoples of our planet.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws33casstu.html">workshop 3.3</A> page.<BR>
