<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Cetto abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Science and development -- a Latin American perspective</H3>
Ana Maria Cetto<BR>
Instituto de F&iacute;sica<BR>
Universidad Nacional Aut&ograve;noma de M&eacute;xico<BR>
Apartado postal 20 - 364, 01000 M&eacute;xico D.F., M&eacute;xico <BR>
TEL: +52 5 548 9783 / 622 5014 / 658 7528, <BR>
FAX: +52 5 616 1535 / 658 7528<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:ana@sysul1.ifisicacu.unam.mx">ana@sysul1.ifisicacu.unam.mx</A>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Being concerned by the tremendous development inequalities of today and<BR>
trying to understand how they can be met, we ask ourselves: what role do<BR>
the sciences play in relation to development? The aim of this paper is<BR>
to sketch some possible, even if partial, answers to this question from
a<BR>
Latin American perspective.<BR>
<BR>
For this purpose we include first a selection of statistical data and<BR>
indicators of development, which are clear symptoms of a highly<BR>
unstable, erratic and heterogeneous evolution; to overcome this<BR>
situation is one of our major challenges. It is under these<BR>
circumstances that one must address the question about the role that<BR>
science and the scientists have played and can play. <BR>
<BR>
Whereas in other parts of the world a rapid scientific and<BR>
technological transformation has taken place, this process of<BR>
development has not occurred in the so-called developing countries. We<BR>
present a brief description of the main features of the Latin American<BR>
scientific and technological system, to conclude that our signs of<BR>
'modernity' are to a large extent mere reflections or adaptations of the<BR>
advances produced in the developed world.<BR>
<BR>
To understand how this situation has come about, we briefly discuss some<BR>
of the main consequences of three centuries of colonial rule followed by<BR>
a difficult post-colonial period of political independence. It is clear<BR>
that the S&Ouml;&amp;T gap that existed already at the end of last century
has<BR>
only widened; in particular, our countries lag much behind in the<BR>
systematized production of relevant knowledge and in its utilization for<BR>
the solution of our problems and the benefit of our people. The various<BR>
aspects of dependence permeate the whole of our societies; they<BR>
determine even the objectives that we set for ourselves. The need to<BR>
break this vicious circle is a big challenge for our educational systems<BR>
and scientific communities: either S&Ouml;&amp;T is put to work for our
benefit,<BR>
or there is no guarantee that they will play such a positive role as<BR>
they are usually assigned. Latin America needs to design and implement<BR>
her own way of evolving, drawing as much as possible from her own<BR>
resources and on regional cooperation, with the purpose of gradually<BR>
achieving a capacity of self-determination and of interaction with the<BR>
rest of the world on an equal footing.<BR>
<BR>
In this regard, normally the population at large is taken as object of<BR>
study rather than as an active participant. There is, however a great<BR>
wealth of wisdom and knowledge that did not disappear with the conquest<BR>
but has been transmitted and enriched through generations and<BR>
constitutes a pillar for survival. There are valuable examples that<BR>
serve as testimony, in the areas of (truly) sustainable agriculture,<BR>
health care, food processing, use of natural resources, &Ouml;ldots, precisely<BR>
where some of the most pressing problems have been identified. Such<BR>
assets, if appropriately taken into consideration and linked to our<BR>
scientific systems, could result in important comparative advantages.<BR>
<BR>
This view is contrary to the conventional one among our scientists, who<BR>
largely consider international science as a highly successful endeavour,<BR>
disregarding what it has not achieved or has failed to do. In this<BR>
regard, we question whether the present scheme of science as produced<BR>
predominantly in the industrialized countries is the only possible one.<BR>
Nobody has been able to demonstrate that there is a unique way for<BR>
knowledge to support the development of humankind; in fact, very little<BR>
is known about how knowledge contributes to development. We seem to fear<BR>
that the act of investigating our own reality in our own way would<BR>
prevent us from being universal; whereas, on the contrary, the 'global'<BR>
modern civilization should be the integrated result of the contributions<BR>
of all peoples and cultures.<BR>
<BR>
A discussion of these matters with the participation of well-informed<BR>
members of all the relevant sectors could be particularly useful in<BR>
providing us with elements for alternative patterns of knowledge-based<BR>
and people-based development. We hope that the Amsterdam Congress will<BR>
provide a fertile ground for such discussions.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
