<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Serfaty abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Human rights violations, dictatorships and oppression in general as
obstacles to economic and social development</H3>
Abraham Serfaty<BR>
54 rue J.J. Rousseau, 94120 Fontenay sous Bois, France <BR>
FAX: +33 1 48 76 45 63<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Starting from the fact that the majority of Humanity remains victim of<BR>
dictatorial political regimes and find expressing their aspirations to a<BR>
better way of life impeded by a whole arsenal of repressive means, the<BR>
paper brings to light the gravity and importance of institutionalised<BR>
terror that weighs on the peoples and on the communities.<BR>
<BR>
Obviously these repressive and despotic attitudes are supported by the<BR>
current working of international relations and the predominant power<BR>
exercised by technocratic structures and by the banks and the financial<BR>
system of the western countries. But the responsibilities of the populist<BR>
nationalistic ideologies, which rejected whatever came from the former<BR>
colonizers, including the notion of modern democracy, are also<BR>
emphasized, as well as technocratic and chauvinistic interpretations of<BR>
Marxism in the former &quot;real socialist&quot; block.<BR>
<BR>
However, the political and social movements in the world reveal the<BR>
existence of very lively struggles for democracy: it is very important<BR>
to understand the beginnings of these struggles, the factors of success<BR>
that they bring about and the obstacles that explain their failures, in<BR>
attempts to imagine how the forces of success that exist everywhere<BR>
could be able to overcome developmental inequalities, beginning with<BR>
imposing the recognition of men's, women's and children's rights.<BR>
<BR>
But very powerful contradictory forces can equally be seen: during <BR>
the Gulf War, while trying to appear to fight Saddam Hussein's attack <BR>
on Koweit, the coalition forces lead by the US carried out the <BR>
systematic destruction of Irak's infrastructure and industrial <BR>
capacities, slowing up its development for years to come. In the <BR>
same manner, the exactions and the destruction that some of the <BR>
members of the ex-Federation of Yugoslavia commit on another can <BR>
only produce a very deep-rooted economic and social regression in <BR>
this region of Europe. Dramas analogic to this are happening in <BR>
Rwanda and several countries of the former soviet empire. <BR>
It has also become known that France, Italy and Spain, faced with <BR>
internal confrontations that are tearing apart an Algeria deeply <BR>
suffering from problems caused by the debt and corruption of its<BR>
Heads of State, envisage working together to create a &quot;Rapid<BR>
Intervention Force&quot; which is clearly directed against the peoples of<BR>
North Africa.<BR>
<BR>
Evolution of this type, whether already started or still only<BR>
threatening, shows us that the risk of seeing inequalities in<BR>
development worsened and further broadening of global areas doomed to<BR>
economic ruin and social and political chaos is not negligeable. It is<BR>
concluded that the struggle for the respect of Human Rights and the<BR>
strengthening of Democracy does not only concern individuals or groups<BR>
of individuals, but also entire peoples, that are collectively victims<BR>
of violence and repression.<BR>
<BR>
The paper shows how democratic forces in every country of the world have<BR>
necessarily equally common goals, such as deep reform of international<BR>
monetary and financial policies that worsen development inequalities<BR>
instead of setting them right. But these forces of democracy are<BR>
restricted to adjusting their actions to the realities of each country<BR>
and to the history of each people.<BR>
<BR>
Finally the paper concludes that the goal of development cannot be <BR>
limited to economic and technological notions. All aspects of <BR>
Man have to be taken into account to realise genuine development <BR>
and such development must be carried out under the direction and <BR>
through the intervention of human beings directly concerned.<BR>
Such a demand entails two essential conditions:<BR>
<BR>
&#183;the existence of a freedom space in which the rules of democracy <BR>
allow for all initiative to blossom and a concerted regulation of <BR>
social relations;<BR>
&#183;and in other respects the deep rootedness of the peoples concerned<BR>
in their history and culture, which is to say the acceptance and<BR>
recognition of their identity.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws34conune.html">workshop 3.4 </A>page.<BR>
