<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Donchenko et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Ecological integration as a key factor for Russia in the world process
of transitions to sustainable development</H3>
V.K. Donchenko and L.P. Romanyuk<BR>
Scientific Research Centre for Ecological Safety RAS<BR>
ul. Korpusnaia, St. Petersburg, Rossia<BR>
TEL: +7 812 230 7936, FAX: +7 812 235 4361,<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:wr@srces.samson.spb.su">wr@srces.samson.spb.su</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
A.D. Ursul (1) has substantiated the prospects for the<BR>
integration of Russia into the global socio-ecodevelopment process: &quot;The<BR>
lack of alternative to the model of sustainable development on a global<BR>
scale predetermines the necessity for the integration of Russia into<BR>
this process and the peculiar features of the &quot;Russian way&quot; into
the<BR>
noosphere.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The ecological crisis in Russia is occurring simultaneously with<BR>
the political crisis and has significantly contributed to the<BR>
dismantling of the old political system. However, Russia is still an<BR>
&quot;ecological superpower,&quot; since the natural environment of Russia
makes<BR>
up a significant share of the biospheric potential of the globe, and<BR>
during the reorganization of Russia's economic system, the natural<BR>
environment acts as a buffer to prevent an economic collapse by<BR>
providing the security capital (explicit or implicit) for foreign<BR>
investments, loans, credits, and financial support. At the same time,<BR>
public consciousness in Russia is based on the idea of a boundless<BR>
natural-resource potential of the country, which significantly<BR>
contributes to smoothing of the negative socio-economic impact involved<BR>
in the transition to a market economy and the transformation of property<BR>
relations.<BR>
<BR>
It is quite natural that the change in Russia's internal<BR>
socio-political orientation affects the external economic and political<BR>
relations. A new process of integrating Russia into the international<BR>
community is under way in practically all spheres. At the same time, in<BR>
view of the fact that Russia was isolated from the rest of the world for<BR>
a long time, the international community is anxious about the<BR>
difficulties entailed in such an integration in the economic, political,<BR>
and military spheres.<BR>
<BR>
At the same time, ecological integration of Russia has explicit aims<BR>
and objectives and may become a key factor in the development (on a<BR>
scientific basis) and implementation of new mechanisms for economic and<BR>
social management as a part of realization of the overall objective,<BR>
namely, sustainable, ecologically safe, development of the society as a<BR>
whole. The scope and content of ecological integration make it a<BR>
&quot;front-line&quot; experimental process, where there are spheres of
agreement,<BR>
co-operation, and mutual assistance.<BR>
<BR>
In this process, the use of foreign experience (based on a serious<BR>
and reasonable attitude) is of extreme importance. Since the preserved<BR>
biospheric potential of Russia compensates for (almost gratis) the<BR>
biospheric potential lost by many of the contiguous countries, Russia<BR>
will hold a proper position in the world community in the future. Fred<BR>
Harrison (2) feels certain that &quot;Russia will become a world leader
once<BR>
again. To this end, however, they need to learn to combine social<BR>
justice and wealth creation, with taking account of the interests of the<BR>
citizens and the Mother Nature.&quot; <BR>
Given below are the high-priority tasks:<BR>
&#183;Creation of a highly developed legal basis to ensure regulation of<BR>
the &quot;society-natural environment&quot; system.<BR>
&#183;Co-ordination of objectives and action plans aimed at perspective<BR>
social development of Russia as stipulated by international agreements<BR>
and obligations.<BR>
&#183;Participation of Russia in the development of effective methods of<BR>
economic activity management, based on ecological-safety criteria.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
References: 
<OL>
  <LI>Ursul A.D., Sustainable Development: Noospheric Perspectives, Metronom,
No. 2, 1993, p. 65-66. 
  <LI>Fred Harrison, A Russian Model. - London: Centrefor Stimulating Taxation;
St. Petersburg: SRC &quot;Ekograd,&quot; 1993. 47 pp. 
</OL>
