<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Conclusions of Workshop 4.2</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Conclusions of Workshop 4.2</H2>
<BR>
<BR>
NUCLEAR WEAPONS ABOLITION AND NUCLEAR WASTE STORAGE<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The Workshop on Nuclear Weapons Abolition and Nuclear Waste<BR>
Storage, which was composed of 22 participants from ten countries, <BR>
found that an essential element of sustainability that is often<BR>
overlooked is the need to move from a culture of violence to a<BR>
culture of peace. Nuclear weapons are the quintessential tool of<BR>
violence and coercion in the relationship between states, and may<BR>
be viewed as the apex of a pyramid of violence. The elimination<BR>
of these weapons of mass destruction would open new avenues to<BR>
achieving security and resolving conflicts without violence. <BR>
<BR>
Sustainability demands due regard to the concerns of future<BR>
generations, those without voice to speak for themselves. Nuclear<BR>
waste could adversely affect thousands of generations, and<BR>
therefore demands the utmost care by those generating these<BR>
dangerous substances. <BR>
<BR>
Nuclear Weapons Abolition <BR>
<BR>
The Workshop finds unprecedented opportunities in recent<BR>
events, including the World Court's Opinion on the general<BR>
illegality of nuclear weapons; the report of the Canberra<BR>
Commission on Elimination of Nuclear Weapons and particularly its<BR>
important suggestions for immediate steps to dramatically reduce<BR>
nuclear dangers; the efforts of the G-21 at the Conference on<BR>
Disarmament to set forth a timetable of steps to a nuclear weapons<BR>
free world; and the agreement on new nuclear weapons free zones in<BR>
Africa and Southeast Asia so that now nearly the entire Southern<BR>
Hemisphere is a nuclear weapons free zone.<BR>
<BR>
The Workshop also welcomes the initiatives of non-governmental<BR>
organizations, particularly the Abolition 2000 Network, a growing<BR>
citizens' movement for nuclear weapons abolition.<BR>
<BR>
A number of important challenges are currently facing the<BR>
international community, including issues of security in Europe<BR>
(expansion of NATO and the Eurobomb); growing stocks of plutonium,<BR>
and its transport and processing by some countries; the need to<BR>
complete the CTBT, and then move beyond a focus on nuclear<BR>
explosions to ban all design and development of new nuclear weapons<BR>
and to open the weapons laboratories to full transparency; the need<BR>
for the Russian Duma to ratify START II, and for the U.S. and<BR>
Russia to move forward with START III; and the growing threat of<BR>
nuclear terrorism.<BR>
<BR>
Perhaps the greatest single obstacle to nuclear weapons<BR>
abolition is the lack of political will by the nuclear weapons<BR>
states. To achieve this political will there will need to be far<BR>
more public debate and media attention to critical issues related<BR>
to nuclear dangers and opportunities. Scientists and engineers<BR>
can play a role in stimulating public interest and discussion of<BR>
these issues.<BR>
<BR>
Recommendations:<BR>
<BR>
1. Negotiations among governments should commence immediately on a<BR>
Convention for the Elimination of Nuclear Weapons within a time-<BR>
bound framework. The conclusion of this Convention should be by<BR>
the year 2000.<BR>
<BR>
2. Scientists and Engineers can contribute to this by studying the<BR>
recommendations of the Canberra Commission and similar initiatives,<BR>
and offering proposals on the technical aspects of implementation.<BR>
<BR>
3. In particular, a Societal Impact Assessment should be generated,<BR>
covering all aspects of nuclear weapons development, testing, use,<BR>
dismantlement and waste storage, with full consideration of the<BR>
long time-frames of potential hazards, and the impact on societies<BR>
due to secrecy and the need for expert control.<BR>
<BR>
4. One principle on which a Societal Impact Assessment could be<BR>
undertaken is that of the &quot;Polluter Pays.&quot; This should be applied<BR>
to the nuclear weapons states collectively. They must bear<BR>
responsibility for dismantlement of their weapons, clean-up of the<BR>
environmental damage they have caused, and disposal of the nuclear<BR>
wastes.<BR>
<BR>
5. The status of plutonium needs to be clarified. It must be<BR>
viewed as a liability and not an asset. Its 24,400 year half-life<BR>
and extreme health and environmental hazards raise key issues of<BR>
inter-generational equity.<BR>
<BR>
6. Another principle for a Societal Impact Assessment is to make<BR>
explicit the relationship between nuclear power and nuclear<BR>
weapons, and between the environmental and proliferation issues<BR>
related to plutonium.<BR>
<BR>
7. The Workshop felt that existing arms control treaties should be<BR>
seen as valuable but incomplete. The CTBT will not end research<BR>
and further development of nuclear weapons since it allows the use<BR>
of computer simulations and other scientific means to develop<BR>
weapons. <BR>
<BR>
8. It is important, therefore, that scientists and engineers assume<BR>
a more important role in challenging projects that continue nuclear<BR>
weapons development under the guise of pure science. This means<BR>
supporting whistle-blowers of secret government activities in this<BR>
area.<BR>
<BR>
9. The Workshop recommends that scientists and engineers should<BR>
rethink their relationship to the state, and more actively<BR>
challenge the ways in which science has been used. The moral,<BR>
ethical and legal issues raised by nuclear weapons is only part of<BR>
the agenda. Scientists should speak out on these issues to their<BR>
peers as well as to governments and fellow citizens.<BR>
<BR>
Nuclear Waste Storage<BR>
<BR>
Nuclear energy and nuclear weapons production are not<BR>
sustainable because their radioactive wastes are an enormous<BR>
negative burden on current and future generations of living species<BR>
and their environment. The isotopic half-lives of these wastes<BR>
last far beyond practical human comprehension and current technical<BR>
skill to deal with them. Their mutagenic consequences will last<BR>
virtually forever.<BR>
<BR>
A major challenge facing humanity is to end nuclear waste<BR>
production by stopping uranium mining, phasing out nuclear energy<BR>
production (eg. civil electrical power, ship propulsion, satellite<BR>
power, etc.) and prohibiting nuclear weapons production,<BR>
particularly plutonium separation, uranium enrichment and tritium<BR>
production. Halting these activities supports sustainable nuclear<BR>
disarmament by reducing and eventually eliminating access to these<BR>
materials. <BR>
<BR>
Recommendations: <BR>
<BR>
1. Enact a nuclear waste transportation moratorium.<BR>
<BR>
2. Retain nuclear wastes at their point of origin.<BR>
<BR>
3. Convert government nuclear subsidies to R &amp; D funding for <BR>
nuclear waste management.<BR>
<BR>
4. Renegotiate existing statutes of contracts concerning nuclear<BR>
wastes.<BR>
<BR>
5. Debate definitions of nuclear classifications democratically.<BR>
<BR>
6. Classify all plutonium, and possibly all nuclear reactors and<BR>
their containments as nuclear wastes. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Participants of the Workshop on Nuclear Weapons Abolition and<BR>
Nuclear Waste Storage:<BR>
<BR>
1. Colin Archer, International Peace Bureau, Switzerland.<BR>
2. Edel Havin Beukes, WILPF, Norway. <BR>
3. Maria Drotmann, Umwelt Akademie Fresenivs, Germany.<BR>
4. Eric Fawcett, Science for Peace, Canada.<BR>
5. Gert Harigel, CERN, Switzerland.<BR>
6. Huub Jaspers, Trans National Institute, Netherlands.<BR>
7. Martin Kalinowski, IANUS, Germany.<BR>
8. G. J. Koteles, National Institute Radiobiology, Hungary.<BR>
9. David Krieger*, Nuclear Age Peace Foundation, U.S.A.<BR>
10. Carlota Lopes da Silva, WILPF, Netherlands.<BR>
11. Svetlana Maiortehik, Baltic University Program, Belarus.<BR>
12. Ak Malten, Global Anti-Nuclear Alliance, Netherlands.<BR>
13. Zia Mian, SDPI, Pakistan.<BR>
14. Gururaj Mutalik, IPPNW, U.S.A.<BR>
15. John Otranto, Global Care, Germany.<BR>
16. Roland Reimers, Universitat Bremen, Germany.<BR>
17. Jurgen Scheffran, INESAP, Germany.<BR>
18. Puck Schmidt, WILPF, Netherlands.<BR>
19. Bart van der Sijde, Eindhoven Univ. of Technology, Netherlands.<BR>
20. Charlotte Wetzel, Women for Peace and Ecology, Germany.<BR>
21. Marcel Witt, Baltic University Program, Germany.<BR>
22. Alla Yaroshinskaya, Yaroshinskaya Charity Foundation, Russia.<BR>
<BR>
___________<BR>
* Workshop Convenor<BR>
