<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Krieger 1 abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Abolition 2000: lessons of the past year</H3>
David Krieger<BR>
Nuclear Age Peace Foundation <BR>
1187 Coast Village Road, Suite # 123, Santa Barbara CA 93108, USA <BR>
TEL: +1 805 965 3443, FAX: +1 805 568 0466<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:napf@igc.apc.org">napf@igc.apc.org</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
In the past year the growing movement for the abolition of nuclear<BR>
weapons has faced the proponents of retaining nuclear weapons in three<BR>
major engagements. It would be useful to reflect upon these, and<BR>
consider the lessons we can apply to future efforts. The three<BR>
struggles I refer to are the Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT)<BR>
Review and<BR>
Extension Conference, which took place at United Nations Headquarters in<BR>
New York; French Testing in the South Pacific; and the World Court case,<BR>
which was heard in The Hague.<BR>
<BR>
NPT Review and Extension Conference<BR>
<BR>
At the preparatory committee meetings leading up to this Conference and<BR>
at the Conference itself, in April-May 1995, the abolition movement<BR>
lobbied for an extension of the Treaty that would be linked to a<BR>
commitment by the nuclear weapons states (NWS) to eliminate nuclear<BR>
weapons within a time-bound framework. To do this, it was argued, the<BR>
Treaty should not be extended indefinitely, but rather for specific and<BR>
renewable periods of time when progress toward the abolition of nuclear<BR>
weapons would be reviewed by Treaty members.<BR>
<BR>
The NWS lobbied hard for an indefinite extension of the Treaty with no<BR>
strings attached. They clearly preferred to maintain the two-tier<BR>
structure in which they, and only they, could maintain nuclear arsenals,<BR>
and all other states were prohibited from doing so. They put<BR>
significant pressure on the non-aligned states, but in the end were able<BR>
to obtain the indefinite extension of the Treaty only with the<BR>
acceptance of certain non-binding conditions. The most important of<BR>
these, reinforcing the promises in Article VI of NPT, <BR>
were the pledges<BR>
regarding nuclear disarmament. These are:<BR>
<BR>
(a) The completion by the Conference on Disarmament of the<BR>
negotiations on a universal and internationally and effectively<BR>
verifiable Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty no later than 1996.<BR>
Pending the entry into force of a Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, the<BR>
nuclear-weapons States should exercise utmost restraint;<BR>
(b) The immediate commencement and early conclusion of negotiations<BR>
on a non-discriminatory and universally applicable convention banning<BR>
the production of fissile material for nuclear weapons or other nuclear<BR>
explosive devices, in accordance with the statement of the Special<BR>
Coordinator of the Conference on Disarmament and the mandate contained<BR>
therein;<BR>
(c) The determined pursuit by the nuclear-weapon States of<BR>
systematic and progressive efforts to reduce nuclear weapons globally,<BR>
with the ultimate goal of eliminating those weapons, and by all States<BR>
of general and complete disarmament under strict and effective<BR>
international control.<BR>
&Ouml;end&auml;description <BR>
While these pledges by the nuclear weapons states are not legally<BR>
binding, they provide standards by which to measure their behavior in<BR>
the future. This behavior came under question almost immediately when<BR>
the Chinese conducted a nuclear test within days of the end of the<BR>
Conference, and the French announced a month later that they would<BR>
conduct a series of tests in the South Pacific.<BR>
<BR>
I would draw the following lessons from this Conference:<BR>
&#183;The NWS intend to fight hard to maintain their position of<BR>
nuclear &quot;elitism&quot; in the world and are not prepared to move rapidly<BR>
toward nuclear abolition on their own.<BR>
&#183;The NWS have important powers of the pocketbook to influence the<BR>
positions of other states on this issue.<BR>
&#183;The states of the Non-Aligned Movement, a majority of the<BR>
world's nations, favor the elimination of nuclear weapons in a<BR>
time-bound framework. However, to keep them together on this issue,<BR>
lobbying and other behind-the-scenes work must be done at the United<BR>
Nations and in national capitals well before the issue comes to a point<BR>
of decision.<BR>
&#183;It is very difficult to get the press to pay attention to this<BR>
issue and, when they do, to understand it. A major effort must be<BR>
devoted to reaching and educating key members of the press before an<BR>
important events occur.<BR>
&#183;The NGOs that organized in advance of the Conference had the<BR>
most success in their lobbying efforts at the Conference and in reaching<BR>
the media. (This may be primarily due to the fact that these NGOs<BR>
supported the position of the NWS and consequently were well funded by<BR>
U.S. foundations to prepare for the Conference.)<BR>
&#183;The NGOs supporting abolition increased their effectiveness by<BR>
meeting in caucus to share information and work assignments during the<BR>
Conference.<BR>
<BR>
French Testing in the South Pacific<BR>
<BR>
From September 1995 through February 1996 the French conducted six<BR>
nuclear tests on atolls in the South Pacific. Their testing raised<BR>
protests throughout the world and resulted in boycotts of French<BR>
products. The protests were particularly vehement from nations in the<BR>
Pacific where the threat was felt more immediately, and came from<BR>
governments as well as citizen groups.<BR>
<BR>
The French stated on many occasions that the reason for the testing was<BR>
to obtain information that would allow them to conduct<BR>
computer-simulated tests after a Comprehensive Test Ban went into<BR>
effect. This, they argued, would put them on an equal footing with the<BR>
other NWS. The French government made it clear that they needed this<BR>
information in order to assure their deterrent force in the future.<BR>
<BR>
One positive outcome of French testing was that it provided the impetus<BR>
for the Australian government to establish the Canberra Commission on<BR>
the Elimination of Nuclear Weapons. This Commission, composed of<BR>
experts from throughout the world, is the first high-level international<BR>
commission sponsored by a Western government to seriously examine the<BR>
steps needed to abolish nuclear weapons.<BR>
<BR>
The lessons I would draw from French testing are as follows:<BR>
&#183;The French government, like other NWS, intends to maintain its<BR>
nuclear arsenal for the indefinite future.<BR>
&#183;The NWS intend to continue to test their nuclear weapons by<BR>
means of computer simulations after entering into a Comprehensive Test<BR>
Ban Treaty.<BR>
&#183;One person in a position of power in a NWS, like Jacques Chirac,<BR>
can set his will against the people of his own country and the people of<BR>
the world with regard to nuclear weapons. In this case it was testing,<BR>
but in the future it could be use.<BR>
&#183;There is widespread public opposition to continued testing of<BR>
nuclear weapons. This opposition may be built upon to create a<BR>
groundswell of public support for the elimination of these weapons.<BR>
&#183;Public opposition to French testing caused the French government<BR>
to reduce the originally announced schedule of eight tests to six, and<BR>
to make other concessions such as calling for a zero yield test ban<BR>
agreement.<BR>
<BR>
The World Court Case<BR>
<BR>
The requests by the World Health Organization and the United Nations<BR>
General Assembly for advisory opinions from the International Court of<BR>
Justice in The Hague on the illegality of the threat or use of nuclear<BR>
weapons resulted in oral hearings at the Court in October-November 1995.<BR>
More nations participated in these hearings than in any case before the<BR>
Court previously.<BR>
<BR>
The NWS and some of their allies argued that the Court <BR>
should not issue<BR>
an opinion since this was a political rather than a legal issue. They<BR>
further argued that if the Court did issue an opinion, it should find<BR>
that the threat or use of nuclear weapons was not illegal under<BR>
international law. Non-aligned states argued that the threat or use of<BR>
nuclear weapons would be illegal as a violation of the laws of war<BR>
against weapons that are excessively injurious and cause unnecessary<BR>
suffering, cause disproportionate harm, release poisonous toxins<BR>
(radioactivity), violate neutrality, and cause severe, widespread, and<BR>
long-term harm to the environment.<BR>
<BR>
The Court is now deliberating and preparing its opinion, which is<BR>
expected to be released to the public in late March.<BR>
<BR>
These lessons may be drawn from the World Court case:<BR>
<BR>
&#183;There is a very strong case to be made for the illegality of the<BR>
threat or use of nuclear weapons.<BR>
&#183;The arguments made by the NWS before the Court were strained and<BR>
self-serving.<BR>
&#183;NGOs were successful in encouraging the World Health Organization<BR>
and the General Assembly of the United Nations to ask the Court for<BR>
advisory opinions despite strong lobbying from the NWS not to do so.<BR>
This demonstrates that NGOs can be a powerful force in influencing<BR>
decisions of the international community if they are organized,<BR>
creative, and persistent.<BR>
&#183;The majority of countries in the world believe that the World<BR>
Court should provide an advisory opinion on this issue, and not duck the<BR>
issue as the NWS would prefer.<BR>
&#183;The press was again not particularly active in reporting on this<BR>
important event, and therefore the public was kept largely uniformed of<BR>
it.<BR>
<BR>
Conclusions<BR>
<BR>
This past year has witnessed an important series of events related to<BR>
the abolition of nuclear weapons. Some general conclusions can be drawn:<BR>
&#183;The NWS are tough opponents. They are rich, powerful, willing to<BR>
flex their muscles, and to cajole and bribe other states to support them<BR>
in maintaining their nuclear arsenals.<BR>
&#183;Abolitionists are gaining ground. We are better organized than we<BR>
were a year ago. There are more of us throughout the world, we are<BR>
communicating better with each other (although there is much room for<BR>
improvement here), and we are developing strategies to achieve short,<BR>
medium, and long-term goals.<BR>
&#183;As abolitionists, we have articulated our vision in the Abolition<BR>
2000 Statement developed at the NPT Review and Extension Conference, <BR>
and<BR>
in other subsequent statements, including the Founding Declaration of<BR>
the U.S. Abolition Network. These statements provide a grounding for our<BR>
efforts, and work must be done in spreading this vision to the public<BR>
and to specific broader communities, such as religious communities,<BR>
throughout the world and particularly in the NWS. It is important to<BR>
keep a focus on the target date of the year 2000 for achieving a Nuclear<BR>
Weapons Convention committing all NWS to the elimination of nuclear<BR>
weapons within a time-bound framework.<BR>
&#183;A weak point in the abolition movement has been in getting our<BR>
vision across to the public in a simple, clear and inspiring way. We<BR>
must continue to brainstorm and seek professional assistance on how to<BR>
do this more effectively.<BR>
&#183;Another weak point in the abolition movement has been in getting<BR>
our message across to the press. This area must be a major focus of our<BR>
efforts. Specific reporters at selected newspapers, magazines, and radio<BR>
and television stations throughout the world should be targeted for<BR>
education on nuclear weapons issues and the goals of the abolition<BR>
movement.<BR>
&#183;Specific efforts should be made to keep statements by 1995 Nobel<BR>
Peace Laureate Joseph Rotblat in the press, and also any statements on<BR>
nuclear weapons issues coming from the Canberra Commission and the<BR>
Non-Aligned Movement.<BR>
&#183;The promises of the NWS in Article VI of the <BR>
NPT, and those made<BR>
at the NPT Review and Extension Conference, should be kept before the<BR>
NWS like a mirror, <BR>
and any deviations from these promises should be made<BR>
public issues.<BR>
&#183;The opinion of the World Court on the illegality of the threat or<BR>
use of nuclear weapons, when it is issued, should be used to further the<BR>
goals of abolition. If the opinion supports illegality, abolitionists<BR>
should demand that the NWS comply. If the opinion supports legality<BR>
under certain circumstances, efforts should be made to change the law so<BR>
that it is compatible with the most basic standards of human rights and<BR>
human dignity.<BR>
<BR>
As we continue our work to achieve the complete elimination of nuclear<BR>
weapons, we should keep in mind the message of the Hibakusha, &quot;Never<BR>
again! We must not repeat this evil.&quot; To abolish nuclear weapons is
not<BR>
only an issue of security, politics, economics, environment, and human<BR>
rights. At its center, it is a spiritual issue, an issue of the soul. No<BR>
nation has the right to threaten the destruction of hundreds of millions<BR>
of people, perhaps all human life and that of many other species, in the<BR>
name of national security. To abolish nuclear weapons is to free<BR>
ourselves and humanity of this corruption. It is a critical test of the<BR>
human spirit and our ability to cooperate as a species that we are<BR>
facing as we approach the new millennium.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
