<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Lopes da Silva abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Nuclear weapons/energy versus security</H3>
Carlota Lopes da Silva<BR>
Women's International League for Peace and Freedom (WILPF)<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:100571.502@compuserve.com">100571.502@compuserve.com</A><BR>
International address:  WILPF<BR>
1, Rue de Varembe, 1211 Gen&egrave;ve, Suisse<BR>
TEL: +41 22 733 6175, FAX: +41 22 740 1063<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:womensleague@gn.apc.org">womensleague@gn.apc.org</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
When we think of sustainability, energy-production is a very important<BR>
subject. In many countries a vast amount of research and development<BR>
has gone to nuclear energy, not to solar or other renewable forms of<BR>
energy. The use of nuclear energy is closely connected with military<BR>
aspects. Nuclear energy requires a police presence to protect the fuel,<BR>
the reactors and the waste generated.<BR>
<BR>
Nuclear energy is intimately tied to the nuclear weapons industry. The<BR>
terrible tragedy of Chernobyl (now 10 years ago) reminds us how<BR>
dangerous relying on nuclear power can be. (The reactors in Chernobyl<BR>
were not only for supplying electricity, but also for the generation of<BR>
materials for nuclear weapons.)<BR>
<BR>
Concerns and evidence regarding the health and environmental effects<BR>
have contributed to the adoption of the Treaty Banning Nuclear Tests in<BR>
the atmosphere (Partial Nuclear Test Ban Treaty, 1963) - and recently to<BR>
the negotiations on a Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT). <BR>
A nuclear war would be an ecological disaster, but so is<BR>
building, transporting and testing of nuclear weapons.<BR>
<BR>
Energy production that is dependent upon fossil fuel resources leads to<BR>
competition and conflict in order to protect or obtain the fuels (The<BR>
Gulf War shows this!). The burning of fossil fuels contributes to<BR>
climate changes which will result in migration - even wars - due to<BR>
changes in rainfall, agriculture etc.<BR>
<BR>
Decentralized production of renewable energy gives the people a stake in<BR>
the sustainability of the system. Renewable energy sources are essential<BR>
to international peace and security.<BR>
<BR>
Further research, education and political action are needed to promote<BR>
the concept of a common security based on protecting the environment,<BR>
rather than a power strategy based on armies and weapons of mutual<BR>
destruction. Common security, the idea that was introduced in the Palme<BR>
Commission report, &quot;must replace the present expedient of deterrent<BR>
through armaments; it must rest on a commitment to joint survival,<BR>
rather than a threat of mutual destruction.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
This vision of security asks for ending the nuclear experiment, and<BR>
globally developing new ways of sustainably methods of energy-production<BR>
- and conflict-solving.<BR>
<BR>
We have not promoted renewable energy enough internationally. The only<BR>
international UN-agency on energy is the International Atomic Energy<BR>
Agency (IAEA), founded to promote &quot;peaceful use of the atom.&quot;
<BR>
This should be abolished and a new agency for sustainable energy should<BR>
be established instead.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws42nucwea.html#anchor515837">workshop 4,2</A><A HREF="../ws35polsus.html#anchor10311622">
</A>page.<BR>
