<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Lock abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Conventional disarmament, arms exports and conversion in Russia and
CEE</H3>
Peter Lock<BR>
EART e.V. European Association for Research on Transformation <BR>
c/o Peter Lock, Auf der Koppel 40, 22399 Hamburg, Deutschland<BR>
TEL/FAX: +49 40 602 7975, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:eartpl@oln.comlink.apc.org">eartpl@oln.comlink.apc.org</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Gorbatchev nurtured the illusion that the end of the Cold War might provide<BR>
the Soviet economy with sufficient reserves (`peace dividend') to prevent<BR>
the Soviet system from collapsing. The system collapsed however and its
very<BR>
core, the Soviet MIC (VPK), suffered the heaviest losses of all industrial<BR>
sectors. Nowhere was the disenchantement as profound as within the <BR>
MIC andthe consequences of the transformation process as resented. During
<BR>
the initial period of transformation the League of Military Industries<BR>
appeared as a cohesive and powerful industrial lobby in Russia. It turned<BR>
out, however, that individual enterprises and research institutes developed<BR>
diverging interests while still paying lip service to the League.<BR>
<BR>
Internal and external demand shrank to minimum levels with little prospects<BR>
to recover except in case of a complete reversal of the transformation<BR>
process. Hence the military <BR>
enterprises apply diverging strategies in their fight for survival. The<BR>
paper will discuss the determinants of the different approaches and the<BR>
respective chances to succeed. Effective demand (procurement and export),<BR>
the capability to innovate and to compete with the <BR>
leading American producers, international co-operation, and the capability<BR>
to expand into civilian markets on the basis of synergies (space launch<BR>
systems i.e.) are the major determinants.<BR>
<BR>
In the case of smaller states the strategic question is how to integrate
the<BR>
remaining national arms production capacities into the international<BR>
division of labour. To what extent can Russia fend off a total dominance
of<BR>
Western penetration of the markets? <BR>
<BR>
Finally, the military posture of Germany and the <BR>
NATO forces in Europe will codetermine the stability of the on-going <BR>
Russian downsizing. The paper<BR>
therefore argues in favour of integrating the Russian MIC<BR>
in co-operative schemes within Europe. Thus, a European <BR>
defence industrial base contributing to condition of stability and security<BR>
would have to include Russia.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws44condis.html#anchor236576">workshop 4,4</A>
page.<BR>
<BR>
