<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Holmberg et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Resource and environmental restrictions on metal flows and stocks in
a future global industrial  society</H3>
John Holmberg, Sten Karlsson (corresponding author, <A HREF="mailto:frtsk@fy.chalmers.se">frtsk@fy.chalmers.se</A>)
and<BR>
Stefan Wirsenius<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.frt.fy.chalmers.se/frteng.html">Institute of Physical
Resource Theory</A><BR>
Chalmers University of Technology och G&ouml;teborg University<BR>
S-412 96 G&ouml;teborg, Sweden<BR>
TEL: +46 31 772 31 49, FAX: +46 31 772 31 50 <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Metals are characteristic of the industrial society. The societal use is<BR>
large compared to the turnover in nature. However, potentially<BR>
extractable metal ore deposits are suffering from various degrees of<BR>
scarcity. The intensive and often dissipative use of metals has led to<BR>
severe contamination of the environment and threat to human health. A<BR>
further industrialisation of the world due to an increasing economic<BR>
standard, as well as an expected increase in the global population to<BR>
around 10 billion people during the next century will lead to an<BR>
enhanced demand for metals.<BR>
<BR>
Here we examine metal resource aspects of the possibilities to achieve<BR>
and sustain a metal metabolism in a future global industrial society of<BR>
10 billion people with an average per capita economic standard<BR>
comparable to that of the industrial countries today. We also compare<BR>
resource restrictions to limits set by the assimilation capacity of<BR>
metals in the environment.<BR>
<BR>
We show that for several metals, the ultimately available amounts of<BR>
metal resources will restrict the accumulation of metal stocks in the<BR>
technosphere to per capita levels below the historical use in present<BR>
industrial countries. Because it is a restriction on the accumulated<BR>
stock, this conclusion is relatively unaffected of increased recycling.<BR>
We argue that the restriction can have important implications for<BR>
strategic choices among possible future key technologies, within, for<BR>
instance, energy conversion and storage. It also raises the question of<BR>
allocation of metal resource use within and between human generations.<BR>
<BR>
The possibilities to within a limited time build up required stocks of<BR>
specific metals in various important applications may be even further<BR>
restricted by the interconnectedness of various metals resources due to<BR>
geological circumstances or feasibility and economics of extraction<BR>
processes.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../posterabstracts.html">poster abstracts page</A>.<BR>
