<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Holmberg et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Exergy, ecology and democracy -- concepts of a sustainable development</H3>
G&ouml;ran Wall<BR>
Department of Engineering, Kristianstad University<BR>
P.O. Box 59, 291 21 Kristianstad, Sverige<BR>
TEL: +46 44 203 171, FAX: +46 44 203 153, <BR>
TEL/FAX: +46 31 877 579<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:Goran.Wall@tec.hkr.se">Goran.Wall@tec.hkr.se</A>,
<A HREF="mailto:Goran.Wall@hks.se">Goran.Wall@hks.se</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The vitality of society depends strongly on the management of<BR>
physical, environmental and human resources. The dilemmas of modern<BR>
society can be stated as: misuse of physical resources through poor<BR>
understanding of concepts such as exergy, misuse of nature from<BR>
ignorance of ecology, and misuse of people or human intelligence from<BR>
lack of democracy. Exergy is a well-established concept in engineering,<BR>
the awareness of the living nature and its behaviour is increasing and<BR>
new rules for management of people are being successfully developed in<BR>
Japan. Optimization of real world processes involving energy, matter and<BR>
people must include all these parts, otherwise, it will only be a sub<BR>
optimization doomed to failure. An exergy tax is suggested as a first<BR>
step to improve present resource use and decrease environmental<BR>
destruction.<BR>
<BR>
