<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Karlsson abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Sustainable use of metals? An analysis from the example of lead</H3>
Sten Karlsson<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.frt.fy.chalmers.se/frteng.html">Institute of Physical
Resource Theory</A><BR>
Chalmers University of Technology och G&ouml;teborg University<BR>
S-412 96 G&ouml;teborg, Sweden<BR>
TEL: +46 31 772 31 49, FAX: +46 31 772 31 50 <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:frtsk@fy.chalmers.se">frtsk@fy.chalmers.se</A> 
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The historical use of metals has to various extent emptied rich ore<BR>
resources and threatened the environment and the human health. To what<BR>
extent is this avoidable in the future and what are the important<BR>
determining factors? We examine the possibilities for a future sustainable<BR>
large-scale use of a toxic and scarce metal, the lead metal. This is done<BR>
by analysing the lead flows and losses to the environment in a modelled<BR>
lead-acid battery system for Sweden. The modelled system is built on<BR>
today's technology for production and recycling of lead and batteries,<BR>
while the recovery of used batteries is varied. The analysis shows that
the<BR>
losses from the production and recycling processes are so low that the<BR>
consumption losses and recovery factor are very important for the total<BR>
system losses. In a situation with a very high recovery of used batteries,<BR>
the system losses are small compared to natural lead flows. The analysis
is<BR>
applicable to other metals as well.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../posterabstracts.html">poster abstracts page</A>.<BR>
