<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Vehmas et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>The debate of energy taxation policy in Finland in the 90's: What the
policy makers can learn about it.</H3>
Jarmo Vehmas<BR>
E-MAIL: jarmo.vehmas@uta.fi <BR>
Jyrki Luukkanen<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:atjylu@uta.fi">atjylu@uta.fi</A><BR>
University of Tampere, Environmental Policy/Department<BR>
of Regional Studies<BR>
P.O. Box 607, 33101 Tampere, Suomi<BR>
TEL: +358 31 215 7036, FAX: +358 31 215 7311, <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:atjave@uta.fi%20">atjave@uta.fi </A><BR>
WWW: <A HREF="http://www.uta.fi/~atjave/">http://www.uta.fi/~atjave/</A>
(only in Finnish)  <BR>
   <BR>
Pentti Malaska and Jari Kaivo-oja<BR>
Turku School of Economics, Finland Futures Research Centre<BR>
P.O. Box 110, 20521 Turku, Suomi<BR>
FAX: +358 21 233 0755, <BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:Malaska@utu.fi">Malaska@utu.fi</A>, <A HREF="mailto:Jari.Kaivo-oja@tukkk.fi%20">Jari.Kaivo-oja@tukkk.fi
</A><BR>
  <BR>
<BR>
The paper presents current prospects for incorporating environmental<BR>
costs in energy prices in Finland, and describes the progressive energy<BR>
taxation reform in 1990's. A review of the debate in Finland on the<BR>
structure and level of the energy taxation in 1990s is given.<BR>
<BR>
The statements of different energy policy makers and agents<BR>
participating in business and energy policy formulation are analysed in<BR>
the national case study. The diversity of interest from commercial<BR>
competitiveness to new behaviour in the opening Nordic energy market and<BR>
to the necessities of environmental concerns are analysed.<BR>
<BR>
The focus of the article is on the environmental policy questions<BR>
related to the ecological tax reform discussion in EU, and the authors<BR>
claim that the experience of Nordic countries may offer relevant<BR>
examples to these questions in European Union.<BR>
<BR>
