<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: van Klinken abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Energy from a Thorium cycle; aspects of importance to Society</H3>
J. van Klinken<BR>
KVI-Universiteit Groningen<BR>
Zernikelaan 25, 9747 AA Groningen, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 50 363 3558, FAX: +31 50 363 4003,<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:vKlinken@kvi.nl">vKlinken@kvi.nl </A><BR>
<BR>
In last years a new concept which may lead towards an alternative way of<BR>
energy production is drawing much attention. It is the Fast Energy<BR>
Amplifier at present strongly promoted by C.&uuml;Rubbia, Nobel-laureate
and<BR>
former director of CERN. In concept this FEA is a subcritical lead-cooled<BR>
reactor fueled with the element Thorium and no more with Uranium-235). The<BR>
technological challenge is in the requirement that the FEA has to be<BR>
driven by a future high-power proton accelerator. The use of Thorium as<BR>
breeding fuel has considerable advantages in comparison with Uranium. An<BR>
early CERN publication listed as major advantages: 
<UL>
  <LI>The FEA prevents risks of criticality and excludes a Chernobyl-type
catastrophe. 
  <LI>The FEA generates almost zero long-lived transuranic waste. 
  <LI>The element Thorium is more abundant than the isotope U-235 by a factor
<BR>
larger than 200. 
  <LI>The risk of nuclear proliferation is negligible. 
</UL>
Points 1-3 are in essence true. They do raise the FEA to a <BR>
level of unexpected importance, the more since there are a number of <BR>
additional attractive features when FEAs prove to be realistic, <BR>
like: they restrict energy plants to a modest human size; they may be more
feasible to make<BR>
than the elusive fusion reactors; they remove all need for U-235<BR>
enrichment plants; they allow a world-wide prohibition of weapon-grade U-235
and<BR>
Pu-239.<BR>
<BR>
Unfortunately point 4 is mistaken when taken at face value, since the FEA<BR>
transmutes the natural Th-fuel into fissile U-233. However, <BR>
the most important implication of this fourth point may be approached <BR>
by insisting that the FEA should be constructed as closed systems and by
banning <BR>
U-233 recovery from fuel-waste under effective world-wide control enforcement.<BR>
It is important to remark that the long-term FEA concept leaves the world<BR>
community at least one or two decades to establish adequate regulation to<BR>
effect this banning. It is time to start with this task so that not once<BR>
more technology is confronting ethics and legislation for a fait accompli.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../posterabstracts.html#anchor14200872">poster
abstracts page</A>.<BR>
