<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Karlsson &amp; Banacu abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Life-Cycle Thinking (LCT), a framework for sustainable industrial development:
Producer responsibility in societal communication and environmental adaptation</H3>
<BR>
Reine Karlsson<BR>
Chalmers University of Technology, G&ouml;teborg<BR>
School of Technology Management and Economics<BR>
41296, G&ouml;teborg, Sverige<BR>
FAX: +46 31 772 2497, E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:reinek@mot.chalmers.se">reinek@mot.chalmers.se</A><BR>
<BR>
Cristian Silviu Banacu<BR>
Technical University of Civil Engineering of Bucharest<BR>
Construction Machinery Faculty<BR>
41280, Bucharest, Romania<BR>
FAX: + 40 1 312 7780<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Goal-visions like Sustainable Development (Brundtland Report, 1987) and<BR>
Eco-cycle Society (Swedish Government, 1992), are widely used and commonly<BR>
accepted today.<BR>
<BR>
There are also industrial tools like LCA (Life-Cycle<BR>
Assessment), LCC (Life-Cycle Costing) and Cost Benefit Analysis<BR>
(CBA) that share the same overarching intention. This thinking<BR>
is also evolving, for example, among politicians, researchers, media and<BR>
general public. Still, the communication around this subject is often<BR>
mixed-up and let too much room for misunderstandings around the<BR>
life-cycle concept.<BR>
<BR>
The Life Cycle Thinking (LCT), as a unifying concept, could be<BR>
useful to establish a common frame of reference; that may facilitate the<BR>
industries' communication with other societal actors. The companies have<BR>
a growing responsibility for the future effects of their activities,<BR>
processes and products. In a growing number of countries, e.g. Sweden,<BR>
companies are required to make Environmental Impact Assessments (&auml;&Ouml;small<BR>
EIA). The &quot;polluters pay&quot; principle, make the companies aware
of their<BR>
producer responsibility, and that their economical future, or even<BR>
survival, is uncertain. The companies should consider the likely risk<BR>
of considerable price rise on scarce raw materials and energy.<BR>
Furthermore, dramatic effects of consumer reactions to media<BR>
information, and about environmental problems, could bring the polluting<BR>
companies into difficult market positions. This has particular<BR>
importance in decision making regarding investments for long term<BR>
profitability. The paper describes, how a strategic LCT<BR>
position may provide the companies with a better basis for<BR>
multi-disciplinary assessments and communications concerning the five<BR>
dimensions of Sustainability: Political, Economical, Ecological,<BR>
Technological and Social.<BR>
<BR>
The key issue is to communicate how future resources are dependent on<BR>
present activities, as a spiral type model of evolution, that visualises
a<BR>
common foundation in the general relation between continuity and change,<BR>
toward a sustainable society.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../posterabstracts.html#anchor14200872">poster
abstracts page</A>.<BR>
