<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Jarzabek abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Small water reservoirs serving for water quality improvement</H3>
Adam Jarzabek<BR>
Institute of Engineering and Water Management, Cracow University<BR>
of Technology<BR>
ul. Warszawska 24, 31-155 Krakow, Polska<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:btwarog@lajkonik.wis.pk.edu.pl">btwarog@lajkonik.wis.pk.edu.pl</A>
<BR>
<BR>
Introduction.<BR>
<BR>
 The necessity of nutrient media flows reduction is one of the<BR>
most important and ecologically proved problem. Using small water reservoirs<BR>
could be considered as one of methods that could be practically used for
this<BR>
purpose. At the Cracow University of Technology there were carried out,
in the<BR>
period 1981-1991, some investigations of usability of small reservoirs for<BR>
reduction of nutrient media.<BR>
<BR>
Object under investigation.<BR>
<BR>
 The investigations were carried out on singleobjects represented by small
<BR>
reservoirs in Biertowice, Czechowka and<BR>
Siepraw. A system of reservoirs working in series was represented by small<BR>
ponds in Polanka. In Trzyciaz four reservoirs working in series took<BR>
successively water from the Dubnia River. The investigations on the Biertowice<BR>
reservoir were carried out as to compare its reduction ability for two water<BR>
stream configurations: natural and specially directed for making use of
the<BR>
whole reservoir capacity. <BR>
<BR>
Results. <BR>
<BR>
All the investigated reservoirs were highly trophic and intensity of<BR>
this phenomenon is related to the concentration of nutrient media. Reduction<BR>
of nutrient media in reservoirs were observed from April to the half of<BR>
November, and is caused by their accumulation in developed biomass and<BR>
sorption in bottom sediments. The system of reservoirs in Polanka showed<BR>
effective reduction of the concentration of nitrate and phosphate compounds.<BR>
Four pounds working in Trzyciaz was the most effective system reducing<BR>
nutrient media. Reduction of the concentration for the whole system was:<BR>
phosphate ions - 75,1%, ammonia - 58,3%, nitrate nitrogen - 25,8%. <BR>
<BR>
Such satisfying results were achieved also for directed labyrinthian water<BR>
flow through the Biertowice reservoir. <BR>
<BR>
Conclusions. <BR>
<BR>
The small, shallow and highly eutrophicated reservoirs are able to<BR>
reduce nitrient media outflow in vegetative periods. Reduction effects depend<BR>
mainly on the time of keeping water stream in a reservoir. The suggested<BR>
solution in Biertowice pound consisting in labyrinthian flow of water stream<BR>
through reservoir of o given average depth ensures efficient reduction of<BR>
nutrient media and can be recommended for projects. It seems to be reasonable<BR>
that projects consisting with several reservoirs working in series could
be<BR>
also recommended. This was proved by the system in Trzyciaz where suspended<BR>
matter was almost entirely cumulated in two first reservoirs which created<BR>
good conditions for nutrient media reduction in the next reservoirs. The<BR>
reservoirs quickly undergo silting-up, overgrow with macrophytes and in
case<BR>
of intensive pollution inflow and bad water circulation sediments decay
can be<BR>
observed. This can be sediments and macrophytes removal at least once a
year<BR>
in winter. In Poland such reservoirs can be applied in urban areas, in areas<BR>
without sewerage systems as well as in catchments of agricultural character<BR>
where strong erosion is observed during snow melting periods as well as
during<BR>
intensive rainfalls. Biomass amount in a reservoir can be controlled by
taking<BR>
water from a micro-reservoir for irrigation. This causes water and nutrient<BR>
media work together in a sort of closed cycle (water races - reservoir -<BR>
arable land  drain - water races). Arable land with plants and ground filter<BR>
will be working as the following eliminators of nutrient media. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../posterabstracts.html">poster abstracts page</A>.<BR>
