<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Kliucininkas &amp; Kliucininkas abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>GIS based planning of protected areas development in South West Lithuania</H3>
Linas Kliucininkas<BR>
Associate Professor, Department for Environmental Engineering<BR>
Algirdas Kliucininkas<BR>
Professor, Department of Human Safety<BR>
Kaunas University of Technology<BR>
Radvilenu 19, 3028 Kaunas, Lithuania<BR>
TEL: +370 7 751 016, FAX: +370 7 756 366,<BR>
E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:Linas.Kliucininkas@ct.ktu.lt">Linas.Kliucininkas@ct.ktu.lt</A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Protected areas in Lithuania are established with a view to preserve all
<BR>
aspects of the landscape and its individual components as well as <BR>
biological diversity. At present protected areas cover 6&Ouml;% of the <BR>
total country's territory. The further formation of a network of <BR>
protected areas will occur according to the Lithuanian Natural Framework
<BR>
Concept - a system of natural balances to an environment disturbed and <BR>
cultivated by man. According to the concept,  protected areas would make
<BR>
up 10% of the country's territory.<BR>
<BR>
The study being conducted was to foresight strategy for sustainable <BR>
development of protected areas  in south west part of Lithuania. The <BR>
study area is covered by Sesupe  river watershed (6105 km2) and makes up
<BR>
a region with the similar environmental conditions and infrastructure. <BR>
The region comprises 3 administrative counties with 5797 ha of protected
<BR>
areas, which make up 1.3% of the total region's area.<BR>
The use of natural resources and landscape planning were based on the <BR>
short/mid  term as well as the long term perspectives. The aim of the <BR>
study was to make a zoning maps which will indicate wildlife areas to be
<BR>
protected, while at the same time will estimate industry, infrastructure
<BR>
as well as agriculture development perspectives. Since land can be <BR>
allocated to only one of these uses at any one time, the objectives must
<BR>
be viewed as conflicting - i.e., they may potentially compete for the <BR>
same land.<BR>
<BR>
Geographic Information Systems (GIS) were applied for decision support <BR>
procedure. IDRISI  for Windows 1.0 - a grid-based geographic information
<BR>
and image processing system was employed to develop different scenarios.
<BR>
The choice between alternatives was made on multi-objective  and <BR>
multi-criterion  basis.  A set of suitability maps, each derived in the
<BR>
context of a specific objective, serve as the factors for a new <BR>
evaluation in which the objectives are themselves weighted and combined
<BR>
by linear summation.<BR>
<BR>
With conflicting objectives, one possible solution lies with a <BR>
prioritization of objectives. However, the instance where a prioritised
<BR>
solution makes sense are rare. More often a compromise solution is <BR>
required.<BR>
<BR>
As a result, a solution to the problem of multi-objective land <BR>
allocation under conditions of conflicting objectives are the <BR>
suitability maps to be thought of as axis in a multi-dimensional space.
<BR>
Every raster cell in the image can be located within this decision space
<BR>
according to its suitability level on each of the objectives. To resolve
<BR>
these areas of conflict, a simple partitioning of the affected cells is
<BR>
used. The process of resolving conflicts and lowering the decision lines
<BR>
is iteratively repeated until the exact area targets are achieved.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
