<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: de Bruin et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Sustainability Assessment for Production systems, SAP</H3>
L. de Bruin, J.P.R. Meijer and M.J. Knapen<BR>
 <BR>
Department of Environmental Studies, University of Nijmegen<BR>
Toernooiveld 1, 6525 ED Nijmegen, Nederland<BR>
TEL: +31 24 365 5393, FAX: +31 24 355 3450<BR>
 E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:sustdvlm@sci.kun.nl">sustdvlm@sci.kun.nl</A><BR>
<BR>
 <BR>
To reach a sustainable society it is necessary to measure the sustainability<BR>
of various activities. In this poster we present a method to determine the<BR>
sustainability of one kind of activity, a production system. Indicators
are<BR>
used for the determination of sustainability. For several environmental<BR>
problems indicators are developed derived from the themes of the Dutch<BR>
National Environmental Policy Plan. The deduction of the indicators is<BR>
uniform and quantitative: by comparing the environmental impact with the<BR>
sustainable level per theme the distance to the sustainable level is<BR>
assessed. A production system is defined as a chain of activities from<BR>
extraction of resources to waste-treatment which is a part of the economic<BR>
system that produces a specific product. To assess sustainability, the<BR>
geographically (world-wide) spread production system is subdivided into<BR>
production units which are geographically localized. Per location the<BR>
sustainable levels are determined. The main advantage by doing so, is that<BR>
the locally derived sustainability levels are used to assess the<BR>
sustainability of the geographically spread production system. A case study<BR>
is performed for a paper production unit to evaluate the method. <BR>
<BR>
The method is described in six steps:<BR>
<BR>
&#183;determining demands implicated by sustainable development<BR>
demands in terms of input = output and inter- and intragenerational<BR>
equity environmental quality, environmental carrying capacity.<BR>
<BR>
&#183;definition of the system and system boundaries<BR>
several boundaries have to be chosen: the production system boundaries,<BR>
its relations to other systems, its relations to the environment, the<BR>
time-horizon.<BR>
<BR>
&#183;assessing the environmental impact for relevant theme's<BR>
data research in cooperation with the producer. The environmental<BR>
impacts are aggregated to the level of themes by a classification with is<BR>
comparable to the LifeCycleAssessment classification.<BR>
<BR>
&#183;assessing (local) sustainable environmental impact levels<BR>
the sustainable impacts of environmental problems are derived on<BR>
different geographic levels. For example the greenhouse effect is considered<BR>
as a global problem, the acidification of the environment will be approached<BR>
as a national or continental problem. To transform these levels to local<BR>
levels some kind of allocation is needed. Therefore the Netherlands are<BR>
considered homogeneous. Other themes are already on a local level, for<BR>
example odour and noise annoyance.<BR>
<BR>
&#183;presentation of the indicator scores in a radar graph<BR>
the radar-graph presentation clearly presents the distance between the<BR>
sustainable level and the additional level per theme per production unit.<BR>
Further aggregation can be achieved by  summation of the effect scores from<BR>
different production units combined to one production system.<BR>
<BR>
&#183;interpretation and use<BR>
the results can be used to give priority to themespecific reduction for<BR>
producers as wel as for politicians.<BR>
<BR>
The method, as far as it is operationalized, describes only the<BR>
environmental sustainability. The remaining two components of<BR>
sustainability, social and economic, are not yet worked out but can be<BR>
integrated in the method.<BR>
<BR>
In the poster presentation we will focus on step 4.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../posterabstracts.html#anchor20631581">poster
abstracts page</A>.<BR>
