<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Tian et al. abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Models for landscape dynamics and their application</H3>
Tian Xiang Yue, et al.<BR>
Umweltforschungszentrum Leipzig-Halle UFZ,<BR>
(Research Center for Environment)<BR>
P.O. Box 2, 04301 Leipzig, Deutschland<BR>
TEL: +49 341 235 2437, FAX: +49 341 235 2511<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Since the early 1970's, W. Haber's Continuous studies upon spatial <BR>
diversity of land use has created DLU strategy. Since<BR>
the late 1970's, owing to yhe continuous efforts mainly from<BR>
B.B.&uuml;Mandelbrot, the theoretical system of fractal geometry has been<BR>
developed. According to the Haber's DLU strategy, the<BR>
models for landscape dynamics are constructed by means of fractal<BR>
geometry. In their case studies of experimental zones that are <BR>
separately located in Europe and Asia, several major issues of<BR>
landscape changes are analyzed. They are:
<UL>
  <LI>Spatial dynamics,
  <LI>Temporal dynamics,
  <LI>Driving forces of the landscape changes,
  <LI>Their effects on economic efficiency and ecological environment.
</UL>
<BR>
