<DOCNO>WT13-B39-282</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA049-000856-B025-51</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.frt.fy.chalmers.se:80/amst/posters/hammond.html 129.16.119.200 19970210102538 text/html 5541
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: WebSTAR/2.0 ID/33439
Message-ID: <af244e57.307@g7-mac5.fy.chalmers.se>
Date: Monday, 10-Feb-97 10:25:45 GMT
Last-Modified: Friday, 13-Sep-96 14:38:55 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 5290
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Hammond abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<H3>Alternative energy strategies for the United Kingdom revisited: Market
competition and sustainability</H3>
Geoffrey P. Hammond <BR>
School of Mechanical Engineering<BR>
University of Bath<BR>
Claverton Down, Bath BA2 7AY, United Kingdom<BR>
TEL: + 44 1225 826 168, FAX: + 44 1225 826 928,<BR>
 E-MAIL: <A HREF="mailto:g.p.hammond@bath.ac.uk">g.p.hammond@bath.ac.uk
 </A><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
In the late 1970s a research team fromthe International Institute for<BR>
Environment and Development (IIED) led by Gerald Leach examined  UK energy
<BR>
demand up to the year 2025  (Leach et al., &quot;A Low Energy Strategy for
the <BR>
United Kingdom,&quot; Science Reviews/IIED , 1979). <BR>
They adopted what was then a novel approach to energy demand forecasting,
using<BR>
physical models rather than traditional econometric extrapolations.  End-use<BR>
energy requirements were broken down within all sections of the <BR>
UK economy, and the IIED  team demonstrated how <BR>
large savings could be made by the widespread<BR>
adoption of feasible energy conserving technologies.  This led them to suggest<BR>
that the consumption of primary fuels by the year 2025 would remain at<BR>
approximately the same level as in 1976.  A key reason for this low energy<BR>
demand was the belief by the IIED team that &quot;saturation&quot; effects
in the<BR>
ownership of various appliances would limit electricity consumption to almost<BR>
zero growth over the period 1976-2025.  This implies a much reduced need
for<BR>
electricity generating capacity, both fossil fuel and nuclear power stations,<BR>
over this time frame. <BR>
<BR>
 These findings were very influential in stimulating<BR>
debate on alternative energy policy options and the potential for energy<BR>
conservation far beyond the United Kingdom (see, for example, Stobauch &Ouml;&amp;<BR>
Yergin (Editors), &quot;Energy Future,&quot; Vintage books, New York, Third
Edition,<BR>
1983). The Leach report was not without its detractors.  In the UK the Atomic<BR>
Energy Authority prepared a detailed response which acknowledged <BR>
the IIED team's contribution in stimulating the adoption of energy saving
measures, but<BR>
was critical of many of the assumptions made (Day et al., &quot;An analysis
of the<BR>
low energy strategy for the United Kingdom,&quot; UKAEA <BR>
Energy Discussion Paper No. 1, 1980).  <BR>
<BR>
The authors of the UKAEA study argued that the trend towards higher<BR>
quality fuels, in particular, would ensure a greater market share for<BR>
electricity than that suggested by the IIED team.  It is now nearly two
decades <BR>
since the baseline year adopted for the projection in the Leach report (1976).
<BR>
During the intervening time the UK has had the longest period of continuous<BR>
Conservative Party Government since the Second World War.  This government,<BR>
despite a change in leadership, has been consistent in its efforts to privatise<BR>
the hitherto publicly-owned energy utilities and introduce competition into
the<BR>
market.  The resulting structural changes have been so fundamental as to
make<BR>
it unlikely  that any future government would significantly alter the<BR>
competitive framework of the energy market.  <BR>
<BR>
In parallel with these UK developments there has been great concern on a
<BR>
global scale with the notion of<BR>
sustainability; balancing economic and social development while protecting
the<BR>
environment.  The present contribution reviews the IIED energy demand<BR>
projections in the context of both increased market competition and the
need to<BR>
achieve sustainable development.  Although UK  energy demand overall in
1995<BR>
was much in line with that suggested by the Leach report, a detailed<BR>
examination of the structure of demand and of the supply sector shows<BR>
significant differences from that forecast by the IIED team. The potential<BR>
conflict between energy market competition and the requirements of sustainable<BR>
development is of much wider significance than just the UK. <BR>
Regional groupings of industrialised countries, such as the European Union
and <BR>
NAFTA, are also trying  to resolve these conflicting goals.<BR>
<BR>
The present contribution drawslessons for future long-term energy forecasting
<BR>
exercises, while identifying constraints imposed on environmental protection
<BR>
and sustainable development by competitive energy markets. The research
to be <BR>
reported forms part of a study supported by a research grant from the UK
<BR>
Engineering and  Physical Sciences Research Council, under its &quot;Sustainable
Cities&quot; <BR>
Managed Programme, entitled &quot;Monitoring the City&quot; (GR/J92910,
 awarded jointly <BR>
with Dr A.K. Day of the School of Architecture and Civil Engineering and
<BR>
Dr A. Lewis of the School of Social Sciences). <BR>
