<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Ezekwe abstract</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>Abstract</H2>
<STRONG>THE IMPORTANCE OF SCIENCE AND ENGINEERING INFRASTRUCTURE FOR THE
SUSTAINABLE ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT OF SUB-SAHARAN AFRICAN COUNTRIES</STRONG><BR>
<BR>
BY PROF. G.O. EZEKWE (NIGERIA) <BR>
<BR>
A sustainable nature-friendly management of the earth's resources is a<BR>
challenge that now faces all nations, both the developed and the<BR>
developing, as the effects of activities which damage the earth and its<BR>
atmosphere go beyond national boundaries. The advanced countries of the<BR>
North owe that status to their phenomenal mastery of science,<BR>
engineering and technology, and the application of these powers to<BR>
prolific production activities in agriculture, industry and commerce,<BR>
and to the taming of the harsh aspects of life on earth, including the<BR>
diseases of man, animals and plants. They have therefore achieved highly<BR>
productive, affluent and self-reliant national economies, and the<BR>
scientific and technological skills required to solve physical problems<BR>
of diverse kinds. Their obligation in the global sustainable development<BR>
crusade is therefore the application of scientific methods and<BR>
technology to the moderation, containment, and elimination of the<BR>
production processes, practices and products that are nature-hostile,<BR>
and the facilitation of the adoption of such safe technologies by other<BR>
nations. They are well placed to play this leadership role because they<BR>
possess the financial and material resources and the know- how and the<BR>
technology, all of which are pre-requisites for an effective<BR>
confrontation of the menace.<BR>
<BR>
In contrast, Sub-Saharan African countries are yet poverty-ridden,<BR>
debt-burdened, and threatened by population explosion, all these with<BR>
their attendant adverse effects on the environment. The sub-region is<BR>
therefore in dire need of a science and technology capacity which is the<BR>
only means by which it can arrest the decline and reverse its fortunes.<BR>
Towards the attainment of this goal, the sub-region has made<BR>
considerable investment in scientific and technical manpower development<BR>
for some forty years, an important programme which has also benefitted<BR>
immensely from multi-lateral and by- lateral competition. But is<BR>
ironical that many of the high-level manpower out-put of the programme<BR>
now reside in the industrialized countries, to the chagrin of their own<BR>
countries which need them more.<BR>
<BR>
The phenomenon of brain drain is traceable to the same cause that is<BR>
responsible for those countries' low achievement in science and<BR>
technology development, their lack of a sustainable industrialisation,<BR>
their poverty, and their incapacity in effectively tackling<BR>
environmental problems. This root cause of the sub-region's woes is its<BR>
concentration of effort in consumer products industries, to the neglect<BR>
of capital goods industries. Because of this, there are no local sources<BR>
for equipment, machinery, and tools, whether they are required for<BR>
agriculture, industry, education, health care, utilities supply,<BR>
housing, transportation, communication, or whatever. The sub-region<BR>
therefore depends almost completely on import for its capital equipment<BR>
needs. In the present situation in which these countries are steeped in<BR>
foreign debts to the extent that debt-servicing alone consumes a large<BR>
part of their foreign earnings, not much capital goods importation can<BR>
be accomplished.<BR>
<BR>
Obviously, since a productive and sustainable development is not<BR>
possible in the absence of readily available and affordable capital<BR>
equipment, Sub-Saharan African countries must launch into the<BR>
establishment of science and engineering infrastructures, which they<BR>
require for the local mass-production of such equipment and materials.<BR>
This is the subject with which this presentation is concerned.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>Go back to the <A HREF="../ws23Bindsus.html#anchor5105018">workshop
2.3B</A> page.<BR>
