</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>INES Workshop: Mukendi abstract (english translation)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<B>Sustainable development and education: an African view<BR>
</B><BR>
The African continent presents, at the end of the century, a picture of<BR>
poverty and social-economic maladjustment which requires a tremendous<BR>
effort of development. In addition we realize that the programs for<BR>
development initiated since the sixties have not achieved the desired<BR>
results.<BR>
<BR>
Beyond doubt, one of the reasons for this failure is that the present<BR>
model of development is maladapted to the socio-cultural structure of<BR>
African societies, and as a consequence, the local populations have<BR>
difficulty carrying out these programs and adapting to the cultural<BR>
demands which they presuppose: organization of labour, rational<BR>
division of time, etc.<BR>
<BR>
This situation brings with it a new consciousness with respect to the<BR>
place of education in the realization of sustainable development. A<BR>
particular model, arising in a given social and cultural context, cannot<BR>
succeed without a first phase in which the concepts, the kinds of<BR>
behaviour and the practices which it presupposes, are learned. The<BR>
culture of Africa contains certain elements which appear to be<BR>
refractory to the demands of development. A suitable education is the<BR>
only way to ensure a harmonious confrontation between these elements and<BR>
the demands of development.<BR>
<BR>
On the other hand, in the present evolution of events, marked by<BR>
numerous serious ethnic conflicts, education for development is<BR>
integrally bound with education for citizenship.<BR>
This paper has the following central issues:<BR>
<BR>
Development and African culture: This part sheds light on the difference<BR>
between, on the one hand, African cultures, and on the other, the<BR>
Western culture which gave rise to modernity. It traces the geneology of<BR>
Western development based on a secular vision of nature, on<BR>
techno-science, and on an economic ideology characterised by<BR>
individualism, and confronts this vision with the holistic African<BR>
societies impregnated with a magical and spiritualistic view of nature<BR>
in which the economy is still buried within the society as a whole.<BR>
<BR>
The issues of education for development.<BR>
<BR>
Theoretical issues: These concern development as an intercultural<BR>
challenge, free from socio-cultural particularities on the one hand and<BR>
from universal (or possibly universal) values on the other. This<BR>
representation is important because it permits the population concerned<BR>
to embrace development not only as an ideal for which to strive, but<BR>
which can be reached.<BR>
<BR>
Practical issues: These concern the education of the actors in<BR>
development: business men, cadres, rural leaders, skilled workers. The<BR>
goal of introducing new concepts and new behaviour: reactions and<BR>
techniques to control the economic domain, the conception that<BR>
development is the concern of all and the concern of each one, a<BR>
projection into space and time, and the organization of labour.<BR>
Development for citizenship: Development cannot be separated from<BR>
democracy, understood as pluralism and liberty. In short, it requires a<BR>
state bound to a regime of law.<BR>
<BR>
Education for development implies education for citizenship, i.e. to<BR>
teach the population its rights and its duties, to encourage mechanisms<BR>
of participation in social life and to stimulate free expression and<BR>
creativity in all domains.<BR>
<BR>
In conclusion the contents of a program for development will be<BR>
sketched, with the broad lines of an appropriate pedagogy and the role<BR>
of civil society.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
Go back to the <A HREF="../../mukendi.html">French original</A>.<BR>
<BR>
