*<BR>*   *</P>
<A NAME="Sec6"></A><P>RINDERPEST IN SENEGAL<BR>The Delegate declares the country 'provisionally free'</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
<EM>
Translation of a fax received on 8 January 1997 from Dr A.B. Niang, Director of Animal Production, Ministry of Agriculture, Dakar:</P>
<P></EM>
Since 1962, rinderpest has been a notifiable disease in Senegal and vaccination has been compulsory. Mass vaccination carried out under joint programme No. 15 (PC15) allowed the disease to be controlled.</P>
<P>The last outbreak of rinderpest in Senegalese animals was recorded in 1968. A stamping-out policy was applied to prevent any spread of the outbreak.</P>
<P>In 1978, an outbreak was recorded in northern Senegal in transhumant animals from a neighbouring country.</P>
<P>In 1991, a serological surveillance survey was carried out within the framework of the Pan African Rinderpest Campaign (PARC) to assess the effectiveness of rinderpest vaccination campaigns. The results of this survey showed that animals aged three years and over had a level of immunity ranging from 80 to 91% and that animals aged less than three years had a low level of immunity (37 to 73%). The 1992 survey showed similar results.</P>
<P>On the basis of these results, a new vaccination strategy, spread over four years, was set up in 1993. This strategy is as follows:</P>
<P>Year 1 (1994)	Mass vaccination, irrespective of age, in those regions where the results of serological surveillance were found to be insufficient, in order to consolidate the level of immunity. In the remaining regions, only cattle aged under three years were vaccinated.</P>
<P>Year 2 (1995)	Vaccination in those zones of the national territory where the results of serological surveillance conducted in 1994 demonstrated a low level of immunity, and vaccination of subjects aged under three years in the remainder of the territory.</P>
<P>Year 3 (1996)	Vaccination of bovines aged under three years throughout the national territory. Aserological surveillance survey was carried out after each vaccination campaign.</P>
<P>Year 4 (1997)	Halting of vaccination against rinderpest throughout the national territory; epidemiological surveillance of the disease.</P>
<P>Since October 1996, Senegal has stopped vaccinating against rinderpest. All rinderpest vaccine has been withdrawn from veterinary services in the field and stored at the National Livestock Production and Veterinary Research Laboratory in Dakar.</P>
<P>A rinderpest epidemiological system has been set up based on a central epidemiological unit and, in the field, all the staff involved in livestock production coordinated around a network of six regional laboratories.</P>
<P>The epidemiological unit is made up of veterinarians from the Directorate of Livestock Production and research veterinarians, and is responsible for periodically carrying out epidemiological surveys in the field.</P>
<P>With regard to provisions for clinical surveillance, 23 field survey points covering the entire territory have been selected. Their staff have been trained to recognise clinical signs of rinderpest.</P>
<P>The use of rinderpest vaccine for the vaccination of sheep and goats against peste des petits ruminants has been suspended.</P>
<P>In view of the above, Senegal declares 'provisional freedom from rinderpest'.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
<A NAME="Sec7"></A><P>RINDERPEST IN C&Ocirc;TE D'IVOIRE<BR>The Delegate declares the country 'provisionally free'</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
<EM>
Translation of a communication received on 8 January 1997 from Dr P. Ackah Angniman, Delegate of C&ocirc;te d'Ivoire to the OIE:</P>
<P></EM>
C&ocirc;ted'Ivoire, having observed no cases of rinderpest since 1986, declares 'provisional freedom from rinderpest', in accordance with the recommended standards for epidemiological surveillance for this disease.</P>
<P>Since 1986, C&ocirc;te d'Ivoire has practised a policy of prevention based on the following:</P>
<P>	annual vaccination of animals;</P>
<P>	annual post-vaccinal serological tests based on random sampling;</P>
<P>	systematic vaccination of imported animals;</P>
<P>	surveillance over the national territory and at borders, which allows any suspected cases of contagious diseases to be systematically reported.</P>
<P>Surveillance of the territory is currently carried out by staff of the external services of the Ministry of Agriculture and Animal Resources and by veterinarians in private practice in rural areas.</P>
<P>Any cases of contagious diseases are reported to the Regional Directorate of Agriculture and Animal Resources via the local Departmental Directorate. The information is then passed to the Directorate of Veterinary Services, which makes any necessary declaration to the OIE.</P>
<P>In view of the stability of the situation in regard to rinderpest and the presence of a surveillance system to detect any outbreaks, C&ocirc;te d'Ivoire decided to halt rinderpest vaccination with effect from 1996, while retaining the capacity to act immediately in the event of any recurrence of the disease.</P>
</BODY>
