<P><STRONG>
<A NAME="Sec1"></A>FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN KUWAIT</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A10_02.HTM#Sec1"> 10 January 1997; Vol. 10 - No. 2</A>, <A HREF="A09_44.HTM#Sec5"> 15 November 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 44</A><P><EM>
Text of a fax received on 22 December 1996 from Dr Sultan A.S. Khalaf, Deputy Director General, The Public Authority for Agriculture Affairs and Fish Resources (PAAF), Safat:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 2  No. 1</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of previous report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
5 November 1996 (see <EM>
Disease Information</EM>
, <STRONG>
9 </STRONG>
[44], 171).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of this report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
1 December 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Number of separate outbreaks identified so far: </STRONG>
</EM>
two (2) farms.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Geographical identification of the outbreaks: </STRONG>
</EM>
Sulaibiya.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Latest details concerning the outbreaks:</P>
<CENTER></STRONG></EM><TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>No.
<TD>Species
<TD>No. of animals<BR>in the outbreaks
<TD>No. of<BR>cases
<TD>No. of<BR>deaths
<TD>No. of animals destroyed
<TD>No. of animals slaughtered
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>1-2/96
<TD>bov
<TD>1,199
<TD>113
<TD>3
<TD>0
<TD>0
</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P>Comments concerning affected population: </STRONG>
</EM>
Friesian cattle in two intensive dairy units. Most cases were cattle imported from Northern Europe since March 1996. Two deaths were in newborn calves delivered by infected cows. </P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Diagnosis:</P>
<P>A.	Conclusions to date concerning nature of agent: </STRONG>
</EM>
virus type O, subtype O1 Manisa.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
B.	Comments concerning diagnosis: </STRONG>
</EM>
diagnosis was confirmed at the Virology Laboratory of the Animal Health Department and the OIE World Reference Laboratory for foot and mouth disease (Pirbright, United Kingdom). The virus was isolated in BHK21-C13 cell line and was identified using an ELISA kit obtained from the Pirbright Laboratory.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments to date concerning epidemiology of the disease: </STRONG>
</EM>
the source of the agent is unknown, but it is suspected to be carriers which had recovered from the previous foot and mouth disease outbreak. The mode of spread was probably by direct contact between animals, indirectly by fomites and through human movements. The cows were vaccinated against FMD.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken during report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
treatment of sick animals to alleviate inflammation and to combat secondary infection. Sanitary measures were employed.</P>
<CENTER>
