<A NAME="Sec3"></A><P>VENEZUELAN EQUINE ENCEPHALOMYELITIS IN MEXICO<BR>Suspected outbreak</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_29.HTM#Sec2"> 2 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 29</A>, <A HREF="A09_28.HTM#Sec5"> 26 July 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 28</A><P><EM>
Translation of a fax received on 2 October 1996 from Dr A.O. Flores Hern&aacute;ndez, Director General of Animal Health Department, Secretariat for Agriculture, Animal Production and Rural Development, MexicoCity:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 1</P>
<P>Officials responsible for DINESA, the animal health emergency intervention scheme in Mexico, are currently investigating cases of equine neuropathy observed in Aldama municipality (Tamaulipas State) since 21 September 1996. To date, 55 cases (of which 26 subsequently died) have been detected within a radius of 10km in 23 ranches with an estimated total population of 505 equids. Venezuelan equine encephalomyelitis is suspected.</P>
<P>The following measures have been introduced, with effect from 29 September 1996:</P>
<P>a)	Sanitary measures:</P>
<P>-	Epidemiological investigations and surveillance within the focal and perifocal region up to a radius of 40km around the outbreak.</P>
<P>-	Ban on the movement of horses from the affected municipality.</P>
<P>-	Preventive vaccination of the 505 equids present in the zone at risk, and the start of vaccination within the perifocal area, where there are approximately 5,500 equids.</P>
<P>b)	Samples for laboratory analysis: 44 serum samples have been taken from sick animals and animals having been in contact with them. Four brains and other organs have also been removed for examination.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Preliminary results:</P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
-	In all, 10 of the 29 samples analysed so far present Venezuelan equine encephalomyelitis virus antibodies, at varying titres from 1:10 to 1:640 (equids in this region have a history of vaccination).</P>
<P>-	Attempts at virus isolation are currently under way.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
