<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>30/96
<TD>second. 25
<TD>Korymvo, Evros
<TD>28 September
<TD>28 September (2)
<TD>170
</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P></STRONG>
</EM>
(1) Confirmation by serology and subsequent virus isolation.</P>
<P>(2) Confirmation by clinical examination and epidemiological linkage.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments to date concerning epidemiology of the disease:</P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
In Evros, secondary outbreaks are easily related with primary ones through direct contact, mainly due to common grazing and watering. However, epidemiological investigations in the primary outbreaks have failed to identify the origin of the disease and the exact mode of incursion.</P>
<P>Direct contact with infected animals from outside Greece can be safely ruled out because in all primary outbreaks there were neither animal movements on the premises in recent months nor animal husbandry and breeding conditions that might favour the temporary mixing of susceptible animals across the borders.</P>
<P>That leaves indirect contact, mainly through personnel movements, as the only plausible explanation for the primary outbreaks.</P>
<P>Although the epidemiology of sheep pox does not support this mode of transmission, the frequency and intensity of cross-border personnel and vehicle traffic in the area may very well increase the possibility of indirect transmission. The outbreak in Xanthi, in particular, is definitely linked with infected premises outside Greece through personnel movement.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken during report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
measures for the eradication of the disease involve a stamping-out / non vaccination policy, establishment of protection and surveillance zones around the outbreaks and strict movement control inside these zones.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
