<A NAME="Sec2"></A><P>RINDERPEST IN KENYA</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_45.HTM#Sec2"> 29 November 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 45</A>, <A HREF="A09_15.HTM#Sec2"> 26 April 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 15</A><P><EM>
Text of a fax received on 24 September 1996 from Dr R.S. Kimanzi, Director of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture, Livestock Development and Marketing, Nairobi:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 2  No. 1</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of previous report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
23 April 1996 (see <EM>
Disease Information</EM>
, <STRONG>
9 </STRONG>
[15], 46).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of this report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
17 September 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Estimated date of first infection: </STRONG>
</EM>
30 March 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Number of separate outbreaks identified so far: </STRONG>
</EM>
one (1).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Geographical identification of the outbreak: </STRONG>
</EM>
Finno area, Mandera district, North-Eastern Province (onthe border with Somalia).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Latest details concerning the outbreak:</P>
<CENTER></STRONG></EM><TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>No.
<TD>Species
<TD>No. of animals<BR>in the outbreak
<TD>No. of<BR>cases
<TD>No. of<BR>deaths
<TD>No. of animals destroyed
<TD>No. of animals slaughtered
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>1/96
<TD>bov
<TD>...
<TD>2
<TD>0
<TD>...
<TD>...
</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P>Comments concerning diagnosis: </STRONG>
</EM>
detection of virus antigens by agar-gel immunodiffusion (AGID) test at the Muguga Reference Laboratory, Kenya. However, the positive result was not corroborated by the Pirbright Reference Laboratory (United Kingdom), which obtained negative results. Attempts to isolate the virus were fruitless.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments to date concerning epidemiology of the disease: </STRONG>
</EM>
the disease has not spread to other herds in the locality or the region. Disease surveillance has been conducted in the region. However, we have been unable to establish the disease origin. Cross-border transhumance has complicated the issue. The disease epidemiology and diagnosis outcome appear to discount the presence of the disease. However, disease surveillance is continuing in search of the virus.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken to date: </STRONG>
</EM>
vaccination against the disease has been carried out in the region and it is continuing in neighbouring districts. Quarantine has been lifted.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
