<A NAME="Sec3"></A><P>NEWCASTLE DISEASE IN FINLAND<BR>Wildlife</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A10_04.HTM#Sec1"> 24 January 1997; Vol. 10 - No. 4</A>, <A HREF="A09_31.HTM#Sec1"> 16 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 31</A>, <A HREF="A09_20.HTM#Sec3"> 31 May 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 20</A>, <A HREF="A09_18.HTM#Sec6"> 17 May 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 18</A><P><EM>
Text of a fax received on 24 September 1996 from Dr Saara Reinius, Director General of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry, Helsinki:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 1</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: </STRONG>
</EM>
7 September 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Estimated date of first infection: </STRONG>
</EM>
August 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Number of separate outbreaks identified since 1 January 1996: </STRONG>
</EM>
two (2).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Geographical identification of the new outbreak:</P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
2/96.	Zoological park, Helsinki.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Details concerning the new outbreak:</P>
<CENTER></STRONG></EM><TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>No.
<TD>Species
<TD>No. of animals<BR>in the outbreak
<TD>No. of<BR>cases
<TD>No. of<BR>deaths
<TD>No. of animals destroyed
<TD>No. of animals slaughtered
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>2/96
<TD>fau
<TD>13
<TD>1
<TD>1
<TD>12
<TD>0
</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P>Comments concerning affected population: </STRONG>
</EM>
the outbreak occurred in the zoological park of Helsinki City, in an isolated unit where injured wild fauna is treated. A goosander (<EM>
Mergus merganser</EM>
) was brought into the unit on 18 August 1996 and died on 7 September 1996. The other 12 birds kept in the unit showed no clinical signs of disease. Two of them were serologically positive for paramyxovirus-1. </P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments concerning diagnosis: </STRONG>
</EM>
paramyxovirus-1 was isolated from the goosander in a virological examination on 23 September. The intracerebral pathogenicity index was 1.37. Virus isolation of the other birds in the unit is not yet completed.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments to date concerning epidemiology of the disease: </STRONG>
</EM>
no clinical signs of disease have been detected in birds in other parts of the zoological park. The probable source of infection is wild fauna though no disease outbreaks (e.g. increased mortality) have been reported in wild bird populations in Finland. </P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken to date: </P>
<P></EM>
-	</STRONG>
The zoological garden has been placed under official restrictions.</P>
<P>-	All the birds kept in the infected unit have been killed and passed to laboratory examinations.</P>
<P>-	The cleansing and disinfection measures in the unit have been completed. </P>
<P><STRONG>
-	</STRONG>
The screening (serology and cloacal swabs) of birds in other parts of the zoological park has been initiated.</P>
<P>-	Intensified sampling of wild birds will be carried out.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
<A NAME="Sec4"></A><P>OLD WORLD SCREWWORM (<EM>CHRYSOMYIA BEZZIANA</EM>) IN IRAQ</P>
