<TD>bov<BR>ovi<BR>equ<BR>avi
<TD>10,000
<TD>104
<TD>...
<TD>...
<TD>...
</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P>Comments concerning affected population: </STRONG>
</EM>
disease involved local breeds of animals owned by farmers in a few villages.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments concerning diagnosis: </STRONG>
</EM>
diagnosis was based on epidemiology and clinical findings. Laboratory confirmation*.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments to date concerning epidemiology of the disease: </STRONG>
</EM>
the manner in which the screwworm fly entered the country is not yet known.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken to date: </P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
-	Movement of animals from or into the infested area was prohibited.</P>
<P>-	All infested animals were treated and kept under daily observation.</P>
<P>-	All livestock in, or adjacent to, high risk areas was treated with insecticide to reduce the risk of infestation.</P>
<P>*	<STRONG>
Note by the OIE Central Bureau: </STRONG>
the notification of this outbreak does not indicate whether the causal fly is <EM>
Cochliomyia hominivorax </EM>
(classified in the OIE List B of diseases) or, more probably, a screwworm fly described in Africa, the Middle East or Asia, e.g. <EM>
Chrysomyia bezziana</EM>
.</P>
