</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P>Comments concerning affected population: </P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
1/96.	A small backyard flock used for egg production and direct sales from the farm. The flock consists of 9 hens and 16 chickens.</P>
<P>2/96.	An egg-producing flock comprising 25,600 hens.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments concerning diagnosis: </STRONG>
</EM>
mild clinical signs in the flocks. Virological confirmation on 23August 1996. Intracerebral pathogenicity index: 1.75 (outbreak No. 1/96) and 1.76 (outbreak No.2/96).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments to date concerning epidemiology of the disease: </STRONG>
</EM>
the epidemiology of the disease is not yet known but contact farms are under investigation.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken to date: </STRONG>
</EM>
slaughter and rendering of the entire flocks. Protection zone (3-km radius) and surveillance zone (10-km radius) established on 23 August 1996.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
<A NAME="Sec2"></A>FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN GREECE<BR>Zoning</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_32.HTM#Sec5"> 23 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 32</A>, <A HREF="A09_30.HTM#Sec7"> 9 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 30</A>, <A HREF="A09_28.HTM#Sec2"> 26 July 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 28</A>, <A HREF="A09_26.HTM#Sec1"> 12 July 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 26</A><P><EM>
Text of a fax received on 27 August 1996 from Dr D. Panagiotatos, Acting Head, Infectious Diseases Section, Directorate General of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture, Athens:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 2  No. 4</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of previous report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
20 August 1996 (see <EM>
Disease Information</EM>
, <STRONG>
9 </STRONG>
[32], 125).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of this report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
26 August 1996.</P>
<P>No new outbreaks have been reported since the previous report and the disease appears to have been brought under control.</P>
<P>The European Commission organised an on the spot visit to Evros from 12 to 17 August in order to evaluate the situation and the overall efficacy of the control and safeguard measures imposed by the Greek Authorities.</P>
<P>The Commission experts concluded that these measures comply fully with the requirements of the community legislation, have led to the disease being placed under control and guarantee that the disease will not spread outside Evros Prefecture.</P>
<P>On the basis of these favourable conclusions, the Standing Veterinary Committee of the European Union held a special meeting on 22 August and adopted a proposal for a Commission Decision repealing Commission Decision 96/440/EC, which had placed the entire territory of Greece under quarantine, and regionalising Evros.</P>
<P>This new Decision is scientifically justified and restores intra-community trade in live animals and products of animal origin coming from or through Greece, with the exception of Evros.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
