<A NAME="Sec2"></A><P>FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN ALBANIA</P>
<P>Additional information</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_22.HTM#Sec2"> 14 June 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 22</A>, <A HREF="A09_21.HTM#Sec5"> 7 June 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 21</A>, <A HREF="A09_19.HTM#Sec6"> 24 May 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 19</A><P><EM>
Extract from FAO Information Bulletin No. 3 on the foot and mouth disease situation in the Balkans (as of 3 August 1996):</P>
<P></EM>
The situation is now under control. The disease is limited to ten villages in the Kor&ccedil;a district. The 623animals clinically affected have been destroyed (463 cattle, 74 small ruminants, 86pigs). The restriction measures for animal movement and the measures for disinfection are still in force in and around the infected zone. Clinical surveillance is also being maintained in this zone. A surveillance zone has been set up around the vaccination zone and the border districts. The ring vaccination campaign around the infected villages was completed on 12 July, finishing with the infected villages. A total of 266,048 animals have been vaccinated (59,234 cattle, 137,190 sheep, 57,202 goats and 7,422 pigs) and marked by a hole in the ear. The second campaign of revaccination has started in the peripheral zones and should be completed by 15 August.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
<A NAME="Sec3"></A><P>FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA</P>
<P>Additional information</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_47.HTM#Sec3"> 13 December 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 47</A>, <A HREF="A09_25.HTM#Sec1"> 5 July 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 25</A><P><EM>
Extract from FAO Information Bulletin No. 3 on the foot and mouth disease situation in the Balkans (as of 3 August 1996):</P>
<P></EM>
The disease is under control. The last two outbreaks were notified on 18 July in two villages in the vicinity of previously infected villages. Only two regions have been infected, Titov Veles with one outbreak (village of Orizari) and Skopje with 17 outbreaks (17villages). Control of the disease has been achieved by slaughter and destruction of the cattle in infected villages, i.e. a total of 4,369cattle destroyed. Ring vaccination of cattle in these two regions has been carried out (Titov Veles: 7,500 and Skopje: 20,239). Precautionary vaccination has been decided for the animal population considered to be most at risk of infection (73,700 cattle at the border with Albania and Kosovo and 17,600 cattle in 25 large holdings). The first vaccination campaign has been completed and revaccination should start on 6 August and be completed by 15 August.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
<A NAME="Sec4"></A><P>FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN FRY (SERBIA AND MONTENEGRO)</P>
<P>Additional information</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_28.HTM#Sec3"> 26 July 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 28</A>, <A HREF="A09_26.HTM#Sec6"> 12 July 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 26</A><P><EM>
Extract from FAO Information Bulletin No. 3 on the foot and mouth disease situation in the Balkans (as of 3 August 1996):</P>
<P></EM>
One hundred and one (101) villages have been infected, corresponding to approximately one quarter of the territory of Kosovo (south). Stamping out has been applied and 4,079 animals have been destroyed (2,580 cattle, 829 sheep and goats, and 670 pigs). A three-phase programme for vaccination has been prepared for Kosovo (900,000animals).</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
