</CENTER><CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
<A NAME="Sec1"></A>INFECTIOUS BOVINE RHINOTRACHEITIS / INFECTIOUS PUSTULAR VULVOVAGINITIS IN KUWAIT</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_36.HTM#Sec4"> 20 September 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 36</A>, <A HREF="A09_32.HTM#Sec1"> 23 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 32</A>, <A HREF="A09_27.HTM#Sec3"> 19 July 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 27</A><P><EM>
Text of a fax received on 29 July 1996 from Dr Sultan A. Sultan Al Khalaf, Deputy Director General, Public Authority for Agriculture Affairs and Fish Resources (PAAF), Safat:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 2  No. 1</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of previous report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
16 July 1996 (see <EM>
Disease Information</EM>
, <STRONG>
9 </STRONG>
[27], 98).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of this report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
20 July 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Number of separate outbreaks identified so far: </STRONG>
</EM>
two (2).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Geographical identification of the new outbreak: </P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
2/96.	Sulaibiya.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Details concerning the new outbreak:</P>
<CENTER></STRONG></EM><TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>No.
<TD>Species
<TD>No. of animals<BR>in the outbreak
<TD>No. of<BR>cases
<TD>No. of<BR>deaths
<TD>No. of animals destroyed
<TD>No. of animals slaughtered
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>2/96
<TD>bov
<TD>408
<TD>18
<TD>4
<TD>0
<TD>8
</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P>Comments concerning affected population: </STRONG>
</EM>
dairy cows in an intensive unit.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Diagnosis:</P>
<P>A.	Conclusions to date concerning nature of agent: </STRONG>
</EM>
herpesvirus I, not typed.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
B.	Comments concerning diagnosis: </STRONG>
</EM>
ELISA test for IBR-IPV antibodies carried out at the Virology Laboratory of the Animal Health Department, PAAF.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments to date concerning epidemiology of the disease: </STRONG>
</EM>
it seems likely that an animal with a latent infection developed the disease after having been subjected to severe stress. The farm had imported animals from Northern Europe in April 1996. Screening for the disease and the use of ELISA for IBR-IPV may thus have revealed a preexisting disease. Mode of spread: aerosol, since animals are confined in a building where air blowers (fans) are used for cooling purposes.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken during report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
a survey of dairy farms and the introduction of a vaccination programme to control the disease are currently under preparation.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
<A NAME="Sec2"></A>VENEZUELAN EQUINE ENCEPHALOMYELITIS IN MEXICO</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_38.HTM#Sec3"> 4 October 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 38</A>, <A HREF="A09_28.HTM#Sec5"> 26 July 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 28</A><P><EM>
Translation of a fax received on 31 July 1996 from Dr A.O. Flores Hern&aacute;ndez, Director General of Animal Health Department, Secretariat for Agriculture, Animal Production and Rural Development, MexicoCity:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 2  No. 1</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of previous report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
24 July 1996 (see <EM>
Disease Information</EM>
, <STRONG>
9 </STRONG>
[28], 108).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of this report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
30 July 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Number of separate outbreaks identified so far: </STRONG>
</EM>
three (3).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Geographical identification of the outbreaks: </STRONG>
</EM>
municipalities of Mat&iacute;as Romero, Chahuites and Tepanatepec, Tehuantepec isthmus region, State of Oaxaca.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Details concerning the outbreaks:</P>
<CENTER></STRONG></EM><TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>No.
<TD>Species
<TD>No. of animals<BR>in the outbreaks
<TD>No. of<BR>cases
<TD>No. of<BR>deaths
<TD>No. of animals destroyed
<TD>No. of animals slaughtered
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>1-3/96
<TD>equ
<TD>2,500
<TD>32
<TD>10
<TD>0
<TD>0
</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P>Comments concerning affected population:  </STRONG>
</EM>
the affected equids are in low-lying rural areas liable to flooding during the rainy season. The latest case was registered on 23 July 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Conclusions to date concerning nature of agent: </STRONG>
</EM>
two virus isolates were obtained on 20 July 1996. On 29 July they were identified as belonging to subtype I variant E (I-E). This subtype is enzootic on the south west coast of Mexico and in Central America. It is maintained by a small-mammal/mosquito cycle. It may occur that equids become infected through involvement in this cycle, but morbidity and mortality remain low and epizootics do not occur.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures applied during report period: </P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
-	Strict control of the movement of equids from the three infected municipalities to the remainder of the State and from the State of Oaxaca to other States.</P>
<P>-	Active epidemiological surveillance throughout the country.</P>
<P><EM>
-	</EM>
A vaccination campaign against VEE was implemented in the three municipalities affected and in 29 other municipalities in the same region. A total of 16,700 equines have been vaccinated in the State of Oaxaca.</P>
<CENTER>
