<A NAME="Sec3"></A><P>NEWCASTLE DISEASE IN AUSTRIA<BR>End of the outbreak</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A10_02.HTM#Sec5"> 10 January 1997; Vol. 10 - No. 2</A>, <A HREF="A09_40.HTM#Sec3"> 18 October 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 40</A>, <A HREF="A09_16.HTM#Sec1"> 3 May 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 16</A>, <A HREF="A09_14.HTM#Sec3"> 19 April 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 14</A>, <A HREF="A09_10.HTM#Sec1"> 15 March 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 10</A>, <A HREF="A09_08.HTM#Sec1"> 1 March 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 8</A>, <A HREF="A09_06.HTM#Sec2"> 16 February 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 6</A>, <A HREF="A09_05.HTM#Sec1"> 9 February 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 5</A><P><EM>
Text of a fax received on 31 July 1996 from Dr P. Weber, Chief Veterinary Officer, Ministry of Health, Sports and Consumer Protection, Vienna:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 2  No. 1</P>
<P>The outbreak of Newcastle disease reported in Kottingbrunn, Baden, province of Lower Austria (see <EM>
Disease Information</EM>
, <STRONG>
9 </STRONG>
[16], 49) has been eliminated. All sanitary measures were executed in accordance with Directive 92/66/EEC. All clinical examinations were completed with negative results. All restrictions were lifted on 25 July 1996. Consequently, Austria may again be considered free from Newcastle disease.</P>
<CENTER>
