<P><STRONG>
<A NAME="Sec1"></A>RINDERPEST IN EGYPT<BR>The Delegate declares the country 'provisionally free'</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
<EM>
Text of a fax received on 20 July 1996 from Prof. Dr Ali A.M. Moussa, Chairman of General Organisation for Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture, Cairo:</P>
<P></EM>
I am pleased to inform you of the steps that have been taken to declare Egypt provisionally free from rinderpest according to OIE criteria:</P>
<P>1.	No clinical or epidemiological evidence of rinderpest has been observed since June 1986 (i.e. 10 successive years). In addition, coordinated mass animal vaccination was applied annually to all cattle from 1982 to 1995 (14 successive years) using locally manufactured 'Plowright' tissue culture rinderpest vaccine (TCRV), which meets international standards (OIE and World Health Organization). This was verified in the following manner:</P>
<P>1.1.	Passive disease surveillance through continuous presentation of animals to governorate veterinarians.</P>
<P>1.2.	Serosurveillance:</P>
<P>1.2.1.	To verify the existence of immune barriers to rinderpest among vaccinated animals of different age groups countrywide using competitive ELISA locally and abroad. The result is satisfactory.</P>
<P>1.2.2.	To verify the absence of an attenuated rinderpest virus strain among non vaccinated calves over eight months old, as well as among sheep and goats. The laboratory results using competitive ELISA proved negative.</P>
<P>1.2.3.	In 1996, a total of 5,200 ovine and caprine serum samples have been collected countrywide. The laboratory investigation using competitive ELISA proved negative for an attenuated rinderpest virus strain.</P>
<P>2.	Withdrawal of all TCRV from all governorates countrywide and storage at the Veterinary Serum and Vaccine Research Institute (VSVRI), Abbasiya, Cairo.</P>
<P>3.	Withdrawal of all rinderpest-related antigenic materials from the relevant governmental and private institutions within Egypt.</P>
<P>4.	The importation and transportation of animals and their products from rinderpest-affected areas is not allowed.</P>
<P>5.	Ministerial Decree No. 806, issued on 13 July 1996, states that:</P>
<P>-	vaccination against rinderpest is to be suspended for three successive years;</P>
<P>-	disease and serosurveillance (bovine, ovine and caprine) is to be continued for three successive years;</P>
<P>-	the VSVRI shall produce the necessary strategic amount of TCRV approved by the Chairman of the General Organisation for Veterinary Services.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
<A NAME="Sec2"></A>FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN GREECE</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_33.HTM#Sec2"> 30 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 33</A>, <A HREF="A09_32.HTM#Sec5"> 23 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 32</A>, <A HREF="A09_30.HTM#Sec7"> 9 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 30</A>, <A HREF="A09_26.HTM#Sec1"> 12 July 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 26</A><P><EM>
Text of a fax received on 22 July 1996 from Dr E. Tsaglas, Head of the Infectious Disease Section, Ministry of Agriculture, Athens:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 2  No. 1</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of previous report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
5 July 1996 (see <EM>
Disease Information</EM>
, <STRONG>
9 </STRONG>
[26], 91).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of this report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
22 July 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Number of separate outbreaks identified so far: </STRONG>
</EM>
three (3).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Geographical identification of the new outbreak: </STRONG>
</EM>
the delta area of the Evros river.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments concerning affected population: </STRONG>
</EM>
the two infected herds comprise 250 and 600 bovines respectively, while in the entire delta region 4,000 bovines, 3,000 sheep and 100 pigs are farmed extensively. </P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken during report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
the particular geographical and zootechnical conditions in the delta area dictate that, for disease control purposes, all susceptible animals must be considered as potential contacts. The delta area can be considered as an "island". The river separates it naturally from mainland Greece, and the delta has limited access by bridges which are constantly guarded by the army. In this way, all movements of animals, products, personnel and vehicules into and out of the area can be effectively controlled. Safeguard measures are observed. The prevention of the spread of the disease, either inside or outside Greece, can be guaranteed.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
