<TD>2 6
<TD>1 0
<TD>... 0
<TD>2 6
<TD>0 0
</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P>Comments to date concerning epidemiology of the disease: </STRONG>
</EM>
research conducted in regard to the origin of the disease shows that daily transportation of merchandise, including the illegal trade of cigarettes, from one country to another has resulted in mechanical transmission by horses and donkeys between the neighbouring countries and the national population. There is a possibility that the virus entered through cattle feed (hay), or through contact with herds from the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (FYROM) and Albania, which share collective grazing pastures with FRY (Serbia and Montenegro). Some citizens of FYROM still own grazing pastures in FRY (Serbia and Montenegro). There is a possibility that the virus entered through illegal trade in animals from neighbouring countries.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken during report period:</P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
Strict veterinary and sanitary measures of prophylaxis and suppression were carried out, according to the principles advised at the international level concerning foot and mouth disease.</P>
<P>A "Yugoslav / Federal / Operative Headquarters" was established to fight foot and mouth disease. It coordinates the work of operative centres in the contaminated area, as well as in the endangered area, analyses the situation and programmes the implementation of measures.</P>
<P>Around 130 veterinarians, 30 technicians from the official district services, and militia units and army members, are currently working in the contaminated area. Teams of veterinarians work in the area performing clinical examinations, in addition to teams of specialists-epizootiologists, veterinary inspectors and disinfection teams.</P>
<P>In the endangered area, a total of 120 veterinarians are working in collaboration with the teams.</P>
<P>In order to prevent the spread of the disease, trade is strictly controlled at the border and vehicles and people are disinfected.</P>
<P>The districts of Kacanik, Prizren, Vitina, Gora, trpce, Obilic and Gnjilane have been declared contaminated, and the neighbouring districts have been declared endangered areas. Inside these zones the following measures are being carried out:</P>
<P>-	stamping out in the contaminated farms, as well as in the neighbouring farms, with burying of the carcases and compensation paid to the owners (in 3 days' time);</P>
<P>-	ban on the transport of susceptible animals and their products;</P>
<P>-	ban on the transport of animal feed;</P>
<P>-	quarantine of contaminated farms, confinement of animals and restrictions on movement of people;</P>
<P>-	clinical examinations of cloven-hoofed animals in order to determine the spread of the disease;</P>
<P>-	closure of slaughterhouses where the epizootiological situation requires it;</P>
<P>-	daily disinfection and the establishment of disinfection barriers in appropriate places;</P>
<P>-	vaccination has been planned for the endangered districts, all districts in Kosovo and districts bordering Albania and FYROM.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
<A NAME="Sec4"></A><P>NEWCASTLE DISEASE IN THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA<BR>In psittacine birds</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_42.HTM#Sec4"> 31 October 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 42</A>, <A HREF="A09_35.HTM#Sec2"> 13 September 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 35</A>, <A HREF="A09_31.HTM#Sec2"> 16 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 31</A><P><EM>
