<A NAME="Sec5"></A><P>VENEZUELAN EQUINE ENCEPHALOMYELITIS IN MEXICO</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_38.HTM#Sec3"> 4 October 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 38</A>, <A HREF="A09_29.HTM#Sec2"> 2 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 29</A><P><EM>
Translation of a fax received on 25 July 1996 from Dr A.O. Flores Hern&aacute;ndez, Director General of Animal Health Department, Secretariat for Agriculture, Animal Production and Rural Development, MexicoCity:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 1</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: </STRONG>
</EM>
16 June 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Number of separate outbreaks identified so far: </STRONG>
</EM>
three (3).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Geographical identification of the outbreaks: </STRONG>
</EM>
municipalities of Mat&iacute;as Romero, Chahuites and Tepanatepec, Tehuantepec isthmus region, State of Oaxaca.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments concerning affected population: </STRONG>
</EM>
32 animals presenting clinical signs compatible with Venezuelan equine encephalomyelitis (VEE), 10 of which have died. The last case to be detected was on 14 July 1996. No cases have been observed in humans.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Diagnosis: </P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
From 16 June 1996, cases of neuropathy in equids were reported to the Federal Veterinary Services.</P>
<P>Samples from brain and other organs were taken from five equids and pre-vaccination blood samples collected from 265 animals under two years of age. The results were as follows: </P>
<P>-	<EM>
Serology: </EM>
VEE virus antibodies were detected in 70 blood samples.</P>
<P>-	<EM>
Histopathology: </EM>
lesions compatible with a viral infection were observed.</P>
<P>-	<EM>
Virology: </EM>
two isolates were obtained and were sent for characterisation to the United States National Veterinary Services Laboratories (NVSL), Ames (Iowa) on 24 July 1996. </P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments to date concerning epidemiology of the disease: </STRONG>
</EM>
the clinical picture would appear to suggests an enzootic form of mildly pathogenic VEE virus previously observed in the south-east of Mexico and in Central America.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken to date: </P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
-	<EM>
Vaccination: </EM>
the national animal health emergency committee (DINESA) implemented a preventive plan for ring vaccination against VEE in the three municipalities where cases of neuropathy had been reported and in 29 other municipalities in the same region. This vaccination campaign was completed on 18 July 1996, with 15,453 animals vaccinated.</P>
<P>-	<EM>
Epidemiological survey and surveillance: </EM>
in the infected zone and the surrounding zones: restrictions on the movement of equids from the three infected municipalities to the remainder of the state and from the State of Oaxaca to other States.</P>
<P>-	<EM>
Spraying: </EM>
the public health services have carried out spraying against mosquito vectors in urban areas within the affected municipalities; the relevant epidemiological investigations have demonstrated the absence of any human cases.</P>
<P>No new cases of VEE having been observed during the six days since completion of the vaccination plan, the situation is considered to be under control.</P>
</BODY>
