<P><STRONG>
<A NAME="Sec1"></A>RINDERPEST IN TOGO<BR>The Delegate declares the country 'provisionally free'</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
<EM>
Translation of extracts from a fax received on 12 July 1996 from Dr A.M. Denke, Director of Animal Production and Fisheries, Ministry of Rural Development and Village Water Economy, Lom&eacute;:</P>
<P></EM>
Togo is subdivided into 71 'epizootiological squares' covered by 63 veterinary posts grouped within 30 veterinary inspectorates, directed by five Regional Departments of Animal Production and Fisheries and, at the central level, a Directorate of Animal Production and Fisheries comprising three Divisions, namely the Animal Health Division, the Animal Production Division and the Fisheries Division.</P>
<P>In addition to the state-run services, a dozen private veterinarians cater for the rural clientele and are involved in the disease information procedure. Farmers are capable of identifying morbid states and some animal diseases, which they report to the relevant authorities.</P>
<P>Any case of disease which is declared or suspected at the farm level is immediately reported to the head of the inspectorate for the affected zone. The information is then passed simultaneously to the Head of the Regional Department and the Directorate of Animal Production and Fisheries, where the permanent Delegate of Togo to the OIE makes any necessary declaration to the OIE.</P>
<P>Since 1988, no further cases of rinderpest have been recorded in Togo and vaccination was halted in 1990. However, with the reappearance of contagious bovine pleuropneumonia in 1994, a mixed rinderpest / contagious bovine pleuropneumonia vaccine ('Bisec') is used for vaccination against this disease.</P>
<P>In view of the foregoing, Togo declares 'provisional freedom from rinderpest'.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
