<A NAME="Sec7"></A><P>RINDERPEST IN GUINEA<BR>The Delegate declares the country 'provisionally free'</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
<EM>
Translation of a communication received on 17 July 1996 from Dr Daouda Bangoura, Head of the Veterinary Services Division, National Directorate for Animal Production, Ministry of Agriculture, Animal Production and Forests, Conakry:</P>
<P></EM>
In accordance with the Dakar Declaration issued at the 10th Regional Meeting of the Pan African Rinderpest Campaign (PARC) for Western and Central Africa, I have the honour of informing you that the Republic of Guinea ceased mass vaccination against rinderpest in 1971 and ceased vaccination along the border with Mali and Senegal in 1994.</P>
<P>In view of the above situation, and given the absence of any rinderpest outbreaks throughout the national territory since 1967, Guinea may therefore be declared a country 'provisionally free from rinderpest'. </P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
<A NAME="Sec8"></A>AFRICAN HORSE SICKNESS IN EGYPT<BR>The Delegate declares the country 'provisionally free'</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
<EM>
Text of a fax received on 18 July 1996 from Prof. Dr Ali A.M. Moussa, Chairman of General Organisation for Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture, Cairo:</P>
<P></EM>
It is a great pleasure to inform you that Egypt declares provisional freedom from African horse sickness (AHS) since the following conditions have been fulfilled:</P>
<P>-	AHS is a compulsorily notifiable disease in Egypt;</P>
<P>-	the last outbreak was recorded in 1959;</P>
<P>-	no clinical, serological (in unvaccinated animals) or epidemiological evidence of AHS has been found since 1994;</P>
<P>-	no domestic or other equines have been vaccinated against the disease anywhere in Egypt since 1994.</P>
<P>Additionally, Ministerial Decree No. 750, issued on 1st July 1996, states that:</P>
<P>-	vaccination against AHS is to be suspended for three successive years;</P>
<P>-	disease surveillance is being continued in order to detect any subclinical cases of AHS;</P>
<P>-	serosurveillance to detect any AHS virus activity is to be continued for three successive years.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
<A NAME="Sec9"></A><P>BOVINE SPONGIFORM ENCEPHALOPATHY IN PORTUGAL</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A10_06.HTM#Sec2"> 7 February 1997; Vol. 10 - No. 6</A>, <A HREF="A10_05.HTM#Sec3"> 31 January 1997; Vol. 10 - No. 5</A>, <A HREF="A10_02.HTM#Sec3"> 10 January 1997; Vol. 10 - No. 2</A>, <A HREF="A09_44.HTM#Sec4"> 15 November 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 44</A>, <A HREF="A09_40.HTM#Sec2"> 18 October 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 40</A>, <A HREF="A09_38.HTM#Sec5"> 4 October 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 38</A>, <A HREF="A09_37.HTM#Sec1"> 27 September 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 37</A>, <A HREF="A09_36.HTM#Sec1"> 20 September 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 36</A>, <A HREF="A09_34.HTM#Sec1"> 6 September 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 34</A>, <A HREF="A09_23.HTM#Sec3"> 21 June 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 23</A>, <A HREF="A09_21.HTM#Sec7"> 7 June 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 21</A>, <A HREF="A09_20.HTM#Sec1"> 31 May 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 20</A>, <A HREF="A09_19.HTM#Sec5"> 24 May 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 19</A>, <A HREF="A09_18.HTM#Sec4"> 17 May 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 18</A>, <A HREF="A09_16.HTM#Sec3"> 3 May 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 16</A>, <A HREF="A09_06.HTM#Sec6"> 16 February 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 6</A>, <A HREF="A09_03.HTM#Sec3"> 26 January 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 3</A><P><EM>
