<P><STRONG>
<A NAME="Sec1"></A>FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN GREECE</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_33.HTM#Sec2"> 30 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 33</A>, <A HREF="A09_32.HTM#Sec5"> 23 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 32</A>, <A HREF="A09_30.HTM#Sec7"> 9 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 30</A>, <A HREF="A09_28.HTM#Sec2"> 26 July 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 28</A><P><EM>
Text of a fax received on 5 July 1996 from Dr E. Tsaglas, Head of Infectious Disease Section, Ministry of Agriculture, Athens:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 1</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Nature of diagnosis: </STRONG>
</EM>
clinical.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: </STRONG>
</EM>
3 July 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Estimated date of first infection: </STRONG>
</EM>
23 June 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Number of separate outbreaks identified so far: </STRONG>
</EM>
two (2).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Geographical identification of the outbreaks: </P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
1/96.	Dikella village, Evros prefecture, 20km south-west of Alexandroupolis</P>
<P>2/96.	Makri village, Evros prefecture, 6km east of Dikella.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Details concerning the outbreaks:</P>
<CENTER></STRONG></EM><TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>No.
<TD>Species
<TD>No. of animals in the outbreak
<TD>No. of cases
<TD>No. of deaths
<TD>No. of animals destroyed
<TD>No. of animals slaughtered
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>1/96
<TD>ovi bov sui
<TD>800 25 30
<TD>15 0 0
<TD>8 0 0
<TD>217 4 0
<TD>0 0 0
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>2/96
<TD>ovi
<TD>430
<TD>70
<TD>0
<TD>430
<TD>0
</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P>Comments concerning affected population: </STRONG>
</EM>
outbreak No.1/96: so far only one holding, consisting of 63 sheep and 2 cattle, seems to have been affected. At the time of inspection cattle did not show any clinical signs of disease.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments concerning diagnosis: </STRONG>
</EM>
pathological material was sent to the World Reference Laboratory for foot and mouth disease (Pirbright, United Kingdom) on 5 July 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments to date concerning epidemiology of the disease: </STRONG>
</EM>
the inhabitants of Dikella in general maintain frequent contacts with Turkey through movements of persons, vehicles and goods.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken to date: </STRONG>
</EM>
All the measures prescribed in Article5 of Directive 85/511/EEC were promptly implemented on 3 July 1996. The approved contingency plan has been fully implemented and zones of protection (Makri, Dikella, Mesimvria) and surveillance (Nea Khili, Atarni, Avra, Komaros, Perama, Plaka and Mesti) have been effective since 4 July. All movements of live animals and products of animal origin out of the prefecture have been suspended until further notice.</P>
<P>Outbreak No. 1/96: Although the diagnosis has not been confirmed, the local Veterinary Authorities have proceeded with the slaughter of susceptible animals in the affected holding as well as in all contact herds (preliminary epidemiological investigations have identified definite links through common grazing and watering between the index farm and three more holdings in Dikella, comprising 154 sheep and 2 cattle). The local Veterinary Authorities are considering slaughtering the entire susceptible animal population of Dikella, comprising approximately 800 sheep, 25 cattle and 30 pigs, as an extreme precaution measure.</P>
<P>Outbreak No. 2/96: Stamping out will be carried out on 5 July 1996.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
<A NAME="Sec2"></A><P>SHEEP POX IN BULGARIA</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_38.HTM#Sec1"> 4 October 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 38</A>, <A HREF="A09_33.HTM#Sec3"> 30 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 33</A>, <A HREF="A09_27.HTM#Sec5"> 19 July 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 27</A>, <A HREF="A09_01.HTM#Sec4"> 12 January 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 1</A><P><EM>
Synthesis of two faxes received on 5 July 1996 from Dr N.T. Belev, Delegate of Bulgaria to the OIE, Sofia:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 1</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: </STRONG>
</EM>
3 July 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Estimated date of first infection: </STRONG>
</EM>
28 June 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Number of separate outbreaks identified since 1 January 1996: </STRONG>
</EM>
two (2).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Geographical identification of the new outbreak: </P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
2/96.	Kapitan Andreevo village, Svilengrad district, Khaskovo region (in the south-eastern part of the country).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Details concerning the new outbreak:</P>
<CENTER></STRONG></EM><TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>No.
<TD>Species
<TD>No. of animals in the outbreak
<TD>No. of cases
<TD>No. of deaths
<TD>No. of animals destroyed
<TD>No. of animals slaughtered
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>2/96
<TD>ovi
<TD>107
<TD>28
<TD>0
<TD>107
<TD>0
</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P>Comments concerning diagnosis: </STRONG>
</EM>
clinical diagnosis was confirmed on 4 July 1996 at the Central Scientific and Research Laboratory Institute, Sofia, by agar-gel immunodiffusion and complement fixation tests.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Comments to date concerning epidemiology of the disease: </STRONG>
</EM>
the epidemiological examination established that the herd was grazed on pasture near the border with Turkey and the water source was the river Maritsa.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures taken to date: </STRONG>
</EM>
stamping out with disinfection of the buildings and land. The sheep farms in the village have been placed under quarantine. Ban on animal movements and trade in animals in Khaskovo region. Daily clinical examinations of sheep and goats in Svilengrad district are being carried out, with weekly clinical examinations in the remainder of the country.</P>
<CENTER>
