<A NAME="Sec5"></A><P>FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN ALBANIA</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A09_30.HTM#Sec2"> 9 August 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 30</A>, <A HREF="A09_22.HTM#Sec2"> 14 June 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 22</A>, <A HREF="A09_19.HTM#Sec6"> 24 May 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 19</A><P><EM>
Text of a fax received on 6 June 1996 from Dr A. Rako, Director of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture and Food, Tirana:</P>
<P></EM>
S. R. - 2  No. 1</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of previous report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
23 May 1996 (see <EM>
Disease Information</EM>
, <STRONG>
9 </STRONG>
[19], 64).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Final date of this report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
5 June 1996.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Number of separate outbreaks identified so far: </STRONG>
</EM>
eight (8).</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Geographical identification of the outbreaks: </STRONG>
</EM>
Kor&ccedil;a (Korc&euml;) prefecture, villages of Drithas, Vlogisht, Libonik, Vashtmi, Maliq, Shamolli, Kolanec, and Gurisht.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Details concerning the outbreaks:</P>
<CENTER></STRONG></EM><TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>No.
<TD>Species
<TD>No. of animals in the outbreaks
<TD>No. of cases
<TD>No. of deaths
<TD>No. of animals destroyed
<TD>No. of animals slaughtered
<TR ALIGN=CENTER><TD>1-8/96
<TD>bov o/c sui
<TD>... ... ...
<TD>395 20 67
<TD>... ... ...
<TD>142 16 33
<TD>... ... ...
</TABLE>
</CENTER><STRONG><EM><P>Control measures taken during report period: </STRONG>
</EM>
the Recommendation of the EUFMD/EC mission has been adopted as a Government Order.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
<EM>
Extracts from an Information Bulletin received on 5 June 1996 from the Secretary of the European Commission for the Control of Foot and Mouth Disease (FAO):</P>
<P><STRONG>
Primary outbreak: </P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
The first case of the disease was observed on 3 May 1996 at Drithas in the south-east in a bovine on a former State Farm located 10km north of the town of Kor&ccedil;a, seat of the Prefecture. On the farm there were 393 cattle, 200 sheep and approximately 390 pigs, belonging to some hundred families who used to work on the State Farm and still lived here.</P>
<P>On 6 May, 16 cattle were affected, and on 7 May, 48. Cattle of all ages, sheep and pigs were progressively infected. By 17 May, 81 animals were affected and by 27 May, affected animals amounted to 247 cattle, 15 sheep and 18 pigs.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Secondary outbreaks: </P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
By 1 June, the disease had spread to a total of 7 villages, clinically affecting 298 cattle, 15 sheep and 33 pigs. The villages are all situated within a zone of approximately 10km.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Origin of the outbreak:</P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
Albania recently imported considerable quantities of frozen beef and buffalo meat (some of which was unboned) from countries which are not free from foot and mouth disease. This meat was utilised essentially for processing. However, some was also sold directly, and it is most likely that the swill from this meat (including swill from unboned meat) was fed to pigs, which contracted the disease and then contaminated the cattle.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Characterisation of the isolate:</P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
The virus was isolated at the Brescia National Laboratory (Italy), and transmitted to the OIE World Reference Laboratory for foot and mouth disease (Pirbright, United Kingdom) for characterisation. This work is in progress. The first results would seem to indicate that the virus belongs to the Saudi Arabia/India complex of A22-like viruses present in India and the Middle East.</P>
<P><STRONG>
<EM>
Control measures:</P>
<P></STRONG>
</EM>
Control measures were decided on 13 May 1996. A Government Resolution was taken by the Council of Ministers, and a Decree of the Ministry of Agriculture and Food, dated 20 May 1996, defined 20 practical measures including quarantine of the infected villages, closure of markets, prohibition of transport of animals in Kor&ccedil;a and in nearby districts, destruction of sick animals with compensation to the farmers, and the setting up of a Committee for control of the disease.</P>
<P>Despite the control measures adopted, the disease continued to spread. The mission, therefore, strongly recommended reinforcement of the sanitary measures and the immediate setting up of a vaccination campaign of all susceptible animals in the District of Kor&ccedil;a and in part of the adjoining Districts of Pogradec and Devoll, covering a total of approximately 150,000 animals. The vaccine will be procured by the European Commission for the Control of Foot and Mouth Disease.</P>
<CENTER>
<P><STRONG>
*<BR>*   *</P>
<A NAME="Sec6"></A><P>NEWCASTLE DISEASE IN THE UNITED KINGDOM / GREAT BRITAIN</P>
</CENTER>
<P></STRONG>
See also <A HREF="A10_05.HTM#Sec1"> 31 January 1997; Vol. 10 - No. 5</A>, <A HREF="A10_03.HTM#Sec1"> 17 January 1997; Vol. 10 - No. 3</A>, <A HREF="A10_02.HTM#Sec2"> 10 January 1997; Vol. 10 - No. 2</A>, <A HREF="A09_19.HTM#Sec3"> 24 May 1996; Vol. 9 - No. 19</A><P><EM>
